1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 {This is the start of the Petroff defense, and in this database, I will provide a repertoire for Black with this variation. The main moves 3.d4 and 3.Nxe5 will be the focus of this database since for the sidelines like 3.Nc3 or 3.d3, Black replies with 3...Nc6 where I have already made a course on the Spanish where I cover them.} 3. d4 Nxe4 4. dxe5 {This interesting move became popular in the past few years, although it leads to more or less a forced draw if Black plays accurately. The move 4.Bd3 will be analyzed in the upcoming lessons.} (4. Qe2 d5 5. Nbd2 (5. Nxe5 Be7 $132 {[%cal Ge8g8] The queen seems a bit awkward on e2.}) 5... exd4 {The simple solution where after all the exchanges, Black doesn't have any problems in the position.} (5... Nc6 $5 {A possible try to play for a win as it leads to more complicated positions.} 6. Nxe4 dxe4 7. Qxe4 f5 8. Qe3 e4 9. Bb5 Qd6 {Protecting the knight.} 10. O-O Be7 11. Ne5 O-O 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Qc3 Bf6 {This is a very interesting suggestion by the engine.} 14. Bf4 c5 {Black sacrifices an exchange but will gain nice compensation in return.} 15. Ng6 cxd4 16. Qg3 Qe6 17. Nxf8 Kxf8 $44 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] Intending Ba6 next, while for White it's probably a good idea to go for a repetition with 18.Bg5 Be5 19.Bf4.}) 6. Nxe4 dxe4 7. Qxe4+ Be7 8. Bd2 (8. Qxd4 O-O $11) 8... O-O 9. O-O-O Nc6 10. Bc4 {White has a slight initiative but Black is a pawn up.} g6 {Avoiding any Ng5 ideas in the future and preparing Bf6 or Bf5.} 11. Bh6 (11. g4 Bf6 12. Rhe1 Bg7 $132 {[%cal Gc8d7] The position is double-edged but I prefer Black since White needs to prove the compensation.}) 11... Bf5 12. Qf4 Bd6 13. Qd2 Bb4 {White can't escape with the queen as Qe2 would run into Re8.} 14. Qf4 Bd6 $11) (4. Nxe5 d6 (4... d5 5. Bd3 {Transposes to next lessons.}) 5. Nf3 d5 {Transposes to the upcoming lessons.}) 4... Bc5 $5 {This is a very forced line as you will see in the analysis below.} ({A possible try to keep more play in the position, potentially to play for a win is:} 4... d5 5. Nbd2 Qd7 {This is a popular alternative where Black puts the queen on d7 with the point that it's now protected by a minor piece.}) 5. Bc4 $1 {White's alternatives seem a bit dubious.} ({Slightly risky for White is:} 5. Qd5 Bxf2+ 6. Ke2 {It's better for the king to stay close and keep an eye on the bishop on f2.} (6. Kd1 $6 f5 {Black is already gaining the upper hand.} 7. Bc4 (7. Nbd2 c6 8. Qd3 Qe7 9. Nxe4 fxe4 10. Qxe4 d5 11. Qf4 Nd7 $17) 7... Qe7 8. Nc3 (8. Nbd2 c6 9. Qd3 b5 $1 10. Bb3 Bb6 11. Rf1 Na6 $17 {[%cal Ga6c5] Black can also win the exchange with Nf2 but developing like this is also good.}) 8... c6 9. Qd3 b5 $1 10. Bb3 a5 11. a4 b4 12. Nxe4 fxe4 13. Qxe4 d5 14. Qe2 Bc5 $17 {White's king is stuck in the center and the bishop on b3 is also blocked, so Black enjoys a nice advantage.}) 6... f5 7. Nbd2 (7. exf6 Nxf6 8. Qe5+ Kf8 $17 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gf6g4]}) (7. Nc3 c6 8. Nxe4 {Transposes.} (8. Qd3 Qe7 $1 {[%cal Gd7d5]})) 7... c6 8. Nxe4 {Transposes.} cxd5 9. Nd6+ Kf8 10. Kxf2 {White has two pieces for a queen, but with Black being behind in development, the position is double-edged although Black is not worse.} Nc6 11. Be3 Qc7 $5 $146 {[%cal Gc6e5] The easiest move, threatening the e5-pawn.} (11... d4 12. Bf4 h6 {This move is more accurate according to the computer.} (12... b5 13. Bd3 Qb6 {½- (60) ½ (60) Karthikeyan,M (2610)-Paravyan,D (2612) Chess.com INT 2024} 14. Rhe1 $44) 13. h4 b5 {Now the same line with ...h6 and h4 included gives Black control over the g5-square.} 14. Bd3 Qb6 15. h5 Bb7 16. Nh4 Ne7 17. Rae1 Bd5 18. Rhf1 Kg8 19. Kg1 $44) 12. Nb5 (12. Bc5 $6 Kg8 13. Rd1 b6 14. Nb5 (14. Ba3 b5 $1 {[%cal Gc7b6]} 15. Bxb5 Qb6+ 16. Kg3 Ba6 $19 {Black's pieces are getting active.}) 14... Qd8 15. Bd6 Ba6 $17) 12... Qa5 {The position remains balanced but it's a bit more tricky for White to navigate the position as he is a queen down, so he needs to fight for a draw.} 13. Rd1 (13. Bd3 d6 {[%cal Gc8d7]} 14. exd6 (14. Nxd6 $6 Kg8 {The bishop can go to e6 next.}) 14... Bd7 15. Nc7 g5 $1 {The most accurate move according to the engines.} 16. Nxg5 (16. Nxa8 $6 f4 {This is Black's idea.} 17. Bd2 Qc5+ 18. Ke2 Qxd6 $17 {[%csl Ra8]}) 16... Qb4 17. Rhf1 Qxd6 18. Nxa8 Kg7 $15) 13... h6 (13... d4 $5 14. Bf4 Qb6 {Is also interesting, although it's better to include 13...h6.}) 14. a3 (14. Rxd5 $6 Qxa2 {Is Black's point.}) 14... d4 15. Bd2 Qb6 16. Bd3 d6 $1 (16... d5 {Is the same thing.}) 17. exd6 (17. Nxd6 $6 Be6 $17) 17... Bd7 18. Nc7 (18. Rhe1 Rc8 {Is similar.}) 18... Rc8 19. Rhe1 {We need to return some material, otherwise it will be difficult to develop.} Rxc7 20. dxc7 Qxc7 21. b4 a6 {Black is up in material but White has compensation thanks to the vulnerable king on f8.} 22. a4 (22. c4 $6 dxc3 23. Bxc3 Rh7 {[%cal Gg7g5] With g6 or g5 next and then Re7, when Black is already taking over.}) 22... a5 23. b5 Nb4 24. Ne5 Be8 25. Bxf5 g6 $1 26. Nxg6+ Bxg6 27. Bxb4+ axb4 28. Bxg6 Rg8 {This move poses White more problems.} (28... Kg7 29. Bd3 Qxh2 30. Re7+ Kf8 31. Re2 $11) 29. Re8+ Kg7 30. Rxg8+ Kxg8 31. Rb1 $1 {White needs to find this only move, giving the king a bit more space to maneuver.} Qf4+ 32. Kg1 Qe3+ 33. Kf1 $11) (5. Be3 $6 Bxe3 6. fxe3 Nc6 7. Qd5 Ng5 $132 {With the doubled e-pawns and Qe7 or d6 on the agenda, only Black can be better.}) 5... Nxf2 (5... Bxf2+ $2 6. Kf1 $18 {White is threatening Qd5.}) 6. Bxf7+ $1 (6. Qd5 $6 Qe7 7. b4 Bb6 8. Rf1 Ng4 9. h3 (9. Qe4 d5 $1 10. Bxd5 f5 $1 {And Black already gains the upper hand.} 11. exf6 (11. Qe2 Qxb4+ 12. c3 Qc5 13. Bb3 Nc6 $17) 11... Qxe4+ 12. Bxe4 Nxf6 13. Bd3 Nc6 $17) 9... Nf6 10. Qxf7+ Qxf7 11. Bxf7+ Kxf7 12. exf6 gxf6 $15 {White has some small compensation but it's insufficient.}) (6. Qe2 $2 Nxh1 7. Ng5 Rf8 $19 {White doesn't have nearly enough compensation for the rook.}) 6... Kxf7 {Black needs to accept the challenge.} (6... Kf8 $2 7. Qd5 Nxh1 8. Bh5 Qe7 9. Bg5 Bf2+ 10. Ke2 Qe6 11. Nc3 $16 {White can regain some material back and his pieces are quite active while Black is way underdeveloped,}) 7. Qd5+ Kg6 (7... Ke8 $2 8. Bg5 Be7 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Kxf2 $16 {White restores material equality with a better position.}) 8. Qxc5 (8. Rf1 d6 9. b4 Bb6 10. a4 c6 11. Qb3 a5 $1 12. Bg5 Qe8 13. bxa5 Ba7 14. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 15. Kxf2 h6 16. Qd3+ Kf7 17. Nbd2 d5 18. Be3 Nd7 $132 {Probably the engine can hold this with White, there is compensation, but practically Black can already be preferred.}) (8. O-O d6 $1 9. b4 Bb6 {Transposes.} (9... Nh3+ {This is also a possibility although after} 10. Kh1 Nf2+ {White can go for the repetition but can also choose to play on with} 11. Rxf2 Bxf2 12. g3 $13 {[%cal Gf3h4] When the position remains unclear.}) 10. Nc3 (10. Rxf2 $6 Bxf2+ 11. Kxf2 h6 12. Qe4+ Kf7 $15) 10... Rf8 (10... c6 11. Qb3 Rf8 {Is similar.}) 11. Na4 c6 12. Qb3 Ng4+ 13. Nxb6 Qxb6+ 14. Kh1 Nf2+ 15. Kg1 Nh3+ $11) (8. Nc3 $2 d6 $17 {The light-squared bishop can now join the game.}) (8. h4 $2 h6 $19 {Black's king can hide on h7.}) (8. Bg5 Qe8 {More ambitious in comparison to 8...Qf8.} (8... Qf8 {This is also possible.} 9. Rf1 d6 10. Bh4 Ng4 11. Bg3 Ne3 (11... Kh6 $5 {An alternative suggested by the engines, although it's slightly more complicated than 11...Ne3.}) 12. Qe4+ Kh5 13. Qh4+ Kg6 $11) 9. Bh4 (9. Qxc5 Nxh1 10. Nc3 h6 11. Nd5 d6 {Prevents Ne7+.} 12. Qe3 Kh7 $1 13. Bxh6 Rf8 {Black also needs to be a bit accurate but it's White who is trying to keep the balance.} 14. Bg5 Qa4 15. e6 Qa5+ 16. Nc3 Rxf3 17. gxf3 Bxe6 18. Qxe6 Qxg5 19. Qh3+ Qh6 20. Qf5+ {This was an interesting line suggested by the engines, while now Black can go for a repetition, although Black can also try to play on for a bit since White is down a piece and needs to be accurate.} g6 21. Qf7+ Qg7 22. Qe8 $11) (9. Nh4+ $2 Kxg5 10. Nd2 {1/2-1/2 (14) Short,N (2696)-Smeets,J (2657) Wijk aan Zee 2010} (10. Qxc5 Rf8 $1 11. Nd2 Kxh4 12. O-O d6 13. exd6 cxd6 14. Qd4+ Bg4 $19 {Black is up too much material.}) 10... d6 $1 11. Ndf3+ Kg4 $1 12. h3+ (12. Qd2 Ne4 {Is also fine for Black.}) 12... Kg3 13. Qd2 Qh5 $19 {Black's king is actually quite safe on g3. Surprisingly, it may seem like we are attacking with the king.}) (9. O-O $6 Na6 10. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 11. Kxf2 Qf7 12. Qd3+ Qf5 $15) 9... Qe6 10. Qxe6+ (10. Qxc5 $6 Nxh1 11. Nc3 h6 12. O-O-O Kh7 13. Nd5 d6 14. Qxc7 Bd7 $17) 10... dxe6 11. Bxf2 Bb4+ 12. Nbd2 (12. c3 Be7) 12... Nc6 13. O-O-O b6 14. Ne4 Rf8 $132) (8. b4 Bb6 9. O-O d6 {Transposes.}) 8... Nxh1 9. Nc3 (9. Qd4 d5 {This is a good move that will lead to a draw very soon, although Black also has some alternatives:} (9... Nc6) (9... h6) 10. e6 $1 h6 11. Qg4+ (11. Qd3+ $2 Kf6 12. Be3 Bxe6 13. Nc3 Nc6 14. O-O-O Kf7 15. Rf1 Kg8 16. Rxh1 Qd7 $19) 11... Kh7 12. Qf5+ {White should take the repetition.} (12. Bxh6 $2 Qe7 13. Be3 Re8 $19) 12... Kg8 13. Qf7+ Kh7 14. Qf5+ $11) (9. Qd5 h6 (9... Nc6 {Is also fine.}) 10. Nc3 (10. Qd3+ $6 Kf7 11. Qd5+ Kf8 {Black's king is safer now.}) (10. Be3 d6 11. e6 Qe8 12. Qe4+ Kf6 13. Bd4+ Ke7 14. Nc3 Bxe6 15. Bxg7 Nc6 16. Bxh8 Qxh8 17. O-O-O Nf2 18. Qh4+ Kd7 19. Qxf2 Qg7 $132) 10... d6 11. e6 Nf2 $1 {A nice in-between move.} 12. Kxf2 Qf6 13. Kg1 Qxe6 14. Qd3+ Kf7 15. Bd2 (15. Nd5 Qf5 16. Nxc7 Qxd3 {The endgame is fine for Black.} (16... Qc5+ {This leads to a draw by perpetual checks.} 17. Be3 Qxc7 18. Ng5+ hxg5 19. Rf1+ Kg8 20. Qd5+ Kh7 21. Qe4+ g6 22. Bxg5 Bf5 23. Rxf5 gxf5 24. Qxf5+ Kg8 25. Qg6+ Qg7 26. Qe8+ $11) 17. cxd3 Bg4 18. Nxa8 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Na6 20. Be3 Rxa8 21. Rc1 b6 22. Rc4 $11) 15... Nc6 16. Nd5 Qf5 17. Ng5+ Kg8 18. Qc4 Be6 19. Nxe6 Qxe6 20. Ne7+ Kf7 21. Nd5 $11) (9. Bg5 $6 Qf8 10. Qe3 h6 11. Qe4+ Kf7 12. Nc3 Kg8 {Black's king managed to escape the danger.} 13. Nd5 Nc6 14. Bh4 d6 15. e6 Bxe6 16. Qxe6+ Qf7 17. Qxf7+ Kxf7 18. Nxc7 Raf8 $15 {The knight on h1 is stuck but it's not easy to capture at all, especially since Black intends to go g5 next.}) 9... Nc6 {The simplest continuation.} (9... h6 $5 {Is another good option although it's more complicated.}) 10. Qc4 (10. Qd5 h6 11. Be3 Kh7 12. Qe4+ Kg8 13. Qd5+ $11) (10. Nd5 d6 11. Qc4 Nxe5 12. Nf4+ Kf6 13. Nh5+ (13. Nd5+ $6 Kf7 {Black is fine.}) 13... Kg6 14. Nf4+ $11) (10. Qe3 h6 11. Nd5 Kf7 12. Qf4+ (12. Qb3 $6 d6 13. Nxc7+ Kg6 14. Nxa8 dxe5 $15) 12... Kg8 13. Qc4 Kf8 14. Qf4+ $11) 10... h6 {An accurate move.} 11. Nd5 (11. Nh4+ Kh7 12. Qe4+ Kg8 13. Qd5+ Kh7 $11) (11. Be3 Kh7 12. Nd5 (12. Qe4+ Kg8 (12... g6 $2 13. Nd5 $18) 13. O-O-O (13. Nd5 d6 {Black is fine.}) 13... d6 14. Qc4+ Kh7 $11) 12... Rf8 13. Qe4+ Kh8 14. Bxh6 {This seems like an interesting line but only White can be worse.} Qe8 $1 15. Qh4 (15. Nxc7 $6 Qh5 {Black is already to be preferred.}) 15... Qg6 16. Be3+ Kg8 17. Qc4 Rf7 18. Ng5 (18. O-O-O d6 {Black is fine.}) 18... d6 19. Nxc7 Nxe5 20. Qb3 Rb8 21. Nxf7 (21. O-O-O Bf5 {The position remains complex.}) 21... Nxf7 22. Bxa7 (22. O-O-O Bf5 {Black simply finishes the development and goes for activity.}) 22... Qe4+ 23. Qe3 Qxg2 24. O-O-O Bf5 25. Rd2 Qf1+ 26. Rd1 Qc4 27. Qc3 $1 Qxc3 28. bxc3 Rc8 29. Nd5 $11) (11. Bd2 d6 12. Nh4+ Kh7 13. Qe4+ Kg8 14. Qd5+ Kh7 $11) 11... d6 12. e6 {This is a way for White to continue the game.} (12. Be3 $6 dxe5 13. O-O-O Kh7 14. Qe4+ Kg8 15. Nb6 Nd4 16. Nxd4 axb6 17. Nc6 Qxd1+ 18. Kxd1 bxc6 19. Qxc6 Kf7 20. Qxc7+ Kf6 21. Bxb6 Be6 $15 {Black has a bunch of pieces for the queen.}) (12. Nf4+ Kh7 13. Qe4+ Kg8 $11) 12... Kh7 13. Qe4+ Kg8 14. e7 (14. Qg4 b5 $5 {If Black wants to keep the game going, this is an interesting possibility to continue.} (14... Ne5 {Leads to a perpetual.} 15. Nxe5 dxe5 16. Qg6 Qxd5 17. Qf7+ Kh7 18. Qf5+ $11) 15. Be3 Qf8 16. O-O-O Ne7 17. Nxc7 Rb8 $132 {White is still material down so he needs to play accurately.}) (14. Be3 $2 Ne7 $19) 14... Qe8 15. Be3 (15. Nxc7 Bf5 $1 16. Qc4+ Qf7 17. Nxa8 Qxc4 18. e8=Q+ {Also leads to a perpetual check.} Kh7 19. Ng5+ hxg5 20. Qh5+ Kg8 21. Qe8+ $11) 15... Bd7 16. Nxc7 (16. O-O-O $2 Rc8 17. Rf1 Qh5 $17) 16... Qxe7 17. Qxe7 Nxe7 18. Nxa8 Kf7 19. Nc7 {White still keeps some tension on the board, otherwise Black would have easy equality with any other alternatives:} (19. O-O-O Nf5 20. Bd4 Rxa8 21. Rxh1 g5 $11) (19. Nb6 axb6 20. Kd2 Ng3 21. hxg3 Nf5 22. Bf2 Ra8 $11) 19... Rc8 20. Bxa7 (20. Kd2 Rxc7 21. Rxh1 a6 $11) 20... Rxc7 21. O-O-O (21. Kd2 Bf5 {It's important to attack the c2-pawn.} ({An alternative is:} 21... Rc4 $5 22. Rxh1 Ra4 23. Bb8 (23. Bd4 Rxa2 {This is Black's idea of Rc4.}) 23... Bc6 (23... Nc8 $5) 24. Bxd6 Bxf3 25. Bxe7 Bxg2 26. Rg1 Bd5 27. Bc5 Rxa2 28. Ba3 g5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (49) Abdusattorov,N (2734)-Duda,J (2729) Dusseldorf 2023}) 22. Nd4 (22. c3 $2 b6 $1 {With the point that after 23.Bxb6 Rb7, the b2-pawn falls.}) (22. Rc1 Be4 23. Bb6 Rc6 24. Be3 Nf5 (24... Ng6 $5) 25. c3 Ra6 26. a3 Nhg3 27. hxg3 Nxg3 $11) 22... Nf2 $1 23. Nxf5 Ne4+ 24. Ke3 Nxf5+ 25. Kxe4 Rxc2 26. Rf1 (26. Kxf5 $2 Rc4 $1 $19 {An interesting mating net, now g6 is unavoidable.}) 26... g6 27. Rf2 (27. g4 Rc4+ 28. Kf3 Ne7 29. b3 Rb4 30. Be3 h5 $11) 27... Rc4+ 28. Kd3 Ra4 29. Be3 Ke6 $11) 21... Bf5 $1 {Black should put pressure on the c2-pawn.} 22. Nd4 (22. c3 Nc6 $1 23. Bb6 (23. Be3 Nb4 {This is the point of Nc6.} 24. Rf1 (24. Kd2 Nd3 {Is similar.}) 24... Nd3+ 25. Kd2 Nxb2 26. Nd4 Nc4+ 27. Ke2 Nxe3 28. Kxe3 Rxc3+ 29. Ke2 g6 30. g4 Rh3 31. gxf5 Rxh2+ 32. Kf3 gxf5 33. Nxf5 Ke6 34. Nd4+ Ke5 35. Nb5 $11 {Only Black can play for a win but the game is very likely to end in a draw.}) (23. Bd4 Re7 {[%cal Ge7e2]} 24. Kd2 Be6 $1 {It's also important to put pressure on White's queenside pawns.} 25. Rxh1 (25. b3 Re8 26. c4 (26. Rxh1 Ra8 $11 {With the point that 27.Ra3 runs into 27...Bxb3.}) 26... d5 $11) (25. a3 $2 Bc4 $17) 25... Bxa2 $11) (23. Rf1 Nxa7 24. Nd4 g6 25. g4 Nc6 $11) 23... Re7 24. Kd2 (24. Rxh1 Re2 $11) (24. Nh4 Bh7 25. Rxh1 Re2 26. Rf1+ Ke6 27. Rf2 Re1+ 28. Kd2 Rb1 29. b3 Ne5 $11 {Black is a pawn down but has very good compensation thanks to the active pieces.}) 24... Be6 25. b3 (25. a3 Bc4 {Threatening Re2.}) (25. Rxh1 Bxa2 $11) 25... Re8 $1 26. Kc1 (26. Rxh1 $6 Ra8 {We can see the same idea with Re8-Ra8 again.}) (26. Kc2 Bg4 {Is also fine for Black.}) 26... Bg4 27. Rxh1 Re2 28. Rf1 Rxa2 29. Kb1 Ra6 30. Ne5+ Ke6 $11) 22... Nf2 $1 23. Rf1 Nd3+ 24. Kb1 Nxb2 25. Kxb2 (25. Nxf5 Nxf5 26. Rxf5+ Ke6 $11) 25... Kg6 {The positions seem balanced as both sides have four pawns each, there are also opposite-colored bishops on the board, so the game is very likely to end in a draw.} 26. Bb6 (26. Nxf5 Nxf5 27. a4 (27. g4 Ne7 28. Rd1 Nc6 $5 (28... d5 $11) 29. Rxd6+ {Black's pieces are quite active so the endgame is balanced.} (29. Bb6 Rd7 {Black is fine.}) 29... Kg5 30. Bb6 Rf7 31. a4 Kxg4 32. a5 (32. Kb3 h5 {Black also has some pawns to push.}) 32... Rf5 $11) (27. Rf4 h5 $11) 27... h5 28. a5 Kf6 29. Kb3 Ke6 30. Rf4 Ne7 $11) (26. Bb8 Rc4 27. Nxf5 (27. c3 Be4 28. Rf4 (28. Bxd6 Nd5 $11) 28... d5 29. Be5 Nc6 30. Nxc6 Rxc6 $11) 27... Nxf5 28. Rd1 (28. Rf3 Nd4 29. Rf2 d5 $11) (28. Kb3 d5) 28... Rc8 (28... h5 $5 29. Bxd6 Ne3) 29. Ba7 h5 $11) (26. Rd1 Be4 $11) 26... Rc4 27. Kb3 (27. c3 Bd7 $11) 27... d5 28. Nxf5 (28. Re1 Nc6 29. c3 Bd7 $11) 28... Nxf5 29. Rd1 Rg4 (29... Ne7 {This is also possible, although 29...Rg4 is more accurate.}) 30. Rxd5 (30. g3 d4 $11) (30. Rd2 Kf6 $11) 30... Rxg2 31. Rd7 Rxh2 32. a4 (32. Rxb7 h5 {Is similar.}) 32... h5 33. a5 h4 34. Rxb7 h3 {There is a race going on where Black has sufficient counterplay so the game remains balanced.} 35. a6 (35. Rd7 Rh1 36. Rd2 Kh5 37. Bc7 g5 38. Kb2 Re1 39. a6 Re6 40. Rd5 Ne3 41. Rd3 Nc4+ 42. Kc3 Rxa6 43. Rxh3+ Kg6 $11) 35... Rh1 36. Bc7 (36. a7 h2 (36... Ra1 $6 37. Bg1 $1 {The h-pawn's advance has been prevented.}) (36... Rb1+ 37. Ka2 h2 {Leads to the same thing.}) 37. a8=Q Rb1+ 38. Ka2 h1=Q 39. Qe8+ Kh7 40. Qe5 Ra1+ 41. Qxa1 Qd5+ 42. Kb2 Qxb7 $11) 36... Ra1 $1 37. Rb6+ (37. a7 Rb1+ 38. Ka3 Rxb7 39. a8=Q Rxc7 $11 {The h-pawn is quite strong.}) 37... Kh5 38. Kb2 (38. Kb4 g5 39. c4 Ne3 40. Be5 Ra2 41. Kb3 Nxc4 42. Kxc4 h2 $11) 38... Ra4 39. Kb3 Ra1 $11 {Overall, in this line with 4...Bc5 Black needs to remember some theory, although the variation is a bit limited since it leads to equality quite quickly.} *

