1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4 Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 {Sometimes Black also plays 4...Nc6 but we will focus on the main move 4...d5.} 5. dxe5 {White uses this line occasionally as a surprise weapon, albeit Black is quite solid in this line.} Be7 6. O-O (6. Nbd2 Nc5 {Most often we want to step away with the knight as exchanging it will help White.} 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Ne6 $132 {[%cal Ge6f4] Intending Nf4 and Black has ideas like c5 with Nc6 later on.} (8... a5 $5 {This is an interesting suggestion by the computer, although 8...Ne6 seems a bit more natural.} 9. c3 a4 10. Nd4 Nc6 $132)) (6. Be3 O-O (6... Nc5 {Is similar.}) 7. O-O (7. Nbd2 Bf5 $11) 7... Nc5 8. Bxc5 (8. Nc3 c6 $11 {Intending Nxd3 at some point and continuing the development with Nd7.}) (8. Be2 {Transposes to the main lines.}) 8... Bxc5 9. Nbd2 Qe7 10. Re1 Bb6 $11 {With a playable position where Black can continue with moves like c5 and Be6.}) (6. Nc3 Nxc3 7. bxc3 c5 8. O-O Nc6 $132 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc8e6]}) (6. c3 {[%cal Gd3c2] White's idea is to retreat the bishop on c2 after Nc5.} Nc5 (6... Nc6 {Is also good.}) 7. Bc2 Bg4 $1 8. O-O (8. h3 Bh5 9. O-O Nc6 $132) 8... Nc6 9. b4 Ne6 10. Re1 a6 $132 {[%cal Gd8d7,Gd5d4] The position resembles a type of an Open Spanish that is pleasant for Black.}) 6... Nc5 $1 {Going after White's light-squared bishop straight away.} ({A bit worse is:} 6... O-O 7. c4 Nc6 8. Bc2 {[%cal Gc4d5,Gc2e4] Black needs to deal with a slightly unpleasant tension in the center.}) 7. Be2 (7. Be3 Nxd3 8. cxd3 (8. Qxd3 $6 c5 $15 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gc8e6]}) 8... Nc6 9. d4 Bg4 10. Nc3 Qd7 $132 {The bishop can always retreat to h5 if needed.}) (7. Nc3 Nxd3 (7... c6 {Is also fine.}) 8. Qxd3 c6 {The position is around equal although Black has a good potential thanks to the bishop pair and nice pawn structure.} 9. Nd4 (9. Ne2 O-O 10. h3 Nd7 $11 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gf8e8]}) 9... O-O 10. Bf4 (10. f4 f6 $5 {Other moves might be also possible but this prevents White's f5 pawn push.} 11. e6 f5 $1 12. Re1 (12. Nxf5 Bc5+ {[%cal Gc8e6]}) 12... Na6 {[%cal Ga6c5]} 13. Nxf5 Nc5 14. Nxe7+ Qxe7 15. Qg3 Nxe6 $132 {Black will play Qf6, pressuring the f4-pawn and can try to start taking over.}) (10. Re1 Re8 {Is similar.}) 10... Re8 11. Rfe1 Na6 $11 {[%cal Ga6c5] The knight will go to c5 next while the position is approximately balanced. Black has nice chances in the upcoming battle of the middlegame thanks to the bishop pair.}) 7... O-O 8. Be3 {The idea is to play Nbd2 and c4, or c4 first and then Nc3, while White's alternatives don't put much pressure on Black. Transposes to the main lines.} (8. c3 Nc6 (8... Re8 {Is also good.}) 9. Be3 (9. Re1 Re8 $11) (9. Na3 Re8 {Is another possibility.}) 9... Nd7 {This leads to immediate equality.} (9... Re8 $11) 10. Qxd5 Ndxe5 $11) (8. Nc3 c6 9. Nd4 f6 (9... Qc7 10. f4 f6 {This alternative is also fine for Black.}) 10. exf6 Bxf6 11. Be3 Ne6 $11 {Thanks to the central pawn structure, Black can already be slightly preferred.}) (8. Re1 c6 9. Nd4 (9. Nbd2 Nbd7 {[%cal Gf7f6]} 10. Nb3 f6 $5 {The typical idea for Black, challenging White's e-pawn and opening up the f-file.} 11. exf6 Nxf6 $11) 9... Nbd7 (9... a5 $5 10. Nd2 a4 {Is also possible.}) 10. Bf1 Re8 11. Nd2 Nf8 $11) (8. c4 dxc4 9. Bxc4 Be6 $11) (8. Nd4 f6 {Once again, we can see this typical pawn push.} (8... Nc6 $5) 9. exf6 Bxf6 $11) 8... c6 {Solidifying the center and preparing Nbd7.} 9. c4 (9. c3 Nbd7 (9... Qc7 $5) 10. Nbd2 Ne6 11. Qc2 Qc7 12. c4 Nxe5 {This will exchange some pawns and will lead to equality.} (12... Nb6 $11) 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Qxc7 Nxf3+ 15. Bxf3 Nxc7 16. Rac1 Ne6 17. Bxd5 Rd8 $11) (9. Nbd2 Ne6 $1 {Black can already be preferred in this position thanks to the following plan:} 10. Nb3 c5 11. c3 Nc6 12. Qd2 b6 13. Rad1 {0-1 (42) Gurel,E (2500)-Ivic,V (2590) Baku 2023} Nc7 $132 {[%cal Gc8f5] The most accurate move, keeping White's pieces restricted and intending to develop the bishop to f5.}) (9. Re1 Nbd7 10. Nbd2 {1/2-1/2 (42) Kryvoruchko,Y (2683)-Dardha,D (2540) Germany 2022} Ne6 $1 11. c4 Nb6 $11) (9. Nd4 Na4 $5 (9... Qc7 {Is also possible.}) 10. b3 Nb6 $132 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc6c5] An interesting knight maneuver suggested by the computer. The point is that Black is about to push c5 and maybe even d4 next.}) 9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 (10. Bxc5 Bxc5 11. Bxc4 Bf5 $146 {The computer suggests that this is the most accurate continuation for Black.} (11... Qe7 {Is another possibility.}) 12. Qxd8 (12. Qc1 {[%cal Gc1f4]} Nd7 13. Qf4 Bg6 14. Nc3 Qc7 15. Ne4 Rad8 $11) (12. Nc3 Nd7 {Black equalizes by playing simple moves.} 13. Re1 Nb6 ({An alternative is:} 13... Qe7 14. Nd4 Bxd4 15. Qxd4 Nc5 $11 {With Rad8 next.}) 14. Bb3 Qxd1 15. Raxd1 h6 $11 {Intending Rfd8 is next.}) 12... Rxd8 13. Ng5 Kf8 $1 {13...Bg6 runs into 14.e6.} 14. Nc3 (14. Nxf7 $6 Rd4 15. Bb3 a5 $15) 14... h6 15. Nxf7 Rd4 16. Bb3 a5 $1 17. Rfd1 (17. a3 Na6 $132) 17... a4 $1 18. Rxd4 Bxd4 {The complications will liquidate into a drawn position.} 19. Nxa4 Rxa4 20. Nd6 Bxb2 21. Rd1 (21. Re1 Ra5 {The e5-pawn is in trouble.}) 21... Rd4 22. Nxf5 Rxd1+ 23. Bxd1 Bxe5 $11) (10. Qxd8 $6 Rxd8 11. Bxc4 Nbd7 $15 {Black will gain a tempo on the bishop with Nb6.}) 10... Qxd1 (10... Nbd7 {Keeping the queens on the board is also an option.}) 11. Rxd1 Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7b6]} 12. b4 (12. Nc3 Nb6 $11) (12. Rc1 {Preventing Nb6 due to Bxf7+ when the knight on c5 falls.} Rd8 13. Nbd2 b5 14. Be2 Bb7 $11) 12... Ne6 13. a3 (13. b5 Nb6 $132) 13... Nb6 14. Bb3 Nc7 {[%cal Gc8e6] Intending Be6 or Nbd5.} 15. Nc3 (15. Nbd2 Nbd5 $11) 15... Be6 16. Nd4 Bxb3 17. Nxb3 Nc4 {White might have been threatening Na5 so it's best to deal with this idea energetically.} 18. Na5 (18. Rd7 Bd8 {[%cal Gc4e5]} 19. Bd4 Re8 20. g3 Re7 21. Rxe7 Bxe7 $11) 18... Nxe3 19. fxe3 Bg5 20. Rd3 Rfe8 (20... Rae8 21. Ne4 Bh6 $11 {Is similar.}) 21. Ne4 (21. Nxb7 Rxe5 $11) 21... Rad8 22. Rxd8 Bxe3+ 23. Kf1 Rxd8 24. Nd6 {White's knights are quite active so White will restore material equality.} (24. Re1 Bb6 $11) 24... Ne6 (24... Rd7 25. Naxb7 Bd4 26. Re1 Kf8 $11) 25. Naxb7 Rd7 26. Re1 Bd4 $11 {½- (31) ½ (31) Engelhard,C (2336)-Korn,C (2147) ICCF email 2020 The position is quite drawish as there is reduced material remaining on the board, while Black can also consider pushing c6-c5 at some point.} *

