1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4 Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. Nxe5 Nd7 {The most accurate move. The old main line of 6.Nxd7 and the most popular and critical line 6.Nc3 will be analyzed in the upcoming lessons.} 6. O-O (6. Nxf7 {This is essentially a draw offer.} Kxf7 {Maybe Black can try for a win with 6...Qh4 but the position is unclear and it seems like Black doesn't equalize completely in that line.} 7. Qh5+ Ke7 (7... Ke6 8. Qg4+ Kf7 $11) 8. Qe2 Kf7 $11) (6. Qe2 Nxe5 7. Bxe4 (7. dxe5 $6 Nc5 {[%cal Gc5d3]} 8. O-O Be7 $132 {[%cal Ge8g8] Black will capture the bishop on d3 sooner or later and will enjoy the bishop pair advantage.}) 7... dxe4 8. Qxe4 Be6 {White manages to win a pawn but Black has great compensation for it.} 9. Qxe5 (9. dxe5 $6 Bd5 10. Qg4 h5 11. Qh3 Qe7 12. O-O Qxe5 $15 {[%csl Gd5,Gf8] Thanks to the bishop pair, Black has a very pleasant position. A possible idea after Nc3 is to play Be6 and to castle long.}) 9... Qd7 {[%cal Ge8c8]} 10. O-O (10. Nc3 $6 O-O-O 11. Be3 $6 Bb4 $15 {[%cal Gf7f6]}) (10. Be3 Bb4+ (10... Bd6 $5 11. Qxg7 O-O-O {Is also an interesting continuation.}) 11. Nd2 O-O-O 12. c3 f6 ({An alternative is:} 12... Bd6 13. Qa5 Rhe8 $44) 13. Qe4 Bf5 14. Qf3 Bg4 $11 {White should go for the repetition as 14.Qg3 runs into 14...Bd6.}) 10... O-O-O 11. Be3 Bb4 $5 {Taking control over the a5-square and provoking c3.} (11... Bd6 12. Qa5 Bd5 {Black's bishops are quite well pointed toward White's king.} 13. h3 b6 $1 (13... Kb8 $6 14. Nc3 {Threatening the bishop on d5 and intending Nb5.}) 14. Qxa7 Qc6 15. c4 $1 Bxc4 (15... Bxg2 {Leads to some complications after:} 16. Qa6+ Kb8 17. d5 Qe8 $13) 16. Rc1 Kd7 17. d5 Qxd5 18. Qa4+ (18. Nc3 Qc6 19. Na4 Ke6 $1 {The king tries to run to safety on the kingside, but now the position is about to be simplified:} 20. Nxb6 cxb6 21. b3 Ra8 22. Rxc4 Bc5 23. Rxc5 bxc5 24. Qxc5 Qxc5 25. Bxc5 Rhb8 $11) 18... b5 (18... Bb5 {This is also playable.} 19. Qg4+ Qe6 20. Qf3 Qf6 21. Qxf6 gxf6 22. Nd2 $11) 19. Qc2 Qe5 20. g3 Qh5 21. Nc3 Qxh3 22. b3 Bxg3 23. fxg3 Qxg3+ 24. Kh1 Qxe3 25. bxc4 Rhe8 $44) 12. a3 (12. c3 $6 Bd6 {[%cal Rb1c3] White can't develop the knight to c3 anymore.}) 12... f6 13. Qe4 Bf5 14. Qf3 Bg4 15. Qe4 Bf5 $11) (6. Nd2 Nxe5 7. dxe5 Nc5 {Black avoids the exchange of the knights and targets White's light-squared bishop.} 8. Be2 (8. O-O Nxd3 9. cxd3 Be7 $132) 8... c6 (8... Be7 {Is also good.}) 9. O-O (9. Nb3 Qc7 $5 {[%cal Gc7e5] Putting pressure on White's e5-pawn right away.} 10. f4 (10. O-O Qxe5 11. Re1 Be6 12. Bg4 Qf6 13. Be3 Nxb3 14. axb3 Bd6 15. Bd4 Qh6 16. Bxe6 fxe6 17. Qg4 Kd7 18. Be5 {The position remains complex when White has some compensation for the pawn but Black isn't worse.} (18. Qxg7+ Qxg7 19. Bxg7 Rhg8 20. Be5 Rg5 21. f4 Rf5 $11)) 10... Nxb3 11. axb3 Bc5 {Preventing 0-0.} 12. Bd3 Qe7 13. Qh5 (13. Qe2 O-O 14. Be3 Bxe3 15. Qxe3 f6 {A typical move to diminish the strength of White's center.} 16. O-O fxe5 17. fxe5 Rxf1+ 18. Rxf1 Be6 $11 {Black can consider bringing the rook in the game or to continue with b6.}) 13... g6 14. Qh6 Be6 15. Bd2 O-O-O 16. O-O-O Qf8 17. Qh4 Qe7 $11 {If White avoids the repetition with Qg3, Black can play h5, and overall, with the solid central pawn structure, Black doesn't have any problems in the position.}) 9... Be7 10. Nb3 {Continuing the development seems a bit more logical for White.} (10. f4 O-O 11. f5 {This is an interesting option for White, simply pushing the pawns but they can also become vulnerable.} Re8 {The simplest approach, intending Bf8 to attack the e5-pawn.} (11... Nd7 $5 12. Nf3 Qc7 $132 {This is another possible continuation although the position can become quite complex after White pushes 13.f6.}) 12. Bh5 g6 13. Bg4 (13. e6 Bf6 14. exf7+ Kxf7 15. fxg6+ hxg6 $132 {Black's king will be quite safe on g7.}) 13... Nd7 $1 14. fxg6 (14. e6 Ne5 15. exf7+ Nxf7 16. fxg6 Bc5+ 17. Kh1 hxg6 18. Bxc8 Qxc8 $11) 14... Bc5+ {This check is also good and then recapturing with the f-pawn is the idea.} (14... hxg6 $5 15. e6 Ne5 {Is another alternative, transposing to the line above.}) 15. Kh1 fxg6 16. Bxd7 Bxd7 17. Nf3 Bg4 $11) 10... O-O $11 11. Re1 (11. Be3 Nxb3 12. axb3 Qc7 13. Qd4 (13. f4 f6 {The typical response to break down White's central pawn structure.}) (13. Bf4 Bf5 {Doesn't change much.}) 13... Be6 14. f4 f6 $11) 11... Ne6 (11... Bf5 $5) 12. c3 (12. f4 a5 $132 {[%cal Ga5a4]}) (12. c4 dxc4 13. Bxc4 b5 14. Bf1 a5 15. a4 Ba6 $11 {The knight on e6 stands very well, especially in comparison to the knight on b3.}) 12... f6 13. exf6 Bd6 $5 (13... Bxf6 14. Be3 {This is also fine more or less, although 13...Bd6 equalizes immediately.}) 14. fxg7 Bxh2+ $1 15. Kxh2 (15. Kh1 Nxg7 {Doesn't change much.}) 15... Qh4+ 16. Kg1 Qxf2+ 17. Kh1 Qh4+ $11) (6. Nf3 Bd6 7. c4 (7. O-O O-O {Will transpose.}) 7... c6 (7... Bb4+ $5 {A nice alternative but it's probably not necessary to enter this line.} 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. O-O Ndf6 10. c5 b6 $11) 8. O-O O-O $11 {Black has a nice version of the Petroff defense.}) (6. Bf4 Qf6 $5 {Black has other options too, but this puts pressure on the bishop on f4 and the knight on e5 right away.} 7. Qf3 Bd6 8. Bxe4 Nxe5 9. dxe5 Bxe5 10. Bxe5 Qxe5 11. Nc3 dxe4 12. Qxe4 Qxe4+ 13. Nxe4 Bd7 $11 {When Black can choose to castle either side next, with an equal position.}) 6... Nxe5 7. dxe5 Nc5 $1 {Retreating the knight right away, otherwise White may go c4 to put pressure on our center.} 8. Be3 (8. Nc3 c6 {White was already threatening Nxd5 and then Bb5+, so it's better simply to defend the pawn.} 9. f4 (9. Qf3 Qh4 {An active move, intending Bg4 next.} 10. h3 Be7 $132) (9. Be2 $6 d4 10. Nb1 Bf5 $15 {0-1 (26) Jones,G (2670)-Aronian,L (2773) chess24.com INT 2020}) (9. Ne2 Be7 10. c3 (10. f4 f6 $132 {1/2-1/2 (23) Mamedyarov,S (2760) -Kramnik,V (2799) Wijk aan Zee 2008}) 10... Nxd3 11. Qxd3 O-O $11) 9... Nxd3 $1 ({After} 9... g6 10. Ne2 $1 Nxd3 11. cxd3 $14 {The computer suggests that White is quite quick with d4 and Ng3, so it's better to capture on d3 immediately.}) 10. Qxd3 (10. cxd3 Bf5 {The point is that now we don't need g6 and we can play Bf5 straight away.} 11. d4 {If 11.g4, we can retreat the bishop to d7, and White's king will be left a bit exposed.} h5 $132) 10... Bc5+ 11. Kh1 f6 $5 $146 (11... g6 {[%cal Gc8f5] Is also good.}) 12. Bd2 (12. exf6 $6 Qxf6 13. Re1+ Be7 $15 {This is Black's point.}) 12... O-O 13. exf6 Rf7 $5 {I like this suggestion by the computer.} ({A playable continuation is:} 13... Qxf6 14. Nxd5 Qd6 15. Nc7 Rb8 $44 {Capturing the knight would have run into Qc4+ when the bishop on c5 would have been lost, while in this position, Black seems to have enough compensation for the pawn.}) 14. fxg7 Bf5 15. Qf3 Rxg7 16. Rae1 Bd4 $132 {[%cal Gd8h4] The queen will go to h4 when Black's pieces will be very active, while at some point, the light-squared bishop can go to e4, for example after Black captures on c3 at the right moment.}) (8. Be2 c6 (8... Be7 9. Be3 O-O {Should be also good.}) 9. c3 (9. Be3 Ne6 {Transposes to 8.Be3.}) (9. Nd2 Be7 10. Nb3 O-O $11) 9... Be7 10. Be3 O-O 11. Nd2 a5 $11) (8. f4 Nxd3 9. Qxd3 g6 {It's important to prevent f4-f5.} 10. Be3 (10. Nc3 Bf5 $1 11. Qb5+ (11. Qxd5 $6 Qxd5 12. Nxd5 O-O-O 13. Ne3 Bc5 14. Kh1 Be6 $17 {Black controls the open d-file, has the bishop pair, and White has difficulties completing the development, so Black is much better.}) 11... c6 12. Qxb7 Bc5+ 13. Kh1 Qc8 14. Qxc8+ Rxc8 $132 {[%csl Gc5,Gf5][%cal Gf5c2]}) 10... c5 11. Nc3 (11. Bf2 Be7 {Is similar.}) 11... d4 12. Ne4 Be7 (12... dxe3 $6 {Capturing the bishop can be quite risky after:} 13. Nf6+ Ke7 14. Qb5 $40) 13. Bf2 Bf5 14. Rfe1 (14. Qe2 O-O 15. g4 Bd7 $132 {Black has fantastic counterplay thanks to White's weakened king.}) 14... O-O 15. c3 dxc3 16. Qxc3 Bxe4 17. Rxe4 Qd5 $11) 8... c6 (8... Nxd3 9. Qxd3 Be7 {Is another possible continuation.}) 9. f4 (9. Be2 Ne6 $5 {Preventing the proper development of White's knight. Transposes to 8.Be3.} (9... Be7 {Is also fine, although I prefer 9...Ne6 immediately.} 10. c4 (10. c3 O-O 11. Nd2 a5 12. Nb3 Nxb3 13. a