nd Black is lacking development, so this accurate move is right on time.} 14. Qh6 (14. Qe2 O-O 15. Bxg5 (15. f4 Bxb2 16. Rab1 Bf6 17. fxg5 Bxg5 18. Bxg5 Qxg5 19. Nf3 Qf4 20. Ne5 Qg5 $11 {It may be difficult for Black to play for an advantage, although for White, being two pawns down, he should probably take the draw.}) 15... Qxg5 16. Nf3 Qh5 17. Qxe5 Qxe5 18. Nxe5 {The endgame is fine for Black.} Re8 19. Rfe1 a5 $11) (14. Qxg5 $2 Qxg5 15. Bxg5 Bxb2 16. Rab1 Bc3 $17) 14... Qf6 $1 15. Bxg5 Qxh6 16. Bxh6 Bxb2 17. Rae1+ (17. Rab1 Bc3 18. Rb3 (18. Rfe1+ Kd8 {Transposes.}) 18... Bf6 19. Re1+ Kd8 20. c4 Re8 {White has compensation for the pawn but Black is also doing well.} 21. Rxe8+ Nxe8 22. cxd5 cxd5 23. Bxh7 (23. Bf4 Nc7 {Black is fine.}) 23... Nd6 24. Bf4 Ke7 25. Nf3 b5 $5 26. Bxd6+ Kxd6 27. Rxb5 Ba6 $44) (17. Rfe1+ Kd8 {Is similar.}) 17... Ne6 (17... Kd8 18. c4 Ne6 {Is unclear.}) 18. Nf3 (18. f4 Kd7 $5 {This is more accurate than Kd8 according to the engine.} 19. f5 Nc5 20. f6 Kd8 21. Bg7 Nxd3 22. cxd3 Re8 23. Nf3 Be6 {White also needs to be careful as Black has the bishop pair.} 24. Ng5 Kd7 25. Rb1 Be5 26. Rxb7+ Bc7 $132) (18. c4 Bd7 19. cxd5 cxd5 20. Nf3 Bc3 21. Re2 Kd8 $11) 18... Kd8 19. Ne5 (19. h3 Kc7 {Doesn't change much.}) 19... Ke7 20. f4 f6 21. Ng4 Kf7 22. f5 Nc5 23. Bf4 h5 24. Nh6+ Rxh6 {Black can return some material now, and after:} 25. Bxh6 Nxd3 26. cxd3 Bc3 27. Re2 Bd7 $44 {Thanks to the active bishop pair and many pawns on the queenside, only Black can be better, while activating the rook with Rg8 and Rg4 may be an idea in the position.}) 9... Nxd3 10. Qxd3 g6 11. Nc3 (11. Nd2 c5 $5 (11... Bf5 12. Qb3 Qd7 13. Qc3 {[%cal Ge5e6,Ge3c5,Gb2b4] This seems slightly more pleasant for White.}) 12. c3 (12. Qb5+ {The check on b5 doesn't accomplish much for White.} Qd7 13. Qe2 Be7 14. Nf3 d4 15. Bf2 b6 $11 {[%cal Gc8b7]}) (12. Rad1 Bf5 13. Qe2 d4 14. Bf2 Qd5 {This is also simple for Black.} 15. Nc4 O-O-O 16. Bh4 Rd7 $11) 12... Bf5 13. Qe2 Qd7 14. Nf3 (14. Rad1 Be7 