1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4 Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. Nxe5 Nd7 6. Nxd7 {This is the old main line which dropped out of fashion because it was proven that the line is fine for Black. In any case, there is plenty of theory and we need to know how to deal with it. After the exchange on d7, White intends to castle and to push c4.} Bxd7 7. O-O (7. Qe2 Qh4 {Provoking g3.} (7... Qe7 {This is also fine.}) 8. Nc3 {Transposes to 7.Qe2.} (8. g3 Qe7 9. f3 (9. c4 Nf6 $11) 9... Nd6 $11) 8... Bb4 {This seems like a forced line where Black is doing well.} 9. O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. c4 {Leads to simplifications.} Nc3 12. Qd2 Qxd4 13. Bb2 {13.Bxh7 Kxh7 14.Qxd4 Ne2+ wins the queen back, so the tactic doesn't work for White.} Ne2+ 14. Qxe2 Qxb2 $11) (7. Nc3 Qh4 $1 {It's better to start with this move since capturing on c3 and then Bd6 would potentially allow some moves like Qh5 that can be annoying to Black.} 8. O-O (8. g3 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Qh3 {White can't castle now.} 10. Qf3 (10. Qe2+ Be7 11. Ba3 (11. Bg5 f6 {Black is fine.}) 11... Qe6 $11) 10... Be6 {Protecting all the pawns.} 11. Be3 (11. Rb1 O-O-O {Doesn't change much.}) 11... Bd6 12. Kd2 O-O-O $11) (8. Qf3 Nxc3 (8... Bg4 $5 9. Qe3 O-O-O {A suggestion by the engines that's also interesting, although capturing on c3 seems straightforward.}) 9. bxc3 Bd6 $1 {Sacrificing the pawn on d5 when Black would have a lot of activity to show for it while White is lacking development and it won't be easy to castle.} 10. Qxd5 (10. g3 Qh3 11. Qxd5 O-O $44 {With Bc6 or a check on e8 next.}) 10... Bc6 11. Qg5 (11. Bb5 $6 O-O 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Qxc6 Rae8+ 14. Kf1 Re6 {Black is down two pawns but the pieces are quite active.} 15. Qf3 Rfe8 {White has difficulties developing and Re1 is a threat, while a move like Bd2 runs into Rf6.} 16. Be3 Rf6 17. Qe2 Bf4 $17) 11... Qxg5 12. Bxg5 Bxg2 13. Rg1 Bf3 14. h4 Bh2 15. Kd2 Bxg1 16. Rxg1 O-O {It seems best to return the exchange immediately and equalize without any problems.} (16... c6 17. Re1+ Kf8 18. Be7+ Kg8 19. Bd6 h5 20. Re7 {Black holds on to the material but considering White's active pieces, White definitely isn't worse.} b5 21. Bf4 $44) 17. Bh6 g6 18. Bxf8 Kxf8 $11) (8. Qe2 {Transposes to 7.Qe2.}) (8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. g3 Bb4+ (9... Qe7 $5 10. Be2 Qf6 {Provoking Be2 and then Qf6, intending Bd6, is also possible.}) 10. c3 Qe7 11. Bc2 Bd6 12. O-O O-O 13. f3 Bc6 $5 {This is not necessary but it leads to complications where White can also go wrong.} (13... exf3 14. Qxf3 Rae8 15. Bf4 Bxf4 16. Qxf4 Bh3 17. Rfd1 Qe3+ 18. Qxe3 Rxe3 19. Re1 Rfe8 20. Rxe3 Rxe3 21. Kf2 Re6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (50) Shankland,S (2710)-Dominguez Perez,L (2743) Saint Louis 2023}) 14. Re1 f5 15. fxe4 Bxe4 16. Bxe4 fxe4 17. Qg4 {White needs to go after the e4-pawn.} (17. Qb3+ $2 Kh8 18. Qxb7 Qf7 19. Be3 Qf3 $17 {Bxg3 can be considered next.}) 17... Qf7 $5 (17... Rae8 {Is also possible.}) 18. Be3 Qd5 19. Bh6 (19. Rf1 Rxf1+ 20. Rxf1 Rf8 $11) 19... Rf7 20. Rxe4 Kh8 21. Bd2 Raf8 $44 {Black's pieces are quite active, potentially intending Rf2 but also White can't easily develop the a1-rook thanks to the pressure on the a2-pawn.}) 8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 O-O-O $1 {Re1+ would have arrived quite quickly, so Black doesn't have time to castle short.} 10. Qf3 (10. g3 Qg4 $11) (10. h3 Bd6 {Black is doing well.}) 10... Be6 11. Bf4 (11. Rb1 Bd6 12. g3 Qg4 $11) (11. h3 Bd6 12. a4 h5 $132 {At some point Bg4 may be a threat, and also there is the idea of pushing g5-g4.}) 11... Bd6 12. Bxd6 (12. Bg3 Qg4 $11) 12... Rxd6 $11 {Only Black can be better thanks to the weak queenside pawns that White has.}) (7. Nd2 Nxd2 ({Another possibility is:} 7... f5 $5 8. O-O Qf6 9. Nf3 Bd6 10. Ne5 O-O-O $13) 8. Bxd2 Qe7+ $1 {This check forces White to react.} 9. Be3 (9. Qe2 Qxe2+ 10. Kxe2 Bd6 $11) (9. Kf1 O-O-O 10. h4 h5 11. c3 Qd6 $11) 9... Qb4+ 10. Qd2 (10. c3 {Black can go after the b2-pawn.} Qxb2 11. O-O Bd6 12. Bd2 (12. a4 O-O {Black is fine.}) 12... O-O 13. Rb1 (13. a4 Rfe8 $11) 13... Qxa2 14. Ra1 Qb2 $11) 10... Qxd2+ 11. Kxd2 Bd6 {The endgame is simply equal.} 12. h4 (12. a4 a5 13. b3 c6 14. Rae1 Be6 15. f4 f5 16. g4 O-O $11 {0-1 (61) Donchenko,A (2636) -Kosteniuk,A (2516) Chess.com INT 2021}) 12... h5 13. Rae1 Be6 14. g3 Kd7 15. Bf4 {½- (24) ½ (24) Fressinet,L (2616)-Svane,R (2629) Germany 2025} a5 16. Re3 g6 $11) 7... Bd6 8. c4 (8. Nd2 O-O 9. Bxe4 dxe4 10. Nxe4 {Black has a typical tactic that restores the material balance:} Bxh2+ 11. Kxh2 Qh4+ 12. Kg1 Qxe4 $11) (8. Qh5 {This is an old line where Black can simply give up the pawn.} O-O $1 9. Qxd5 (9. Nc3 Bc6 10. f3 g6 11. Qh6 Nxc3 12. bxc3 a6 $11 {[%cal Gc6b5,Gf8e8,Gd8d7]}) (9. f3 Nf6 10. Qh4 h6 $11) 9... Bc6 10. Qh5 (10. Qf5 g6 {Is similar.}) 10... g6 {Black has tremendeous activity.} 11. Qh3 (11. Qh6 Re8 $1 {[%cal Gd6f8] Threatening Bf8 and indirectly attacking the d4-pawn.} 12. Be3 (12. Nc3 Bf8 13. Qf4 Qxd4 (13... Bd6 $11) 14. Be3 Qd6 $11) (12. c3 Bf8 {Black can go for the repetition.} (12... Qd7 $44) 13. Qf4 (13. Qh3 Bd7 (13... h5 $44) 14. Qf3 Bc6 $11) 13... Bd6 $11) 12... Bf8 (12... Qd7 $5) 13. Qh3 (13. Qf4 Bd6 $11) 13... h5 $1 {[%cal Gc6d7] We can see this typical idea once again.} 14. Bc4 b5 15. Bb3 a5 16. a4 b4 $44 {Black has very good compensation especially since White has difficulties developing as Nd2 would run into Nxd2 and then White would lose the d4-pawn.}) (11. Qd1 Re8 {Black can get even a winning position if White is not careful.} ({Another possibility is:} 11... Qh4 $5 12. f4 Nf6 13. Qe1 Qxe1 14. Rxe1 Rfe8 $44) 12. Nd2 (12. Nc3 $2 Nxf2 $1 13. Rxf2 Qh4 $19) (12. Be3 $2 Qh4 13. h3 Ng3 $1 14. Re1 Nh1 $3 {An amazing move. Black has many threats in the position now.} 15. d5 Bd7 $17 {[%cal Gd7h3]}) (12. g3 Qd7 $40 {The king on g1 is a bit vulnerable.}) 12... Bxh2+ $1 13. Kxh2 Qh4+ 14. Kg1 Ng5 $1 {Black has a very nice attack.} 15. Be2 (15. Re1 Rxe1+ (15... Nh3+ $5 16. gxh3 Qg5+ 17. Qg4 Rxe1+ 18. Nf1 Qd5 19. f3 {Even though it's two pieces for a rook, Black has good compensation thanks to the active rook on e1 and the overall pieces in general.} h5 2