r, while White would still have weaknesses on the queenside that we are targeting.}) 15... a6 {Preventing Bb5.} 16. Rfe1 (16. c4 dxc4 17. d5 (17. Be2 Be6 18. Bf3 Bd5 19. Bxd5+ Qxd5 20. Qxc7 b5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (25) Hedlund,T (2559)-Yefremov,Y (2558) ICCF email 2012}) 17... Qa4 18. Qxc4 Qxc4 19. Bxc4 b5 $11) (16. h4 b5 17. h5 h6 18. Rbe1 Rae8 $11 {We have counterplay all the time thanks to the weak c3-pawn.}) (16. g3 b5) 16... Qxc3 $146 (16... Rae8 {Is also possible.}) 17. Re7 (17. h4 Qc6 {This is also fine for Black.}) 17... Qc6 {Black will neutralize White's activity and the position will be equal.} 18. Rbe1 (18. Qg5 Rf7 19. Rxf7 Kxf7 20. Bxf5 Bxf5 21. Qxf5+ Kg8 22. Re1 Rf8 $11) 18... Rae8 {Contesting the e-file.} 19. Rxe8 (19. Qg5 Rxe7 20. Rxe7 Rf7 21. Rxf7 Kxf7 22. Bxf5 h6 23. Qh5+ Ke7 24. Bxd7 Qxd7 25. Qe5+ Kf7 $11) 19... Rxe8 20. Rxe8+ Bxe8 21. Qxf5 (21. Bxf5 Bg6 $11) 21... Bg6 22. Qc8+ Kf7 23. Bf5 Ke7 $11) (11. h3 c6 12. c4 (12. Rb1 b5 $11 {Prevents c3-c4.}) 12... Be8 {We can see this typical bishop reroute once again.} (12... Qf6 $5) 13. Qf3 dxc4 14. Bxc4+ Bf7 15. Bxf7+ Rxf7 $11) 11... c6 12. Bg5 (12. c4 Qa5 $5 {This is Black's extra option in this move order.} 13. Bg5 (13. Rd1 Be8 {The typical maneuver once again.}) 13... Be8 14. Qf3 dxc4 15. Bxc4+ Bf7 16. Bxf7+ (16. Bb3 Rfe8 {Black is doing well.}) 16... Rxf7 17. Re6 Rd7 18. c4 (18. Rae1 $6 Qxa2 {Black can simply pick up this pawn.}) 18... Bf8 {There is pressure on the e4-pawn so the position is balanced.} 19. Re5 Qc7 20. Rxf5 (20. Qxf5 Rxd4 {This is Black's counterplay.}) 20... Rxd4 $11) (12. a4 Qc7 {The simplest continuation.} (12... Be8 $5 13. Qf3 f4 14. c4 Qh4 15. Bf1 Bf7 {The position is a bit more complex but definitely playable.}) 13. c4 Be8 14. Qh3 (14. Qf3 dxc4 15. Bxc4+ Bf7 16. Bxf7+ Qxf7 $11) 14... dxc4 15. Bxc4+ (15. Bxf5 Bg6 16. Bxg6 hxg6 17. Qe6+ Qf7 {Black equalizes completely with the help of tactics as f2 is under attack.} 18. Qxf7+ Kxf7 19. Ba3 Rad8 20. Bxd6 Rxd6 21. c3 b6 $11) 15... Bf7 16. B