g center compensate for it quite well.}) 8... O-O $1 {Giving up the pawn and going for activity. This is the choice of most players nowadays.} (8... c6 {This move was the old theory.}) 9. cxd5 (9. Bxe4 dxe4 10. c5 Be7 11. Nc3 {Black has some issues with the e4-pawn as f5 runs into Qb3+ and then Qxb7, but the e4-pawn can simply be sacrificed and Black will have good compensation for it.} b6 $1 12. cxb6 (12. Nxe4 Bc6 $44) 12... axb6 13. Nxe4 Bc6 14. Nc3 Bb7 (14... Re8 $5 15. Re1 Bb4 {This is also fine for Black.}) 15. Re1 Bf6 16. Be3 Qd7 17. h3 Rad8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (34) Nekhaev,A (2489)-Matyukhin,S (2505) ICCF email 2018}) (9. c5 {This move is possible but White needs to be a bit careful.} Be7 10. Qc2 (10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 c6 12. Bf4 (12. Qh5 g6 {Doesn't change much.}) (12. Rb1 b6 {Putting pressure on the c5-pawn is also an idea.}) 12... b6 13. cxb6 axb6 14. a4 Bf6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (15) Smeets,J (2659)-Giri,A (2642) Eindhoven 2010}) (10. Nd2 Bf5 {The simplest continuation.} (10... Ng5 $5 {Provoking f4 is also interesting.} 11. f4 Ne4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Bxe4 Re8 $44) 11. Nxe4 (11. Qc2 Nxd2 12. Bxd2 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Re8 $11) 11... Bxe4 $11) (10. f3 Ng5 11. Nc3 c6 12. f4 Ne6 13. Be3 f5 $132 {Black has good chances to be better after Bf6 since there is pressure on both d4 and f4 pawns.}) (10. Qb3 b6 $1 {Giving up the pawn and going for activity.} 11. Nc3 (11. Qxd5 Nf6 12. Qb3 (12. Qf3 Bg4 13. Qe3 Re8 $44) 12... Be6 (12... bxc5 13. dxc5 Bxc5 $11) 13. Bc4 Qxd4 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. Qxe6+ Kh8 16. Nc3 (16. Qxe7 $2 {All of Black's pieces will contribute to the attack now.} Rae8 17. Qxc7 Ng4 $19) 16... Qxc5 $11) 11... Nxc3 12. Qxc3 c6 13. b4 a5 14. a3 axb4 15. axb4 Rxa1 16. Qxa1 Bf6 $11 {Black isn't better but isn't worse either.}) 10... Bf6 $5 {Putting pressure on d4, while 11.Bxe4 dxe4 12.Qxe4 Bc6 is definitely in Black's favor.} 11. Be3 (11. Nc3 Bf5 $1 {An important move, keeping the knight on e4.} 12. Ne2 (12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Bxe4 Bxe4 14. Qxe4 Bxd4 15. Qxb7 Bxc5 16. Bf4 Bb6 $11 {With equality, while the queen can go to f6 if it's chased away by a rook on d1.}) 12... Bg6 13. Be3 Ng5 14. Nf4 Re8 $11 {After 15.Nxg6 hxg6, Black's knight can land on the e6-square from where it puts pressure on the d4-pawn.}) 11... Re8 12. Nd2 (12. Bxe4 Rxe4 {This is an interesting possibility that can lead to some complications.} (12... dxe4 13. Nc3 Bc6 $132) 13. Nc3 Rg4 14. Qd2 (14. f3 $6 Bxd4 {Is good for Black.}) 14... c6 15. f3 Rg6 16. Ne2 h5 17. Nf4 Rh6 {Black's rook seems a bit weird on the h6-square, although on the other hand, White should probably go for the repetition.} 18. Nd3 Rg6 $11) (12. Nc3 Bf5 $11) 12... Bf5 13. Nf3 Bg6 14. b4 Bh5 15. Nd2 Bg6 $11) (9. Qc2 $6 Qh4 {Provoking weaknesses around the king on g1.} 10. g3 Qh5 $15) 9... f5 10. Nc3 (10. Nd2 Nxd2 11. Bxd2 Qf6 $11 {With White's doubled d-pawns being weak, Black is doing fine.}) (10. Qf3 Qh4 11. g3 Qh3 12. Qg2 Qh5 $132) (10. Na3 Qh4 11. f4 (11. g3 {Black can simply go for a draw.} Nxg3 12. hxg3 Bxg3 13. fxg3 Qxg3+ 14. Kh1 Qh3+ $11) 11... Bxa3 12. bxa3 Rfe8 ({Another possibility is:} 12... Rae8 13. Qb3 Kh8 $44) 13. Qb3 Nd6 $44 {Black's pieces are standing quite well and provide adequate counterplay for the missing pawn, while White also has a lot of weaknesses.}) 10... Qf6 $1 11. Ne2 (11. Nxe4 fxe4 12. Bxe4 Bxh2+ {Not 12...Qh4 due to 13.f4.} 13. Kxh2 Qh4+ 14. Kg1 Qxe4 $11 {Black is at least not worse.}) (11. Be3 Rae8 $132) (11. Qc2 Rae8 12. Nxe4 fxe4 13. Bxe4 Qh4 {Keeping the tension in the position is also interesting.} (13... Bxh2+ 14. Kxh2 Qh4+ 15. Kg1 Qxe4 16. Qxe4 Rxe4 17. Be3 c6 $11 {The endgame is level as Black is a pawn down but it's very difficult for White to win.}) 14. f4 Bb5 15. Bd3 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Qh5 17. Qf3 (17. Be3 g5 $1 {This is a very nice point as there is indirect pressure on the h2-pawn.}) 17... Qxf3 18. Rxf3 Re1+ 19. Rf1 Re2 $11) (11. Qf3 Ng5 $1 12. Qh5 (12. Bxg5 Qxg5 13. Bb5 (13. Nb5 Bxb5 14. Bxb5 Qh4 15. g3 Qxd4 $11 {Only White can be worse.}) 13... Bc8 $1 {0-1 (38) Guseinov,G (2