{[%evp 0,66,26,21,28,5,5,24,13,15,17,17,3,-10,-13,3,28,27,23,30,24,19,1,2,14,6,5,5,20,29,36,39,35,54,29,42,48,45,43,45,42,30,56,32,35,47,34,14,24,22,31,38,50,56,57,55,55,52,60,56,78,77,64,62,69,77,68,59,75]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4 Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. Nxe5 Nd7 6. Nc3 {The main move nowadays.} Nxc3 {The best and simplest continuation.} ({An alternative is:} 6... Nxe5 7. dxe5 Bb4 {Black's position is a bit dangerous but with some concrete knowledge of the theory, Black is also fine here.}) 7. bxc3 Bd6 8. O-O (8. Qh5 Bxe5 $5 $146 (8... g6 {Is also good.} 9. Qh6 {Preventing 0-0.} (9. Qe2 O-O 10. O-O c5 $11) 9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Bxe5 11. O-O Qf6 12. Rb1 (12. Re1 Be6 13. Rb1 {Black will exchange some pawns on the queenside and will equalize.} Bxc3 14. Bg5 Qg7 15. Qxg7 Bxg7 16. Rxb7 O-O 17. Rxc7 Rfc8 $11) 12... Qg7 (12... Bxc3 {Also unclear} 13. Rb3 a6 $13) 13. Qh4 O-O 14. Bh6 Qf6 15. Qxf6 Bxf6 16. Bxf8 Kxf8 {Black has a healthy pawn structure and the bishop pair, so there is sufficient compensation.} 17. c4 dxc4 18. Bxc4 a5 19. a4 b6 {Black will not exchange the light-squared bishops and it will be very difficult for White to win.} 20. Rbd1 Bf5 $44 {½- (47) ½ (47) Mamedov,R (2673)-Nguyen,T (2577) Riga 2021}) 9. dxe5 Qe7 10. Bf4 (10. O-O Nxe5 11. Bg5 Bg4 $1 12. Qh4 f6 {Black intends to keep the extra pawn and little by little, solve the problems in the position.} 13. Rae1 Kf7 $132) (10. f4 Nc5 11. O-O Nxd3 12. cxd3 Qc5+ 13. Kh1 (13. Rf2 {Black is already at least not worse.} g6 14. Qh4 Be6 15. a4 Kd7 {The king is quite safe in the center.} 16. Ba3 Qe3 17. Qe7+ Kc8 $132 {Black might have ideas like pushing the h-pawn to provoke weaknesses around White's king.}) 13... Qxc3 14. Be3 d4 15. Bg1 g6 16. Qh4 c5 17. f5 $1 (17. Rac1 Qa5 {Black is on time to offer a queen exchange.} 18. Qf6 O-O 19. f5 Qd8 $132) 17... Bxf5 (17... gxf5 {This is also possible but it leads to quite a bit of complications.} 18. Qf6 Rg8 19. e6 $1 Bxe6 20. Rae1 Kd7 21. Rxe6 fxe6 22. Qf7+ Kd6 23. h4 $1 {[%cal Gg1h2]} Rac8 24. Bh2+ Kc6 25. Rb1 b6 26. Qxe6+ Kb7 27. Qd7+ Ka6 28. Qb5+ $11) 18. Rxf5 Qxa1 (18... gxf5 $2 19. Qf6 $18) 19. Rxf7 Kxf7 20. Qf6+ Kg8 21. Qe6+ $11) 10... Nc5 11. O-O Nxd3 12. cxd3 Qe6 {The goal is to prevent f4-f5 from White, so this is a nice idea, intending Qf5.} 13. h3 (13. Rfe1 Qf5 14. Qxf5 Bxf5 15. e6 f6 $11 {Black will win the d3-pawn or the e6-pawn eventually.}) 13... Qf5 14. Qh4 h6 {[%cal Gg7g5]} 15. Bc1 (15. Qg3 g5 16. Bd2 Be6 $132) 15... b6 16. Ba3 g5 $1 (16... c5 $6 17. d4 {Might be a bit better for White.}) 17. Qb4 (17. Qa4+ Bd7 18. Qa6 Bc8 $11) (17. Qd4 Be6 $11) (17. Qg3 Be6 {Black has a good position.}) 17... c5 18. Qa4+ Bd7 19. Qa6 Bc8 $11) (8. Bf4 Bxe5 {The same idea, exchanging on e5 and then Nc5.} (8... O-O {This is also possible.} 9. O-O {Transposes.}) (8... Qf6 9. Bg3 {Is another alternative.}) 9. dxe5 Nc5 10. O-O Nxd3 11. cxd3 Bf5 $11 {[%cal Gd8d7,Ge8g8]}) (8. Nxd7 Qxd7 {Recapturing with the bishop is also possible but this is better.} 9. O-O (9. Qh5 c6 10. O-O Qg4 $1 11. Re1+ Kd8 12. Qxg4 Bxg4 $11) 9... O-O {Transposes.}) 8... O-O 9. Re1 (9. Nxd7 Qxd7 {9...Bxd7 10.Qh5 f5 transposes to a line already analyzed, although recapturing with the queen seems more accurate in this case.} 10. Qh5 g6 11. Qf3 (11. Qh4 Re8 12. Bh6 Qc6 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gc6c3]} 13. Rab1 {13.Qf6 runs into 13...Bxh2+, although sometimes Black also has Bf8 as a defensive resource.} a6 $1 {Simply preventing Bb5.} (13... Qxc3 $6 {This might give White good counterplay on the kingside.} 14. Rb3 Qa5 15. Rb5 Qa3 16. f4 $40) 14. Bg5 (14. f4 Be7 15. Bg5 f6 16. Bh6 f5 17. Bg5 Bxg5 18. fxg5 Qxc3 19. Rf3 Qd2 $132) 14... Bf8 15. f4 Bg7 16. f5 {Leads to simplifications.} Bxf5 17. Bxf5 gxf5 18. Rxf5 (18. Qg3 {Doesn't change much as Black has proper resources and the position remains balanced.} h6 19. Bh4 Qg6 20. Rxb7 Re2 $11) 18... Qxc3 19. Bf6 Bxf6 {The material is reduced so Black is doing fine.} 20. Rxf6 (20. Qxf6 Re1+ 21. Rf1 Qe3+ 22. Kh1 Rxf1+ 23. Rxf1 Qe6 24. Qg5+ Kh8 $11) 20... Re4 21. Qg5+ Kh8 22. Rxf7 Qxd4+ 23. Kh1 Rae8 24. h3 Re1+ 25. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 26. Kh2 Qg1+ 27. Kg3 Qe3+ 28. Kh4 Qxg5+ 29. Kxg5 Re2 30. Rxc7 Rxg2+ 31. Kf6 Rf2+ 32. Ke5 b5 33. Kxd5 Rh2 34. Rc6 Rxh3 35. Rxa6 Rc3 $11) 11... Re8 12. Bd2 (12. Bh6 Qg4 13. Qxg4 (13. Qf6 Bxh2+ $1 {This is Black's point.} 14. Kh1 Be5 $1 {[%cal Gg4h5]}) 13... Bxg4 $11) (12. Rb1 c6 13. Bg5 b5 {Preventing c4.} 14. Rbe1 Re6 15. h4 Qe8 $11) (12. h3 {Preventing Qg4.} Qc6 13. Bd2 b6 14. Rfb1 a6 15. a4 Bb7 $11) 12... Qd8 {Intending Be6.} 13. Rfe1 (13. Rab1 c6 {Doesn't change much.}) 13... Rxe1+ 14. Rxe1 Be6 15. g3 Bf8 $11) (9. f4 $6 c5 $15 {Intending c5-c4 at some point and then Nf6, while White will still have a lot of weaknesses on the queenside.}) (9. Bf4 {Transposes.} Bxe5 $1 {The typical idea of capturing on e5 and then Nc5.} (9... Qf6 $6 10. Bg3 Bxe5 11. Qh5 $1 {[%cal Gd4e5] This is a bit risky for Black.}) 10. dxe5 (10. Bxe5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qe7 12. Re1 (12. f4 {Now it's important to react properly:} f6 $1 {The typical way to fight against White's center.} 13. Qh5 (13. Qf3 Be6 14. Rae1 f5 15. Kh1 Rad8 16. Qe3 Qa3 $11 {Black has good counterplay on the queenside.}) (13. Re1 fxe5 14. Rxe5 Qc5+ 15. Kh1 Qxc3 16. Rb1 g6 17. h3 c6 $132) 13... g6 14. Qh4 Bd7 {Intending to complete the development with Rae8 next.} 15. f5 (15. Rae1 Rae8 $11) 15... g5 16. exf6 Qe3+ 17. Qf2 Qxf2+ 18. Rxf2 Kf7 $11 {Black will recapture the pawn on f6 with the king.}) (12. Qh5 g6 13. Qe2 Bd7 $11) (12. Qe2 Qc5 {Black can try to target White's weaknesses already.} 13. Rae1 (13. Qf3 Be6 14. Qg3 f5 15. exf6 Rxf6 16. Rae1 Kh8 $11) 13... Qxc3 14. Qh5 g6 15. Qh6 Re8 16. f4 {White has enough compensation for equality but Black isn't worse.} Qc5+ 17. Kh1 Qf8 18. Qh4 Qe7 19. Qg3 Kh8 20. f5 gxf5 21. Bxf5 Rg8 22. Qe3 Bxf5 23. Rxf5 Rg7 $11) 12... Be6 13. Qd2 (13. f4 Qc5+ 14. Kh1 f5 $11 {A typical way to block the pawns when 15.exf6 is met by 15...Rxf6.}) (13. Qh5 g6 14. Qh6 f5 $11) (13. Rb1 b6 14. Rb4 f6 $11) 13... f6 {In general, we don't want to push f5 until what has played f4.} 14. f4 (14. Re3 Rae8 15. Rae1 f5 $11) 14... fxe5 15. Rxe5 Qc5+ ({An alternative is:} 15... Qf6 16. Rae1 Bf7 17. Qe3 Rae8 $11) 16. Qe3 (16. Kh1 Bf7 {This is fine for Black.}) 16... Qxe3+ 17. Rxe3 Bf5 18. Rb1 b6 $11 {The endgame is balanced.}) 10... Nc5 11. Be3 (11. Qf3 Nxd3 12. cxd3 Bf5 13. h3 Qd7 $11) (11. Re1 Nxd3 12. cxd3 d4 13. c4 Bf5 $11) (11. Be2 Re8 $11 {White has weaknesses and can't push f4 yet, so Black is doing well.}) 11... Nxd3 12. cxd3 {Now White intends f4 next but we have an adequate response.} Re8 (12... Qe7 {This is also possible.} 13. Re1 Bf5 14. h3 Qe6 15. d4 Bg6 {If at any moment White goes for a pawn storm with f4 and g4, we can reply with f5!} 16. Re2 a5 17. Rb2 Rfb8 $11) 13. f4 (13. d4 Bf5 14. h3 Re6 15. g4 Bg6 16. f4 f5 $11 {The typical response to White's kingside expansion.}) (13. Qh5 Qd7 $11 {[%cal Gd7f5]}) 13... f5 $11 {Simply establishing a blockade with Be6 next, while White can't capture en passant due to the bishop on e3.}) (9. Qh5 g6 10. Qe2 c5 $11) (9. Qe2 c5 $11) 9... c5 $1 {Black is threatening c5-c4.} 10. Qf3 (10. Nxd7 Qxd7 (10... Bxd7 {This loses the d5-pawn so it's slightly better for White.} 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Qh5 g6 (12... f5 13. Rb1 $14) 13. Qxd5 Qb6 14. Qf3 Bc6 15. Qg3 Rfe8 16. Bd2 $14 {There is some compensation for the pawn but there is no need to give it up at all.}) 11. dxc5 (11. Qh5 g6 12. Qh4 (12. Qf3 c4 13. Bh6 Rd8 14. Qf6 (14. Be2 Qc6 {[%cal Gc8f5]} 15. g4 Re8 $11) 14... Bf8 {Black can parry White's threats adequately.} 15. Bxf8 (15. Bf5 Qd6 {This doesn't accomplish much for White.}) 15... Rxf8 16. Be2 Qc6 17. Qf4 Bf5 $11) 12... c4 13. Bf1 (13. Bh6 Qd8 $1 {Offering a queen exchange is a good continuation.}) (13. Be2 Re8 {White can't play Bf3 easily.}) 13... f6 14. Bh6 Qf7 $1 {Intending to develop the bishop to f5 at some point.} (14... Rf7 $6 15. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2] White will have a slight pressure on Black's position.}) 15. g4 (15. Bxf8 g5 16. Qxg5+ fxg5 17. Bxd6 Bf5 $132) 15... Rd8 $11) 11... Bxc5 12. Qh5 (12. Bf4 Qc6 (12... Qg4 {This is an alternative where Black has sufficient counterplay.} 13. Qd2 Bf5 14. h3 Qg6 15. Bxf5 Qxf5 16. Re5 Qf6 17. Rxd5 Rfd8 $44) 13. Qh5 h6 14. Be5 Bd7 $11 {With Rae8 next.}) (12. Qf3 b6 $11) (12. Be3 Qd6 $11) 12... h6 $1 {Intending Qc6 and Be6 or Bd7.} (12... g6 13. Qh4 $14 {The dark squares are weakened a bit.}) 13. Be3 (13. Bd2 Qc6 14. g4 {This is ambitious but a bit risky.} (14. Re5 Qf6 15. Be3 Bxe3 16. Rxe3 Be6 $11) 14... b6 {Trying to make use of the newly weakened diagonal toward the king on g1.} 15. g5 g6 16. Qxh6 Bb7 $44) (13. Bxh6 gxh6 14. Re5 (14. Qxh6 $2 f5 $19) 14... f5 15. Rxd5 Qxd5 16. Qg6+ $11) (13. h3 Re8 14. Bf4 Re6 15. Qf5 (15. Rad1 Qc6 {And then we develop the bishop from c8.}) 15... g6 16. Qg4 Rf6 $11) (13. Rb1 b6 $11) 13... Bxe3 14. Rxe3 Qd6 {Intending Be6 next.} 15. Rd1 (15. Qh4 Bd7 16. Qd4 Rfe8 17. Rxe8+ (17. c4 Bc6 18. c5 Qc7 $11 {1/2-1/2 (34) Abdusattorov,N (2646) -Indjic,A (2612) Riga 2021}) 17... Bxe8 18. c4 Bc6 19. Be4 Qb4 20. Bxd5 Bxd5 21. Qxd5 Rc8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (40) Sevian,S (2654)-Dominguez Perez,L (2760) Saint Louis 2021}) 15... Be6 (15... Bd7 {I don't prefer to give up the d5-pawn but it leads to a simple equality too.} 16. Be4 Bc6 17. Bxd5 Bxd5 18. Qxd5 (18. Rxd5 Qa6 {Counterattacks White's weaknesses.}) 18... Qxd5 19. Rxd5 Rfd8 20. Rdd3 Rac8 21. c4 Kf8 22. Kf1 Re8 23. Rxe8+ Kxe8 $11) 16. Qh4 (16. c4 d4 17. Rg3 Qf4 18. h3 Rac8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (49) Abasov,N (2634)-Bluebaum,M (2647) Austria 2022}) (16. Rg3 Kh8 {Black is fine.}) 16... Qb6 17. Rg3 Kh8 18. Qd4 (18. Re1 Bd7 {Intending Rae8 next.}) 18... Qxd4 19. cxd4 Rac8 $11) (10. Ng4 c4 (10... Nb6 $5 11. dxc5 Bxc5 $11 {This continuation is also fine for Black.}) 11. Bf5 b5 {Intending Nb6 next.} (11... g6 $5 12. Qf3 (12. Nh6+ Kh8 {Doesn't change much.}) 12... gxf5 {This leads to some complications.} 13. Nh6+ Kh8 14. Nxf5 Nb6 15. Nxd6 Qxd6 16. Ba3 Qg6 17. Bxf8 Bg4 18. Qf4 Rxf8 19. Re3 Be6 20. Qe5+ Qg7 21. Qc7 Nc8 $132 {The position is balanced according to the engines but I prefer the two pieces over the rook.}) 12. Qf3 (12. h4 Nb6 13. Bxc8 Qxc8 14. Qf3 (14. h5 Qf5 {Is fine for Black.}) 14... Re8 15. Bf4 Bxf4 16. Qxf4 Qc6 $11) (12. Bh6 Nb6 {Bh6 doesn't interrupt Black's plan.}) 12... Nb6 13. Bd2 Bxf5 14. Qxf5 Qd7 15. Ne3 Rad8 16. Qxd7 Rxd7 17. Nf5 Ba3 18. g4 Rfd8 {The position is balanced but long-term, Black seems to have better prospects.} 19. Kg2 Kf8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (50) Rogos,J (2506)-Dunlop,G (2536) GER email 2019}) (10. Bf4 $6 c4 $1 11. Bf1 Qc7 $15 {When White's light-squared bishop is blocked and the weaknesses are fixed.}) 10... c4 $1 11. Bf5 (11. Bxh7+ Kxh7 12. Nxf7 Rxf7 $5 {A possible continuation to try to play for a win.} (12... Qc7 {Leads to a draw.} 13. Re6 (13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Nh6+ $11) 13... Kg8 14. Nh6+ Kh7 15. Nf7 Kg8 $11) 13. Qxf7 Nf6 14. Bf4 Qf8 {Black will have a pleasant position with two pieces against a rook.} (14... Bxf4 $5 15. Re7 Qxe7 {15...Qg8 runs into 16.Qxf6.} 16. Qxe7 Bf5 $132) 15. Qxf8 Bxf8 16. f3 b5 $132 {White can't enter along the e-file so Black may have better prospects in the long run.}) (11. Bf1 {This seems a bit passive for White.} Nb6 $132) 11... Nxe5 (11... Nb6 $6 12. Bxc8 Qxc8 13. h4 $14) 12. dxe5 Re8 {The most accurate move.} (12... Bc5 {Is a decent continuation.}) 13. Bxc8 (13. Bf4 Bf8 (13... Bxf5 {Leads to a position where White might be slightly preferable thanks to the passed pawn.} 14. exd6 Re4 15. h3 $14) 14. g4 (14. Bxc8 Rxc8 {Transposes.}) 14... Be6 15. Be3 b6 16. Bd4 g6 17. Bxe6 fxe6 18. Qg3 Bc5 19. f4 Rf8 $11 {Black's position is quite solid.}) 13... Rxc8 14. Bg5 (14. Bf4 Bf8 {Black's ideas will often include Qa5 or Rc5-Ra5 to attack White's queenside weaknesses. Transposes.} 15. Re2 (15. Red1 Rc5 16. Rd2 Qd7 17. h4 (17. Rad1 Qa4 {Transposes.}) 17... Qe6 18. h5 h6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (31) Vocaturo,D (2621)-Sankalp,G (2504) Sitges 2021}) (15. Rad1 Rc5 {Is similar.}) 15... Qd7 16. Rd1 Rc5 17. Red2 Qa4 {Transposes.} 18. g3 $5 (18. h4 Qxa2 19. h5 h6 20. g4 Qa4 21. Be3 Ra5 {White can win the d5-pawn but Black has sufficient counterplay.} 22. Rxd5 Qc6 $132) (18. Be3 Ra5 19. Rxd5 Rxd5 20. Rxd5 (20. Qxd5 Qxc2 {Is fine for Black.}) 20... Qxc2 21. g3 Qxc3 22. Rd7 Re7 23. Rxe7 Bxe7 24. Qxb7 Qa1+ 25. Kg2 Qxe5 $11) 18... Qxa2 19. Be3 (19. Kg2 b6 20. h4 Ra5 21. h5 h6 22. Rxd5 Rxd5 23. Rxd5 Qa4 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Ga4d7]} (23... Qxc2 24. Rd7 Qf5 25. Rxa7 Bc5 {This is another option for Black.}) 24. Rd2 a5 $132 {The a-pawn starts its march toward the a1-square.}) 19... Rb5 20. Rxd5 Rxd5 21. Rxd5 (21. Qxd5 Qxc2 22. Rc1 Qb3 23. Bd4 a6 $11) 21... Qa4 {We don't want to allow Rd7, that's why we play Qa4 and not Qxc2.} 22. Qf5 Qc6 23. Qd7 Qxd7 24. Rxd7 a5 25. Rxb7 Ra8 26. Kg2 a4 27. Kf3 a3 28. Rb1 a2 29. Ra1 Ra5 30. Ke4 Be7 $11) 14... Be7 (14... Qxg5 15. exd6 Re6 {This may be fine for Black but White has better prospects.}) 15. e6 (15. Be3 Bc5 16. Qg3 {Black equalized without much difficulty in the following game:} (16. Bd4 Bxd4 17. cxd4 b5 18. a3 a5 19. c3 Rb8 $11) 16... Bxe3 17. Qxe3 Qa5 18. h4 Qc5 19. Rad1 Qxe3 20. Rxe3 Rc5 $11 {Intending Ra5 next. ½- (30) ½ (30) Whelan,H (2137) -Moessle,H (2369) ICCF email 2021}) 15... fxe6 16. Rxe6 Bxg5 17. Rxe8+ Qxe8 18. Qxd5+ Kh8 19. Qxg5 Qe2 {White managed to win a pawn but Black has good counterplay and the maximum White can get out of the position is three vs two pawns on the kingside.} 20. Qf5 Rd8 (20... Re8 21. g3 h6 {This is also fine for Black.}) 21. h3 (21. g3 h6 $11 {Is similar.}) (21. h4 h6 22. Rb1 b6 23. a4 Rd2 24. Rc1 Kg8 {Black is quite solid and active, so it's very difficult to improve the position with White.} 25. g3 Rd6 26. Qf4 Rf6 27. Qd4 Rf3 $11 {½- (35) ½ (35) Cheparinov,I (2649)-Liu,Y (2579) Danzhou 2023}) 21... h6 ({Another option is} 21... Qd2 $5) 22. a4 b6 23. Qg4 (23. a5 Rd1+ 24. Rxd1 Qxd1+ 25. Kh2 bxa5 26. Qxa5 Qxc2 $11 {There is pressure on the c3-pawn so it's simply a draw.}) (23. Qf7 Rd2 24. Rc1 Kh7 $11) 23... Qxg4 (23... Qxc2 {Going for the endgame was good but this is also fine.} 24. Qxc4 Re8 $44) 24. hxg4 Rd2 25. Rc1 Kg8 ({An alternative is:} 25... Kh7 $5 {[%cal Gh7g6] The king becomes active on the kingside, eyeing up the g4-pawn.} 26. Kf1 Kg6 27. Ke1 Rd5 28. Rb1 Kg5 29. Rb4 Rc5 30. f3 Kh4 $1 31. Kf2 Rd5 32. Rxc4 Rd2+ 33. Ke3 Rxc2 $11) 26. Kf1 Kf7 27. Ke1 Rd5 28. Rb1 (28. Rd1 Ra5 {Targeting the a4-pawn.}) 28... Rg5 $5 {This seems like the simplest option, provoking f3.} (28... Ke6 29. Rb4 Re5+ 30. Kd2 Kd5 31. a5 (31. Rb5+ Kd6 32. Rxe5 Kxe5 33. Ke3 a5 $11 {The endgame is a draw because White needs to be careful at any moment for some counterplay with b6-b5 on the queenside.}) 31... bxa5 (31... Kc5 32. axb6 axb6 $11) 32. Ra4 Kc6 33. Rxc4+ {½- (50) ½ (50) Nepomniachtchi,I (2773)-Dominguez Perez,L (2753) Bucharest 2022} Kb5 34. Rc7 Rg5 35. f3 Kb6 36. Rd7 h5 $11) 29. f3 h5 30. gxh5 Rxg2 31. Rb4 Rxc2 32. Rxc4 a5 33. Rc6 Rb2 $11 *

