1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nc4 {A rarer option in comparison to the main alternatives. The main move 4.Nf3 and the 4th move Nd3 will be analyzed in the upcoming lessons.} (4. Nxf7 $2 {White doesn't have sufficient compensation for the knight.} Kxf7 5. d4 (5. Bc4+ $2 d5 $1 {The best continuation.} 6. exd5 Bd6 (6... Qe8+ $5 {White doesn't want to exchange the queens due to the Black's king being exposed, but Black gets a good position in any case.} 7. Be2 Bf5 $19) 7. O-O Rf8 8. d4 Kg8 $19 {White has three pawns for the piece but Black is very active, and Ng4 might be a threat sooner or later.}) (5. Nc3 Be6 6. d4 Kg8 {Black is slightly passive but the plan is to play Bf7 if needed and Nbd7 with c5.} 7. Bd3 (7. f4 Nbd7 8. Qf3 c5 $17) 7... c5 {We want to provoke d5, otherwise White's center will be strong and flexible.} 8. d5 Bf7 9. O-O Nbd7 10. f4 a6 11. a4 Qa5 $17 {With ideas like b5, c4, or h5 at some point. Black's pieces are a bit stuck but he is still a piece up, so Black has an advantage.}) 5... c5 $1 {Breaking White's center immediately.} 6. Nc3 (6. Bc4+ d5 $1 7. exd5 Bd6 8. O-O Re8 9. Nc3 Bg4 $1 {Provoking f3.} 10. f3 Bf5 $17 {The pawn on d5 is well blockaded while the king is quite safe and will go to g8, while Nbd7 is also on the agenda.}) (6. dxc5 $6 d5 $1 {This is Black's idea.} 7. e5 Ne4 $19) 6... Bg4 $1 {Provoking f3.} 7. f3 (7. Bc4+ d5 $1 8. Bxd5+ Qxd5 9. Qxg4 Qc6 {9...Nxg4 10.Nxd5 isn't so clear as Nc7 is a threat.} 10. Qd1 cxd4 11. Qxd4 Nbd7 {White has three pawns for the piece but Black is about to develop quite quickly.} 12. Be3 Bd6 {[%cal Gd6e5]} 13. f4 {13.0-0-0 Be5 is Black's point.} Rhd8 $1 14. e5 Bf8 $1 {A slightly difficult continuation but Black is standing very well now.} 15. Qa4 (15. exf6 Nxf6 16. Qa4 Qxa4 17. Nxa4 Re8 $19 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gf6g4]}) (15. O-O-O Nb6 16. Qxd8 Rxd8 17. Rxd8 Nfd5 $19) 15... Qxa4 16. Nxa4 Nd5 $19 {Suddenly White's center isn't strong anymore and there are squares for Black's pieces. Black can continue with moves like b5 or Rac8 next.}) 7... cxd4 8. fxg4 (8. Qxd4 Nc6 9. Bc4+ d5 $1 {Once again, we see this typical move after White gives a check on c4.} 10. Bxd5+ Nxd5 11. Qxd5+ Be6 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 $19 {Intending Nd4 or Nb4 next.}) 8... dxc3 9. bxc3 h6 $1 {It's important to prevent Bg5.} 10. Bc4+ (10. e5 Qe7 11. Bc4+ Ke8 $19 {With dxe5 next.}) 10... Ke8 11. O-O Qc8 $19 {White's scattered pawns are all targets now.}) 4... Nxe4 5. Qe2 (5. d4 d5 6. Ne3 {This version with the knight being placed on the e3-square doesn't seem like it accomplishes much for White.} Qf6 $5 {Immediately putting pressure on f2.} 7. Qe2 Be6 8. c3 c6 9. g3 (9. Nd2 Nd7 10. Nxe4 dxe4 $132) 9... Nd7 10. Bg2 Nd6 $11 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8]}) (5. d3 $6 Nf6 6. d4 d5 7. Ne3 (7. Ne5 Bd6 {This is a worse version for White when Black will castle and push c5.}) 7... c5 $15 {With Nc6 next.}) (5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 (6. bxc3 {I like how Kramnik continued in the following game:} g6 7. d4 Bg7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Nd7 $11 {1/2-1/2 (66) Carlsen,M (2733)-Kramnik,V (2799) Nice 2008}) 6... d5 7. Ne3 (7. Ne5 Bd6 8. Nf3 (8. Qxd5 $2 Qe7 {[%cal Gf7f6]} 9. Bf4 f6 $19) 8... c6 9. c4 O-O {It's fine to give up the isolated pawn in many versions as Black's pieces will become quite active.} 10. cxd5 Re8+ 11. Be2 cxd5 12. O-O Nc6 {With a pleasant type of a French Defense position.} 13. c3 h6 14. Be3 Bf5 $11) 7... Be6 8. f4 {White is going for some counterplay, intending moves like Qf3 or f5.} Bd6 9. Qf3 (9. f5 Bd7 {The d5-pawn is offered again but it's dangerous to capture it due to 0-0 and Bc6 ideas.} 10. Qg4 O-O 11. Bd2 Bc6 {[%cal Gb8d7]} 12. O-O-O Nd7 $132 {With ideas like Ne5 or Nf6.}) 9... c6 10. Bd2 (10. f5 Bc8 11. Bd3 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7e5] Black is fine.}) 10... f5 {The engine suggests to simply block the position.} (10... Nd7 11. O-O-O {11.f5 Ne5 is the point.} Qf6 {This is also good.}) 11. O-O-O O-O 12. Re1 Qf6 $11 {The position is equal but it seems like Black has better prospects since the knight on e3 is a bit passive and Black can eventually bring the knight to e4, for example with the Nd7-Nc5-Ne4 maneuver.}) 5... Qe7 6. Ne3 (6. d4 Nc6 7. c3 d5 $11 {After 8.Ne3, Black can play 8...Be6 and then either to castle long or to push f5. Black is doing well overall.}) (6. d3 Nf6 7. Bg5 Qxe2+ 8. Bxe2 Be7 9. Nc3 Nc6 $11) (6. Nc3 Nf6 (6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 Qxe2+ 8. Bxe2 Nc6 {Black is quite solid in the endgame.}) 7. d4 (7. Nb5 Be6 $11) (7. Qxe7+ Bxe7 8. Ne3 Be6 $11) (7. Ne3 Be6 {Transposes.}) 7... Nc6 8. Be3 (8. d5 Nd4 9. Qxe7+ Bxe7 10. Bd3 Bf5 $11) 8... d5 9. Nd2 Bf5 10. O-O-O O-O-O $11) 6... Be6 {Keeping the possibility for long castling open. Other decent moves are:} (6... c6) (6... Nf6) 7. Nc3 (7. g3 $6 Nc6 8. Bg2 d5 $15 {[%cal Ge8c8]}) (7. c4 g6 $5 {A more aggressive approach, intending Bg7 next.} (7... Nc6 8. Nc3 Nf6 {Is another decent option.}) 8. Qf3 (8. d4 Bg7 9. Nc2 Nf6 10. Nc3 c6 $11) (8. Nc3 Nxc3 9. dxc3 c6 $11 {With Bg7 and Nd7 next.}) 8... f5 {This is the idea, supporting the knight in the center.} (8... Bc8 $5 {A retreat that seems a bit weird but it's the suggestion by the engine.} 9. Nd5 Ng5+ {This is the point.} 10. Qe3 Qxe3+ 11. dxe3 Ne6 $11) 9. d3 Nc5 10. d4 Nc6 $1 {Sacrificing a piece and going for counterplay. It won't be easy for White to navigate the position now.} ({An alternative is:} 10... Ne4 11. Bd3 Bg7 12. Bxe4 fxe4 13. Qxe4 Nc6 14. d5 Bd7 15. Qxe7+ Nxe7 16. Nc3 O-O-O $44) 11. dxc5 O-O-O $40 {All of Black's pieces will join the game very quickly while White's king is still in the center. dxc5 is an idea while Nd4 can also become a nice threat.} 12. Nc3 dxc5 13. Qg3 g5 $5 14. f4 gxf4 15. Qxf4 Rd4 16. Qf2 f4 17. Nc2 Bf5+ 18. Be2 Bxc2 19. O-O Qg7 20. Bxf4 {The position is very double-edged when Rg8 is an idea, but the computer likes to prevent Nb5 with} a6 $132) (7. d4 d5 (7... g6 $5 {[%cal Gf8g7] The same idea with g6 and Bg7 is also possible.} 8. Nd2 Nf6 9. g3 Bg7 10. Bg2 c6 11. O-O O-O $11) 8. c4 (8. Nd2 Nxd2 (8... f5 $5) 9. Bxd2 c5 (9... Nc6 {This is also good.} 10. c3 O-O-O $11) 10. dxc5 Nc6 $11) 8... Nc6 $5 {Attacking d4. This leads to a draw more or less.} 9. cxd5 Nxd4 10. Qd3 Qh4 $1 11. g3 (11. Qxd4 $2 Qxf2+ 12. Kd1 Bg4+ $19) 11... Nf3+ 12. Ke2 Nd4+ {White can't avoid the perpetual check.} 13. Ke1 (13. Qxd4 Nxg3+ 14. Kd3 Qxd4+ 15. Kxd4 Nxh1 16. dxe6 fxe6 $15) 13... Nf3+ $11) 7... Nf6 $1 {Keeping the knights on the board and intending d5 and Nc6 next. Transposes.} (7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 g6 9. g3 c6 10. Bg2 Nd7 11. O-O Bg7 12. a4 {The position seems a bit easier to play for White with ideas like Ba3 and a4-a5.}) 8. g3 (8. g4 $6 Nc6 $1 9. g5 Ng4 10. Ned5 Qd7 11. Nb5 O-O-O 12. Ndxc7 Bf5 {White's position looks a bit shaky with the king still being in the center.} 13. f3 d5 14. fxg4 Bxg4 15. Qf2 a6 16. h3 axb5 17. hxg4 Kxc7 $15) (8. d4 $6 d5 {[%cal Gb8c6] White's knights are a bit passive.}) 8... Nc6 9. Bg2 Qd7 {[%cal Ge8c8] Defending the knight on c6 and intending to castle long and to push d5. 9...0-0-0 can be met by Bxc6 and then Qa6+.} 10. b4 {The critical line, intending b5.} (10. Ncd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 O-O-O $11) (10. O-O O-O-O 11. Ncd5 (11. b4 d5 12. b5 Nd4 13. Qd3 Nf5 14. Nxf5 Bxf5 {Transposes.}) 11... Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Re8 13. Re1 Be7 {Simply continuing the development.} 14. c3 Bd8 15. Qf1 h5 16. d4 h4 {The position remains playable when Black can also try to play for the advantage.} 17. Bd2 Ne7 18. Nf4 Bf5 $11) 10... d5 11. b5 Nd4 12. Qd3 Nf5 13. Ncxd5 (13. O-O {This doesn't put any pressure on Black, so the position is completely fine.} O-O-O 14. Nxf5 Bxf5 {Transposes.} 15. Qd4 b6 {[%cal Gf8c5]} 16. d3 Bh3 17. Bg5 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Be7 19. a4 h6 20. Bd2 Bc5 21. Qf4 Kb8 $11 {The king is quite safe and Black has sufficient counterplay.}) 13... Nxd5 14. Nxf5 Bxf5 15. Qxd5 Qxd5 16. Bxd5 O-O-O 17. Bxf7 Rd7 {White has to watch out for Re7+ and not to get checkmated.} 18. Bh5 g6 19. Be2 (19. Bb2 Bg7 20. Bxg7 Rxg7 21. Be2 Re7 {[%cal Ge7e1] Black is two pawns down at the moment, but thanks to the active pieces, White can't hold on to them.} 22. Kd1 Bxc2+ 23. Kxc2 Rxe2 24. f4 Rd8 25. Rad1 Rd5 26. a4 Rd4 $11) 19... Bg7 20. c3 Re8 {Threatening Bd3.} 21. d4 {Intending Be3 but Black has:} Rxd4 $1 22. cxd4 Bxd4 $11 {[%csl Ra1][%cal Gd4a1] And Black restores the material balance.} *

