1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nd3 {A rarer option in comparison to 4.Nd3 that is still played occasionally. The point is that it reaches an endgame according to the theory where White can continue the game, although the endgame is balanced.} Nxe4 5. Qe2 {Provoking Qe7 and then Nf4 is White's plan.} (5. Nf4 {This move immediately is also possible, although Black doesn't have any issues in the position now.} d5 {Alternatives are:} (5... Nf6) (5... Nc6) 6. d4 Nc6 $5 {I like this move, Black intends to be more aggressive. Other moves are also possible of course, but now the knight puts pressure on the d4-pawn and Black keeps the possibility open for Bf5 and Qd7 next.} 7. Be2 (7. Bb5 Bd6 {Sacrificing the pawn for activity.} 8. Nxd5 O-O 9. Be3 {After 10. 0-0 there are both simply 10...Qh4 or 10...Bxh2+ and then capturing the knight on d5.} Re8 10. Nd2 Bf5 $132) (7. Be3 {It seems a bit early to develop this bishop.} Ne7 $5 {[%cal Ge7f5]} 8. Bd3 (8. Nd2 Nf5 9. Qf3 {9.Nxe4 dxe4 is in Black's favor.} Nxd2 10. Kxd2 c6 $11) 8... Nf6 {Avoiding exchanges. 8...Nf5 was also possible but this is more accurate.} 9. Nc3 Nf5 10. Qf3 Nxe3 11. Qxe3+ Be7 12. O-O-O c6 13. Rde1 Qd6 14. h3 {Preventing any Ng4 ideas.} Bd7 $11 {Black can untangle by playing Kd8 and Re8 when the king will eventually go to c7. With the bishop pair and solid pawn structure, Black isn't worse at all.}) (7. c3 g5 $5 {A more ambitious move, gaining space and playing for advantage.} (7... Nf6 8. Bd3 Bd6 {This is a more solid alternative.}) 8. Nh5 (8. Nd3 Qf6 {Intending Bf5 and 0-0-0.} 9. Be2 Bf5 10. f3 Nd6 $132 {With 0-0-0 and h5 next.}) 8... Qe7 9. Be2 (9. Qe2 Be6 10. Nd2 O-O-O 11. h4 h6 12. Nxe4 dxe4 $132 {White's king is stuck in the center and the pieces are underdeveloped, providing Black with sufficient counterplay.}) 9... Bd7 10. O-O O-O-O $132) 7... Bf5 {7...g5 is not the same like in the 7.c3 line as already White can castle now.} 8. Be3 (8. O-O Bd6 {Intending 0-0 while 9.Nxd5 is met by 9... Bxh2+ and then Qxd5.}) (8. c3 Nf6 9. Nd2 Bd6 10. Nf1 Ne7 11. Ng3 Bd7 12. O-O O-O $11 {[%cal Ge7g6]}) 8... h6 $5 {Maybe Black can also play Nf6 but White can strike in the center with c4, so I like this move 8...h6 which also frees the h7-square against a potential g4 move.} 9. O-O (9. f3 Qh4+ 10. g3 Nxg3 11. Ng2 Qh3 12. Nf4 Qh4 $11) (9. Nd2 Nf6 10. c3 Bd6 11. Nf1 Ne7 12. Ng3 O-O $11 {Giving up the bishop on f5 is fine in this case as our knight will attack the e3-bishop and Black's pieces are quite active in general.}) 9... Qd7 {Preparing 0-0-0.} 10. Nd2 (10. f3 Nf6 11. a3 {11.Nc3 can be unpleasant due to Nb4, so it's better to prevent it.} O-O-O 12. Nc3 Re8 13. Bf2 h5 $11 {Black has counterplay and has ideas like h4 and Bd6 in mind at some point.}) 10... Nf6 {Exchanging on d2 helps White develop, so it's better to retreat.} 11. Nf3 (11. c4 Bd6 $1 {Developing and putting pressure on the d4-pawn.} 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. cxd5 Nb4 14. Qb3 Nxd5 {The knight is immune to capture due to Bxh2+.} 15. Qxb7 O-O $44 {With great compensation when Black is intending moves like Rab8 targeting the b2-pawn, and also Nxe3 is possible.}) 11... Bd6 12. Bb5 {White wants to play Ne5 but it's not very dangerous.} O-O 13. Ne5 Qe8 14. Re1 Bxe5 15. Bd2 Ne4 16. dxe5 a6 17. Bxc6 (17. Bd3 Qd7 18. f3 Nxd2 19. Qxd2 Rae8 $11) 17... Qxc6 18. Be3 Rad8 $11) (5. Nc3 Nf6 {I prefer this move as the knight on d3 is a bit awkward and White needs to spend time to move it and then to push d4.} (5... Nxc3 {This is also a solid option.} 6. dxc3 Be7 {This is similar to the main lines where White's knight would be on f3. Here, the knight on d3 doesn't stand better in comparison.} 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 Nd7 9. O-O-O Nf6 $11) 6. Nf4 d5 7. d4 Be7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. h3 (9. O-O Re8 10. Qf3 c6 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7f8] This is similar.}) 9... c6 10. Qf3 Nbd7 11. O-O Re8 $11 {[%cal Gd7f8] The plan is very simple, intending Nf8-Ng6 next when the pawn structure is almost symmetrical, so Black is doing fine.}) 5... Qe7 6. Nf4 (6. b3 Nc6 7. Bb2 Bf5 8. Nc3 Nxc3 9. dxc3 O-O-O $11) (6. Nc3 Nxc3 7. dxc3 Qxe2+ {Black doesn't have any problems in the endgame.} 8. Bxe2 Nc6 9. Be3 Bd7 $11) (6. Na3 {The knight seems misplaced on a3 and will be restricted by Black's pawns.} d5 7. Nf4 c6 $11) 6... Nf6 {The simplest way to equalize immediately.} (6... Nc6 7. Nd5 Nd4 {This leads to a big theory where the game probably ends in a draw but Black needs to remember a lot, and it doesn't seem necessary to enter this line, so I prefer 6...Nf6.}) (6... c6 {Is another decent option.}) 7. d4 (7. Nc3 c6 {Again, the simpler choice.} (7... Nc6 $5 {Intending Nd4. This line is also possible to play, but there is some theory and Black needs to know how to continue.} 8. Nfd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Qxe2+ 10. Bxe2 Nd4 11. Nxc7+ (11. Bd1 Ne6 $11 {[%cal Gc7c6]}) 11... Kd8 12. Nxa8 Nxc2+ 13. Kd1 Nxa1 14. d3 (14. Bf3 Be6 15. b3 d5 16. Bb2 Nxb3 17. axb3 Kd7 18. Ke2 Bd6 19. Bxg7 Rxa8 $11) 14... Be6 15. Be3 Bxa2 16. Bxa7 d5 17. Bf3 Bb4 $11 {With all the pieces along the a-file, the position seems a bit weird, although the computer assesses it as equal.}) 8. d4 (8. f3 h5 $5 {This is an interesting move, preventing g2-g4 and preparing for an eventual endgame.}) 8... Qxe2+ {If 8...d5 9.Be3, so it's better to exchange the queens now.} 9. Bxe2 (9. Ncxe2 h5 {Black has different plans but I like this one, gaining more space on the kingside.} 10. Bd2 (10. h4 g6 {Is also fine for Black.}) 10... h4 11. f3 Na6 12. O-O-O Nc7 13. Re1 Be7 $11 {The position is quite solid for Black when the next moves can be Kf8, Bd7, and Ne6 in some order.}) 9... Bf5 10. Bd3 (10. Nd3 Na6 {Doesn't change much.}) 10... Bxd3 11. Nxd3 Kd7 $5 (11... Na6 {This is also possible, and the knight will go to a6 eventually.}) 12. f3 (12. Bg5 Be7 13. h4 Na6 $11) 12... Na6 13. Bd2 g6 14. Kf2 Bg7 15. Ne2 Nc7 $11) 7... Qxe2+ 8. Bxe2 Nc6 9. c3 d5 {The knight on c6 is restricted by White's pawns, but the plan is to play Nd8-Ne6 or Ne7-Ng6, intending to exchange more pieces.} 10. f3 {White intends to play g4 and to bring the king to f2.} (10. h4 Nd8 $5 {[%cal Gd8e6]} (10... h5 {Is also possible but it's not necessary.}) 11. h5 Bd6 12. Nd3 Ne6 $11 {The h5-pawn is not going anywhere as h5-h6 can be met by simply pushing g6.}) (10. Bf3 Ne7 11. O-O (11. h4 Bd7 12. O-O (12. h5 O-O-O {Black is fine.}) 12... O-O-O $11 {If White pushes h5, keep in mind that sometimes Black can also play the move g7-g5.}) 11... Bf5 12. Re1 O-O-O $11 {[%cal Ge7g6,Gf8d6]}) (10. g4 h6 11. f3 Nd8 {[%cal Gd8e6]} 12. Na3 c6 13. h4 Bd6 14. Nd3 h5 {This is good because Black will gain control over the f5-square.} 15. g5 Ng8 16. Bf4 Bxf4 17. Nxf4 Bf5 18. Kf2 Ne6 19. Bd3 Bxd3 20. Nxd3 Ne7 $11) 10... Nd8 11. Na3 (11. g4 c6 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gd8e6] Is similar.}) 11... c6 {Black doesn't want to exchange the dark-squared bishop for the knight on a3.} 12. Nc2 Bd6 $11 {[%cal Gd8e6,Ga7a5] The position remains playable for both sides as many pieces are still on the board. The pawn structure is symmetrical and Black doesn't have any weaknesses, so Black is doing fine.} *

