1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Qe2 {This move doesn't pose much problems to Black and it's not played too much nowadays. The main moves 5.d4, 5.Nc3 and even 5.Bd3 will be analyzed in the upcoming lessons.} Qe7 6. d3 (6. d4 {It doesn't make much sense to leave the knight on e4.} d5 (6... g6 $5 {Intending Bg7 is also interesting.}) 7. Bf4 (7. Nbd2 Nc6 8. c3 Bg4 $132 {[%cal Ge8c8]}) 7... Bf5 8. Nbd2 Nd7 9. O-O-O O-O-O $11) (6. g3 Nc6 7. Bg2 Bg4 8. O-O (8. Qe3 {This is similar.} d5 9. d3 Nc5 $11) 8... O-O-O 9. d3 d5 {Using the pin on the f3 knight.} 10. Qe3 Nc5 $11) (6. Nc3 Nxc3 7. dxc3 Qxe2+ 8. Bxe2 Nc6 9. Be3 Be7 10. O-O-O Bd7 $5 {Intending 0-0-0.} (10... O-O 11. Rhe1 Bf6 {0-1 (66) Kramnik,V (2800)-Caruana,F (2784) Berlin 2018 CBM 184 [Postny,E]}) 11. Nd4 O-O-O 12. Nxc6 (12. Rhe1 Ne5 $11) 12... Bxc6 13. Rhe1 {13...Bxg2 runs into 14.Rhg1 when the g7-pawn falls.} Rde8 $11) 6... Nf6 7. Bg5 (7. Be3 Nd5 $5 (7... Nc6 8. Nc3 {White's idea is to castle long, but 7...Nd5 immediately poses problems to White, attacking the bishop on e3.}) 8. Bg5 f6 9. Bd2 Nc6 $11) (7. Qxe7+ Bxe7 $11) (7. Nc3 Qxe2+ (7... Nc6 {Is also possible.}) 8. Bxe2 g6 {Esipenko continued well in the game below. Other options include:} (8... Be7) (8... Bd7 {Preventing Nb5.}) 9. Nb5 (9. O-O Bg7 10. Nb5 Kd8 $11 {[%cal Gh8e8,Gb8c6] 11.Ng5 is met by 11...Rf8.}) (9. Bd2 Bd7 10. O-O-O Bg7 $11 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gb8c6]}) 9... Na6 10. O-O (10. Bd2 Bg7 $11) 10... Bg7 11. c3 O-O 12. d4 Re8 13. Re1 Bd7 14. a4 Bf8 $11 {[%cal Gc7c6] ½- (55) ½ (55) Niemann,H (2734) -Esipenko,A (2691) Moscow 2025}) 7... Qxe2+ 8. Bxe2 Be7 {The structure is symmetrical and although White has one more developed piece in the position, it doesn't change much.} 9. Nc3 (9. O-O h6 10. Bd2 O-O $11) (9. c4 h6 10. Be3 Nc6 11. Nc3 Be6 12. d4 d5 $11) 9... h6 10. Be3 (10. Bxf6 $6 Bxf6 11. Nd5 Bd8 {[%csl Gc8,Gd8][%cal Gc7c6] Giving up the dark-squared bishop and handing over the bishop pair advantage can only favor Black.}) (10. Bf4 Nc6 11. O-O-O Be6 $11) (10. Bd2 O-O 11. O-O-O Nc6 12. d4 (12. Rdg1 Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5] White isn't really attacking so Black is fine.}) 12... Bd8 $5 {An interesting idea suggested by the computer, freeing the e7-square for the knight. Black can also consider playing b5 with Bb7, and also ideas like Ne7-Nd5.} (12... Be6 {Is also fine.}) 13. Rde1 a6 14. h3 b5 $11) (10. Bh4 Nc6 {[%cal Gc8d7] The bishop on h4 might be a bit awkward there as Black can consider playing g5 at any moment.}) 10... Nc6 11. h3 {Avoids Ng4 just in case.} Be6 12. O-O-O a6 13. a3 (13. d4 Nb4 {The knight will go to d5.}) (13. Nd4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 c5 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Bf3 O-O-O $11) 13... O-O-O 14. d4 d5 15. Ne5 {And now Black can exchange some pieces after:} (15. Rhe1 Bd6 $11) (15. Bd3 Bd6 $11) 15... Nxe5 16. dxe5 Ne4 17. Nxe4 dxe4 $11 *

