1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. c4 {The idea of this move is to take d5 under control. However, the tempo spent on c4 allows Black to get a good game.} Be7 ({Another good option is} 5... Nc6 $5) 6. d4 (6. d3 Ng5 {This is one of the points of playing ...Be7 - Black has the option to play ... Ng5 in reply to d3. Exchanging pieces simplifies Black's task.} (6... Nf6 {is also decent.}) 7. Nxg5 (7. Be2 Nc6 8. d4 Nxf3+ 9. Bxf3 Bf6 10. Be3 O-O 11. Nc3 Ne7 {The knight is going to f5 giving Black sufficient counterplay.} 12. Ne4 Nf5 $11) 7... Bxg5 8. Bxg5 Qxg5 9. Qd2 Qe5+ 10. Be2 Nc6 11. Nc3 Nd4 {White cannot achieve anything.} 12. O-O O-O 13. Rae1 Be6 $11) (6. Be2 Nc6 7. O-O (7. d3 Nf6 8. d4 d5 {With this, Black gets a comfortable version of a position with an IQP. For example} 9. Nc3 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Bg4 11. O-O O-O 12. Be3 Qd7 $11) 7... O-O 8. d3 (8. Nc3 Nxc3 9. dxc3 Bf5 $11 {[%cal Gf8e8]}) 8... Nf6 (8... Ng5 9. d4 Nxf3+ 10. Bxf3 Bf6 11. Be3 Ne7 12. Nc3 Nf5 $11 {This is similar to 6.d3 Ng5.}) 9. Nc3 d5 $11 {Black has no problems.}) (6. Nc3 Nxc3 7. dxc3 {Compared to the line 5.Nc3 Nxc3 6.dxc3, White has better control of d5, but Black has good development.} O-O 8. Bd3 Nd7 {White can play with castling kingside, which is harmless or castling queenside, which gives Black good counterplay.} 9. Be3 (9. Qc2 g6 {[%cal Gd7c5]} 10. Bh6 Re8 11. O-O Nc5 $11) (9. O-O Nc5 10. Bc2 Bf6 $11) 9... Nc5 10. Bc2 Re8 11. Qd2 (11. O-O Bf6 $11) 11... Bf8 12. O-O-O Ne4 13. Qe2 g6 $11) 6... d5 (6... Nc6 $5 {is also interesting:} 7. Bd3 (7. d5 Ne5) 7... Ng5) 7. Nc3 {This is the main continuation. Other moves fail to pose any problems:} (7. cxd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3 (8. Bd3 Bb4+ {is similar to 7.Bd3 Bb4+. White has to acquiesce to exchanges or give up his castling right.}) 8... Nxc3 (8... Bb4 {is another sufficient continuation.} 9. Bd2 Bxc3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Be2 c5 12. O-O Bg4 $11) 9. bxc3 c5 {The most direct way to play.} 10. Bb5+ (10. Qb3 Qe4+ 11. Be3 O-O $11) 10... Bd7 11. Be2 cxd4 12. O-O Nc6 13. Nxd4 O-O 14. Bf3 Qc4 $11 {White has enough activity to compensate for his isolated c-pawn, but not more than that.}) (7. Bd3 Bb4+ $1 {Even if Black loses a tempo by playing this, the check is unpleasant for White.} 8. Nbd2 (8. Kf1 {is playable, but also a bit risky for White.} c6 9. h4 h6 10. Qb3 Ba5 11. Qa3 Bf5 $132) (8. Bd2 Nxd2 9. Nbxd2 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Qe7+ 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O Nc6 $11 {Black has the pair of bishops and a comfortable position.}) 8... O-O 9. O-O Bf5 10. a3 (10. Nb3 dxc4 11. Bxc4 Nc6 $11 {0-1 (33) Caruana, F (2727)-Giri,A (2714) Reggio Emilia 2011. Black is doing fine. In this structure, White's knight would rather prefer to be on c3 than on b3.}) 10... Bxd2 11. Bxd2 Nxd2 12. Qxd2 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 dxc4 14. Qxc4 Nd7 $11 {We have an IQP position with only one pair of minor pieces left on the board. Only Black can hope for an advantage.}) (7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O dxc4 9. Bxc4 Nd6 {Black has good game, for example} 10. Be2 ({or} 10. Bb3 Bg4 {[%cal Gg4d1]} 11. Nc3 Nc6 $11) 10... Bf6 11. Nc3 Nc6 12. h3 Re8 13. Bf4 Bf5 $11) 7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 c5 $5 {A rare but good continuation! Black immediately attacks the centre.} (8... O-O {was played in the majority of games.}) 9. Bd3 $146 (9. cxd5 Qxd5 {transposes to 7.cxd5.}) (9. dxc5 Bf6 10. Nd4 O-O 11. Be2 dxc4 12. O-O Nd7 $11) 9... cxd4 $1 {The most reliable way to equality.} (9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 O-O 11. O-O {may offer a tiny advantage to White.}) 10. Nxd4 (10. cxd4 O-O 11. O-O Nc6 12. Re1 Be6 {I like this best. Black provokes c5 after which he will create counterplay against d4.} (12... dxc4 13. Bxc4 Bg4 14. d5 Nb4 15. Bb2 Bf6 {is another decent, more complicated line.}) 13. c5 Bg4 14. Be3 Bf6 15. h3 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Bxd4 17. Bxd4 Nxd4 {White can regain the pawn with} 18. Bxh7+ Kxh7 19. Qd3+ Kg8 20. Qxd4 {, when Black keeps equality. A possible continuation is} Rc8 21. Re5 Qf6 22. Rae1 ({or} 22. Qxd5 Rfd8 23. Qe4 Rxc5 $11) 22... Rfd8 23. g3 b6 24. cxb6 axb6 $11) 10... dxc4 11. Bxc4 O-O 12. O-O {White is slightly ahead in development, while Black can claim to have the better pawn structure.} Bd7 {[%cal Gb8c6]} 13. Rb1 Nc6 14. Bd5 {This leads to multiple exchanges resulting in an equal position.} (14. Rxb7 $2 Na5) (14. Bf4 Rc8 $11) 14... Nxd4 15. Qxd4 Bf6 16. Qe4 Bc6 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Qxc6 Qa5 $11 {[%csl Ra2,Rc3][%cal Gf8c8] Black regains the pawn.} *

