1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Bd3 {This unusual continuation has become popular again. By directly attacking the knight on e4 White hopes to force some kind of concession.} Nf6 {The simplest answer, leading to quite an easy game for Black.} (5... d5 $5 {is a topical way to play.} 6. Qe2 Be7 7. Bxe4 dxe4 8. Qxe4 O-O 9. O-O c5 $44 {Black has reasonable long-term compensation for the sacrificed pawn.}) 6. O-O Be7 7. Re1 (7. c3 {White prepares d4, followed by Bc2.} O-O 8. h3 {If White does not prevent ...Bg4, Black has an easy game:} (8. Bc2 Bg4 9. d4 Re8 10. h3 ({or} 10. Re1 d5 11. Bg5 Nbd7 12. Nbd2 c6 $11) 10... Bh5 11. Re1 d5 {Black has no problems; for example} 12. Bf4 Bd6 13. Rxe8+ Nxe8 14. Bxd6 Nxd6 $11) 8... d5 {This is one of the good moves available.} 9. Bc2 h6 10. d4 Bd6 {We have a symmetrical pawn structure with a slight lead in development for White. Black keeps the balance without much trouble.} 11. Re1 (11. Nbd2 Re8 12. Re1 Rxe1+ 13. Qxe1 Nc6 14. Ne5 Ne7 {[%cal Gc8f5]} 15. Ndf3 Bf5 16. Bxf5 Nxf5 17. Qe2 Qe8 $11) (11. Ne5 c5 12. Bf4 Nc6 13. Re1 Re8 14. Nd2 (14. Nxc6 Rxe1+ 15. Qxe1 bxc6 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 $11) 14... cxd4 15. Nxc6 Rxe1+ 16. Qxe1 bxc6 17. Bxd6 Qxd6 18. cxd4 Qb4 (18... c5 {getting rid of the backward c-pawn, is also good.}) 19. Nb3 Qxe1+ 20. Rxe1 Rb8 {White's pawn structure is a little better, but Black has sufficient counterplay to keep the balance. A possible continuation:} 21. Bd3 Kf8 22. Rc1 Rb6 23. Rc5 Nh5 {[%cal Gh5f4]} 24. Ra5 Nf4 25. Bf1 a6 26. f3 g5 $11) 11... Re8 12. Rxe8+ (12. Ne5 c5 {[%cal Gb8c6]}) 12... Qxe8 13. Be3 Nc6 14. Nbd2 Ne7 15. Nh4 {1-0 (67) So,W (2771)-Caruana,F (2758) Saint Louis 2022} Be6 16. Qf3 Qb5 17. Rb1 Nh7 $11) (7. h3 O-O {will transpose to 7.Re1 or 7.c3 after 8.Re1 or 8. c3.}) 7... O-O 8. Bf1 (8. h3 d5 9. c3 (9. Bf1 c5 $5 {[%cal Gb8c6] Similarly to the line after 8.Bf1, Black can go for a position with an IQP and active piece play.} 10. d4 Nc6 11. Nc3 h6 12. dxc5 Bxc5 $11 {[%cal Gc8f5]}) 9... Re8 (9... Bd6 {leads to similar play.}) 10. Bc2 Bd6 11. d4 Nbd7 12. Rxe8+ Qxe8 13. Be3 Nf8 14. Nbd2 Ng6 $11) (8. c3 d5 9. Bc2 (9. h3 {transposes.}) 9... Bg4 10. d4 Bd6 (10... Re8 {is another good move.}) 11. Bg5 Nbd7 12. h3 (12. Nbd2 c6) 12... Bh5 13. Nbd2 c6 $11) 8... d5 9. d4 c5 $5 {I prefer this active move in the spirit of the French Defence. Black goes for a position with free development and active piece play in return for the Isolated Queen's Pawn.} ({Other decent moves are:} 9... Be6) (9... h6) (9... Nc6) 10. dxc5 (10. Bg5 {Black is well equipped to deal with this pin.} h6 11. Bh4 Nc6 12. dxc5 (12. Nc3 {leads to a good structure for Black after} c4 $1 13. Ne5 Be6 $11) 12... Bxc5 13. Nc3 g5 $1 {This is best, though Black needs to know his way after 14.Nxg5.} 14. Bg3 (14. Nxg5 Ng4 $1 {This forces a repetition of moves. Accepting the piece sacrifice would be too dangerous.} 15. Nf3 Qxh4 $1 16. Nxh4 Nxf2 17. Qf3 Nh3+ 18. Kh1 Nf2+ $11) 14... Bf5 15. a3 (15. Bd3 Ne4 $1 {This pawn sacrifice offers Black sufficient counterplay.} 16. Bxe4 dxe4 17. Nxe4 Qxd1 18. Raxd1 Bxe4 19. Rxe4 f5 20. Rc4 Rad8 21. Rxd8 Rxd8 22. Kf1 Rd1+ $1 23. Ke2 Rd5 24. Bc7 Bf8 $44 {[%csl Rc7] White's bishop will remain in trouble since, if needed, Black can cut off its retreat by playing ...f4.}) 15... a6 16. Bd3 (16. b4 Ba7 17. b5 axb5 18. Nxb5 Bc5 19. Bc7 Qd7 20. Ne5 Nxe5 21. Bxe5 Ne4 22. Bd4 Rfc8 $11) 16... Ne4 $1 {The same pawn sacrifice as after 15.Bd3 Ne4 - it also works here.} 17. Nxe4 dxe4 18. Bxe4 Bxe4 19. Rxe4 f5 20. Rc4 Be7 21. Qxd8 Raxd8 22. Bc7 Rd5 23. a4 {This time White has a slightly improved version of the line beginning with 15.Bd3. However, it's not enough to gain an advantage.} Bc5 24. a5 Re8 25. Kf1 (25. Bb6 Bxb6 26. axb6 Re4 27. Rc3 Rb4 $11) 25... Kf7 $11 {[%csl Rc7] Again, Black's counterplay is sufficient. If White's bishop goes to b6, Black takes and immediately attacks the b6-pawn with his rook.}) (10. c3 Nc6 11. dxc5 ({If} 11. Be3 {, then} c4 {is fine for Black.} 12. Nbd2 Be6 13. Ne5 Qc7 14. Bf4 (14. f4 Rae8 $132 {[%cal Ge7d6,Gc6e7]}) 14... Bd6 $11) 11... Bxc5 12. Be3 Bxe3 13. Rxe3 Qb6 {This secures enough counterplay. Black has no problem achieving equality in the ending after} 14. Qb3 Qxb3 15. axb3 Rd8 {[%cal Gd5d4]} 16. Na3 d4 $1 {Black gets rid of the isolated pawn before White can take d4 under control with Nc2.} 17. Nxd4 Nxd4 18. cxd4 Rxd4 19. Nb5 Rd2 20. Re2 Rd8 21. Nc7 Rb8 22. Rxa7 Rd1 23. Nb5 Be6 24. Nc3 Rd4 $11 {[%csl Rb3]}) (10. Nc3 h6 11. Bf4 (11. Be3 c4 12. b3 Bb4 13. Bd2 Nc6 14. bxc4 dxc4 $11 {[%csl Rd4]}) 11... Nc6 $11 {Black will continue with ...Bg4, or ...Bf5 in case White prevents it.}) 10... Bxc5 11. Nc3 (11. Be3 Bxe3 12. Rxe3 Nc6 13. c3 {tranpsoses to the main line.}) 11... h6 12. Be3 Bxe3 13. Rxe3 Nc6 {White has different attempts to exploit Black's IQP, but each time there's sufficient counterplay.} 14. Ne2 (14. Nd4 Ng4 15. Rg3 (15. Rf3 Qd6) 15... Qf6 $132) (14. Nb5 Bg4 15. Nbd4 Qb6 $11) 14... Qb6 15. Rb3 Qd8 {[%csl Rb3]} 16. h3 (16. Ng3 Re8) 16... Na5 17. Rc3 Re8 18. Qd4 Nc6 19. Qa4 Bd7 20. Qa3 a5 21. Re3 Qb6 $11 {½-½ (27) Kastner,P (2194) -Minnecker,H (2073) ICCF email 2021} *

