1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d3 {With this continuation, the game transposes to the French Defence, Exchange Variation after} Nf6 6. d4 (6. Be2 d5 7. O-O Bd6 $11) 6... d5 {This position can arise via the move order 1. e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 exd5 4.Nf3 Nf6. I think that this is not very dangerous for Black, and we will equalise without too many difficulties.} ({Another options are:} 6... Be7 {, which is a bit passive, and}) (6... g6 $5 {which is a good alternative. White may have some chances for an advantage after} 7. Bb5+ $5 c6 8. Bd3 Bg7 9. O-O O-O {, though this is certainly playable for Black.}) 7. Bd3 (7. c4 Bb4+ $1 {We have encountered a similar situation in the line 5. c4, where Black plays first ...Be7 and ...Bb4+ a few moves later, thereby losing a tempo but still obtaining a good game! Here, Black is even better off since the bishop reaches b4 in one go.} 8. Nc3 (8. Bd2 Nc6 $11) 8... O-O 9. Be2 (9. Bd3 Bg4 $132) 9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 Nc6 11. O-O Bg4 12. Be3 Qd6 $11 {Black is already on the better side of equality.}) (7. Bg5 Be6 $5 {There are other options, but I prefer this one.} ({After} 7... h6 {Black has to be ready for} 8. Qe2+ Be6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Qb5+) (7... Bd6 {is a solid alternative.}) 8. Bd3 (8. Nbd2 h6 9. Be3 Bd6 10. Bd3 O-O $11) 8... h6 {Now is a good moment to go for ...h6, followed by ...g5.} 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 Ne4 11. O-O Nxg3 12. fxg3 Nd7 13. Nbd2 Bg7 14. c3 O-O $11 {[%cal Gc7c5]}) (7. h3 Bd6 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O {transposes.}) (7. Bb5+ {Provoking ...c6 does not seem to have much point.} c6 8. Bd3 Bd6 9. Qe2+ Be7 $5 ({or} 9... Qe7 10. Qxe7+ Kxe7 11. O-O Re8 $11) 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 Re8 12. Bg5 Be6 $11) (7. Nc3 Bd6 8. Nb5 Bb4+ 9. c3 Ba5 10. Bd3 (10. Qe2+ $6 Ne4) 10... c6 11. Na3 O-O 12. O-O Bc7 $11) 7... Bd6 (7... c5 $5 {in order to play with an isolated pawn has become popular of late.}) 8. Qe2+ {The only critical move.} (8. O-O {leads to equal positions with a symmetrical pawn structure.} O-O 9. Bg5 (9. h3 h6 10. Re1 (10. Nc3 Nc6 11. Nb5 Be7 12. Bf4 a6 $1 {It's useful to be aware of this resource!} 13. Nc3 ({The knight is trapped after} 13. Nxc7 $2 Ra7 $19 {[%csl Rc7]}) 13... Nb4 ({I prefer to avoid} 13... Bd6 14. Be5 {when White keeps some pressure.}) 14. Re1 Nxd3 15. Qxd3 Re8 16. Bg3 c6 $11) 10... Nc6 11. a3 (11. c3 Re8) 11... Ne7 $11 {[%cal Gc8f5]}) (9. Re1 Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 11. Bg5 Nbd7 12. Nbd2 Re8 13. Rxe8+ Qxe8 14. c4 dxc4 15. Nxc4 Qe6 $11) 9... Bg4 {Both sides develop their pieces to active squares - this leads to an equal game.} 10. Nbd2 h6 $5 11. Bh4 Re8 12. Re1 Nbd7 13. Rxe8+ Qxe8 14. c4 dxc4 15. Nxc4 Qe6 16. Ne3 Nd5 17. Nxg4 Qxg4 18. h3 Qe6 19. Qb3 Nf4 20. Bc4 Qf5 21. Bg3 Nb6 $11) 8... Be7 $5 {A rare move. Black argues that he will back some time by attacking White's queen after ...0-0, ...Re8, etc.} ({More popular are:} 8... Be6) (8... Qe7) 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 {White can also try other moves.} (10. c4 Nc6 $132) (10. Bg5 h6 11. Bh4 Re8 {Black is about to play ...Ne4.} 12. c3 (12. Nc3 Nc6 13. Rfe1 Bg4 {This potentially leads to mass simplifaction, resulting in a drawish endgame.} 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Qxe8+ Qxe8 16. Rxe8+ Rxe8 17. Nxd5 Bxf3 18. Nxf6+ gxf6 19. gxf3 Nxd4 $11) (12. Nbd2 c5 $132) 12... Ne4 {The simplest way.} (12... c5 $5 13. dxc5 Nbd7) 13. Bxe7 Rxe7 14. Re1 Bf5 $11) (10. Bf4 Re8 {[%cal Ge7d6]}) (10. Ne5 c5 11. c3 Re8 $132 {[%cal Gb8c6]} (11... Nc6 $132)) 10... Bd6 $1 {This may seem strange - Black is losing another tempo with his bishop. However, White cannot achieve anything tangible with his slight lead in development.} ({We should avoid} 10... Re8 11. Bg5 {with some pressure for White.}) 11. Bg5 (11. Qd1 {transposes to 8.0-0.}) (11. Nc3 Re8 (11... h6 {is also good.}) 12. Qf1 Rxe1 13. Qxe1 h6 14. Nb5 Nc6 15. Nxd6 Qxd6 16. c3 Bg4 $11) 11... h6 12. Bh4 g5 $1 {The right moment to break the pin.} (12... Nc6 {allows} 13. Qd2 $1 {, which prevents ...g5. White has the better game; for example} Nb4 14. Nc3 Nxd3 15. Qxd3 c6 16. h3 Be6 17. Re3 Be7 18. Rae1 Re8 19. Ne5 $14) 13. Bg3 Re8 14. Qd1 (14. Ne5 $2 Nc6 15. c3 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Bxe5 $1 17. Bxe5 Ng4 $17) (14. Qd2 {is similar to 14.Qd1, though after} Rxe1+ (14... Ne4 $5 15. Qd1 Nc6) 15. Nxe1 {is an independent try. Black has no trouble to keep equality in the following quiet positions.} Nc6 16. Bxd6 (16. c3 Ne4 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. Bxd6 Qxd6 19. Qe2 Bd7 20. Na3 Re8 $11 21. Nb5 Qf4 $1 22. g3 Bg4 $1 23. gxf4 Bxe2 24. Nxc7 Rd8 25. Ng2 Ne7 $44) 16... Qxd6 17. c3 Ne7 18. Na3 (18. Qc2 b6 19. b4 (19. Nd2 c5) 19... Be6 20. Nd2 Rc8 $11) 18... Bf5 19. Nac2 Ne4 20. Qe2 Re8 21. Ne3 Qe6 22. N1c2 (22. Nxf5 Nxf5) 22... Bg6 $11) 14... Rxe1+ 15. Qxe1 (15. Nxe1 {can also be tried with the queen on d1.} c5 (15... Bg4 $5 {also leads to a roughly equal position after} 16. Qd2 Nc6 17. Bxd6 Qxd6 18. c3 Ne7 {[%cal Gg4f5]}) 16. Bxd6 (16. dxc5 Bxc5 17. Nc3 Nc6 18. Nf3 Be6 $11) 16... Qxd6 17. dxc5 Qxc5 18. Nc3 Nc6 19. Qd2 Kg7 20. Nf3 {Here, some accuracy is necessary on Black's part. White has the more compact pawn structure and Black must use his dynamic resources to keep equality.} Bg4 $1 (20... g4 $6 21. Nh4 $14) 21. Nxg5 Ne5 $1 22. Qf4 (22. h3 Bh5) (22. Be2 Bxe2 23. Qxe2 Re8 24. Nh3 d4 25. Ne4 Ned7 $1 26. Nxc5 Rxe2 27. Nd3 Rxc2 $11) 22... Qd6 $1 {The point of Black's last move - the threat of ...Nf3+ leads to forcing play, resulting in equality.} 23. Nb5 (23. Nh3 Re8 $44) 23... Qb8 24. Nh3 Bxh3 25. gxh3 Nxd3 26. Qxb8 Rxb8 27. cxd3 Rc8 28. Nxa7 Rc2 29. b4 Nh5 30. a4 Nf4 $11) 15... Nc6 {Black will equalise soon after playing a few accurate moves.} 16. c3 Nh5 17. Bxd6 (17. Nbd2 {1-0 (74) Kollars,D (2649)-Gokerkan,C (2473) Eforie Nord 2025} Nxg3 18. fxg3 Qe7 $11) 17... Qxd6 18. g3 (18. Qe8+ Kg7 $11 {...Nf4 and ...Qe7 are about to follow.}) 18... Bh3 19. Bf1 (19. Nbd2 Nf6 $11) 19... Bxf1 20. Qxf1 Ne7 21. Nbd2 (21. Na3 c6 $11) 21... Ng7 22. a4 c6 23. Nb3 Nef5 $11 {Riccio,E (2588)-Kruse,H (2506) FICGS email 2021.} *

