1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 {After covering the rarer options on move five, we turn to the main lines. 5.Nc3 is White's most popular continuation besides 5.d4.} Nxc3 6. dxc3 {In this lesson, we study less common ways to play for White.} ({The capture with the b-pawn} 6. bxc3 {poses no problems at all.} Be7 7. d4 O-O 8. Bd3 Re8 (8... d5 {is also possible.} 9. O-O c5 10. dxc5 Nd7 $11) 9. O-O Nd7 10. Re1 b6 $11 {[%cal Gc8b7]}) 6... Be7 7. Bd3 {Here, we look at lines in which White goes for castling kingside. These are quite harmless - Black gets a good game with logical developing moves.} (7. Bc4 O-O 8. O-O (8. Be3 {transposes to the next lessons.}) 8... Nc6 9. Re1 Bf6 10. Bf4 Bf5 $11) 7... O-O 8. O-O (8. Be3 {transposes to the next lessons.}) 8... Nd7 {[%cal Gd7c5] Black is going to attack the bishop on d3 with his knight.} (8... Nc6 9. Re1 Bf6 {is also OK.}) 9. Be3 (9. Re1 Nc5 10. Bc4 (10. Bf1 Re8 11. Be3 Be6 12. Nd4 Bd7 $11) 10... Be6 (10... c6 $5 {[%cal Gd6d5]}) 11. Bxe6 Nxe6 $11) 9... Nc5 (9... Re8 10. Re1 Bf6 {is fine too.}) 10. Bxc5 (10. Bc4 Be6 11. Bxe6 Nxe6 $11) 10... dxc5 {Black has the pair of bishops, while White is slightly ahead in development.} 11. Re1 (11. Ne5 Bd6 $11) (11. Qe2 Bd6) 11... g6 12. Qe2 (12. Ne5 Bd6 $11 {[%cal Gc8e6]}) 12... Bd6 13. Nd2 (13. Rad1 Kg7 {is similar to the main line.}) 13... Kg7 $5 {This is not the only move, but I like it: Black quietly improves his position. One point is that 14.Ne4 can now be met 14...Re8!} 14. g3 (14. Ne4 Re8 15. Qf3 Be6 16. Bb5 (16. Nxd6 Qxd6 $11 {The game is equal. Taking on b7 is not a good idea:} 17. Qxb7 $6 Rab8 $15) 16... c6 17. Red1 {Black can equalise in two different ways:} Bg4 (17... Bd5 18. Rxd5 Bxh2+ 19. Kxh2 Qxd5 20. Bd3 c4 21. Qf6+ Kf8 22. Qh8+ Ke7 23. Qf6+ $11) 18. Qxg4 f5 19. Qg5 Rxe4 20. Qxd8 Rxd8 $11) 14... Bd7 {Both sides have completed the development - the position is equal.} 15. Qf3 Rb8 ({Also good is} 15... b5 $11) 16. Nc4 Be6 17. Rad1 Qf6 18. Qxf6+ Kxf6 19. Nxd6 cxd6 20. Be4 Rfd8 $11 {½- (24) ½ (24) Mirkowski,P (2356)-Sorcnik,K (2318) ICCF email 2016} *

