1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Be7 7. Bf4 {This was, at some point, White's main move. Now, it has been superseded by 7. Be3.} Nd7 {I like this best: by developing the knight before castling, Black reduces White's options.} (7... O-O {can lead the same positions.}) 8. Qd2 {Thanks to the knight being on d7, Black can immediately get a good game after 8.Bd3 and 8.Bc4.} (8. Bd3 Nc5 9. Bc4 c6 $11 {[%cal Gd6d5]}) (8. Bc4 Nb6 $1 {Now both retreats with the bishop have their drawbacks.} 9. Bd3 (9. Bb3 a5 10. a4 O-O $132 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gd6d5] This is quite good for Black - he may shut out the bishop on b3 with ...d5.}) 9... Na4 $5 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Ga4b2] Very annoying - White won't manage to castle queenside after this.} 10. Bb5+ (10. Qc1 O-O) 10... Bd7 11. Bxa4 Bxa4 $11) 8... O-O 9. O-O-O (9. Bc4 Re8 {We can probably play other moves as well; however, after} 10. O-O-O {we transpose to the main line.}) (9. h4 Re8 10. O-O-O {also transposes.}) (9. Bd3 Nc5 $11 {[%cal Gc5d3]}) 9... Re8 $5 {I like this rare continuation. Black plays a useful move, waiting for White to show his hand.} (9... Nc5 {is the main theoretical line.}) 10. Bc4 (10. h4 h6 $1 {A good reply - White won't be able to exploit the hook created by ...h6.} (10... Nc5 {is also possible.}) 11. Bc4 {White has a lot of options on move eleven - Black is doing great in every case:} ({Black has good counterplay after} 11. g4 Nc5 {with ideas of ...Bxg4 and ...Ne4.} 12. g5 (12. Rg1 Ne4 13. Qe2 d5 $15) (12. Bc4 d5 $1 13. Bxd5 c6 14. Bc4 Qxd2+ 15. Bxd2 b5 16. Bf1 Ne4 17. Be3 Bxg4 18. Bg2 Rac8 $15) 12... Bg4 13. Bg2 (13. Be2 h5) 13... h5 14. Rde1 c6 15. Nd4 g6 $15) (11. Rg1 $6 {Here, Black can take on h4 when White struggles to prove sufficient compensation.} Bxh4 $1 12. g4 (12. Rh1 Bf6 $17 {[%cal Gd7f8]}) 12... Ne5 $1 13. Nxh4 Qxh4 14. Be2 Qxf2 15. Rdf1 Qb6 16. Kb1 Ng6 17. Bd3 Be6 $15) (11. Nd4 $6 {is another dubious move, allowing Black to take on h4.} Bxh4 $1 {The following sacrifice does not work, but otherwise Black would be much better.} 12. Bxh6 (12. g4 Ne5 $17) (12. Nf5 Bg5 $17) 12... gxh6 13. Nf5 Bg5 14. Nxh6+ (14. f4 Nc5 $19) 14... Kf8 15. f4 Bxh6 16. Rxh6 Nf6 $19) (11. Re1 Nc5 12. Nd4 Bf6 $132 (12... Bd7 $132)) (11. h5 Nc5 $15 {[%cal Ge7f6,Gc5e4]}) (11. Bd3 Nc5 12. Ng5 (12. Rdg1 $6 Bg4 13. Nh2 Be6 14. g4 Qd7 $17) (12. Bc4 Bf6 $1 13. Be3 Ne4 14. Qd3 Qe7 $15 {[%cal Gc8g4]}) 12... Qd7 $5 (12... Nxd3+ 13. Qxd3 g6 14. Ne4 Bf8 $11) 13. Bc4 (13. Bh7+ Kh8) 13... Bxg5 14. hxg5 Ne4 15. Qd5 Qf5 16. Qxf5 Bxf5 {[%cal Ge4f2]} 17. Bd3 Bg6 $11) (11. Be2 Nc5 $132) 11... Nb6 $1 12. Bd3 ({The light-squared bishop becomes a target after} 12. Bb3 $6 Bf8 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gc7c5,Gc5c4]}) 12... Bf8 {Black has quite an active game:} 13. Nd4 (13. Rhe1 Bg4 $132 {[%csl Gg4]}) (13. Ng5 $2 {This typical sacrifice is not correct at this point.} hxg5 14. hxg5 g6 15. Rh4 Bg7 16. Rdh1 Qe7 $19) (13. Rdg1 Bg4 14. Nh2 Be6 15. g4 Nc4 $15 {Black is doing great - g5 is always met with ...h5.}) 13... Bd7 {Black is about to continue with ...c5, ...d5, etc.} (13... Na4 $5) 14. g4 (14. Nf5 d5 15. g4 c5 {transposes.}) 14... c5 15. Nf5 d5 16. Bxh6 {The major complications arising from this turn out to be in Black's favour.} (16. Rhg1 Na4 $1 $132) 16... c4 $1 17. Bg5 Qc7 18. Be2 Na4 $40 {Black's counterplay on the queenside is very dangerous. A possible continuation:} 19. Be3 Bxf5 20. gxf5 Rxe3 $1 21. Qxe3 (21. fxe3 Qb6 {[%csl Rb2]} 22. b4 Bc5 $1 23. Rh3 a5 $1 $17 {Black has a vicious attack.}) 21... Bc5 22. Qd2 Qb6 23. b3 d4 $1 24. Rh3 $1 {This allows White to hold, though holding a worse endgame is all he can dream about...} cxb3 25. axb3 Nxc3 26. Rxc3 Qa5 27. Kb1 dxc3 28. Qg5 Qa3 29. Qc1 Qxc1+ 30. Rxc1 Re8 31. Bd3 (31. Bf3 b6) 31... Bxf2 32. Rh1 $15) (10. Kb1 {White plays a useful move. Now Black goes for} Nc5 {giving him good prospects.} 11. Bc4 (11. Be3 c6 {is already quite good for Black.} (11... Ne4 $5 12. Qc1 Bd7 {is another possible continuation.}) 12. Be2 Qc7 $132) (11. Re1 Bd7 $11) 11... Bf6 {[%cal Gc5e4] Creating the threat of ...Ne4.} (11... Be6 {leads to an equal game.} 12. Bxe6 Nxe6 13. Be3 Qd7 14. Qd5 (14. h4 Qc6) 14... c6 15. Qf5 g6 16. Qd3 d5 17. c4 Nc7 $11) (11... Bg4 $5) 12. h4 ({After} 12. Ng5 {Black can force an immediate draw with} Bxg5 13. Bxg5 Ne4 14. Bxd8 Nxd2+ 15. Rxd2 Rxd8 16. Re1 Kf8 $11) (12. Be3 Ne4 13. Qd5 Re7 $11) (12. Rhe1 Be6 13. Bxe6 Rxe6 14. Rxe6 Nxe6 15. Be3 Qe7 $11) 12... Bg4 (12... Bf5 {is also sufficient for equality.} 13. Ng5 Bxg5 14. Bxg5 Qd7 $11) (12... Ne4 $5 {is a sharper alternative.} 13. Qd5 Qe7 14. Ng5 Bxg5 15. Bxg5 c6 $1 16. Qd3 Qe5 17. Qf3 Be6 18. Bf4 Qc5 $11) 13. Ng5 Bxg5 14. Bxg5 Qd7 15. f3 Be6 16. Bxe6 Rxe6 $11 {Black has no problems.}) (10. Nd4 Ne5 $1 {[%csl Ge5] White has given up control of e5 and Black immediately takes advantage of this - the knight is very well placed in the centre.} ({White's point was to meet} 10... Nc5 {with} 11. f3) 11. Be2 (11. f3 $6 {This is too slow.} a6 12. Kb1 (12. g4 $6 Ng6 13. Be3 (13. Bg3 $2 Bxg4 $1 {[%cal Ge7g5]}) 13... Bh4 $1 14. Nf5 Bf6 (14... Bxf5 15. gxf5 Ne5 $15) 15. f4 Ne7 $17) 12... c5 13. Nb3 Qc7 $15) (11. Kb1 a6) 11... Bd7 12. Kb1 (12. Rhe1 a6) 12... a6 {Black prepares ...c5 or ...b5, with good counterplay.} 13. Rhe1 h6 $5 (13... Bf8) (13... Bf6) 14. h3 Bf6 15. g4 Rb8 16. a3 b5 $132) (10. Bd3 {is well met with} Nc5 11. Bc4 Qd7 $5 {[%cal Gd7f5,Gd7a4] - Black has active counterplay.} (11... Be6 12. Bxe6 Nxe6 13. Be3 Qd7 $11) (11... Bg4 $5) 12. Qd5 {Inviting some simplification, resulting in comfortable equality for Black.} (12. Rhe1 Qa4 13. Bd5 Bf5 14. Nd4 Bg6 15. Kb1 c6 16. Bf3 d5 $132 {looks very good for Black.}) 12... Qf5 13. Qxf5 Bxf5 $11) (10. Be2 {Not very ambitious; Black can equalise in several ways:} Nc5 11. Rhe1 Bf8 (11... Ne4 $5 12. Qe3 Bf8 13. Bd3 Nf6 14. Qd2 Bg4 $11) (11... Bf6 $11) 12. Bc4 Rxe1 13. Rxe1 h6 14. Be3 Be6 15. Bxe6 Nxe6 $11) (10. Re1 {White makes a useful waiting move.} Nc5 11. Bc4 (11. Nd4 Bd7 12. f3 c6 {[%cal Gb7b5] with the idea to start an attack with ...b5, leads to a double-edged game.} (12... h6 $5) 13. h4 b5 14. g4 a5 15. g5 b4 16. c4 Qb6 17. h5 a4 $132) (11. h4 h6 $1 {We have already seen this motif - Black takes g5 under control while it's not easy to exploit the weakness created by ...h6.} 12. Nd4 Bd7 13. Bc4 (13. f3 $2 {does not give enough compensation for the pawn after} Bxh4 $1 14. Rxe8+ Bxe8 15. Nf5 Bf6 $1 16. Bxh6 (16. Bc4 Bd7 17. g4 Bxf5 18. gxf5 Qd7 $17) (16. g4 Bd7 $17) 16... gxh6 17. Nxh6+ Kf8 18. Nf5 {This may appear dangerous, yet Black is much better after the precise} Bc6 $1 {, when the Black king escapes to the queenside.} 19. Bc4 (19. Qh6+ Ke8 20. Qh7 a6 $5 {...Kd7 was possible but this is even better.} 21. Bc4 Kd7 22. Qxf7+ Kc8 23. f4 Be8 24. Qg8 Kb8 $19) (19. Rh7 Ne6 20. Kd1 Be5 21. Qh6+ Ke8 22. Qh5 Qf6 $19) (19. Kb1 Ke8 20. Rh7 Bd7 21. Qe3+ Be6 $19) 19... d5 20. Bd3 Ke8 21. f4 Kd7 22. Rh6 Ne6 $17) 13... c6 {[%cal Gd6d5]} 14. g4 d5 15. Bd3 Bf8 16. g5 h5 $15) 11... Be6 {A simple way to equalise.} (11... Bg4 $5 12. Ng5 Bxg5 13. Bxg5 Qd7 $11) 12. Bxe6 Nxe6 13. Be3 Qd7 $11) (10. h3 Nc5 {We get the main line with the insertion of h3 and ...Re8 which is probably in Black's favour.} 11. Bc4 {Black has different ways to get good play:} (11. g4 $6 Ne4 12. Qe1 Bf6 $15 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ge8e1]}) 11... Be6 (11... Qd7 $5 {[%cal Gd7a4]} 12. Qd5 {Since ...Qa4 is an annoying possibility, this is White's best move.} (12. Rhe1 $6 Qa4 13. Bd5 Be6 14. Qd4 Qxd4 15. Rxd4 c6 16. Bxe6 Nxe6 17. Rb4 Nxf4 18. Rxf4 d5 $15 {[%csl Rf4]}) 12... Qf5 13. Qxf5 Bxf5 14. Nd4 Bd7 $11) 12. Bxe6 Nxe6 13. Be3 Qd7 {[%cal Gd7c6]} 14. Qd3 Qc6 $11) 10... Nb6 $1 {Here we see the point of ...Re8 - Black has retained the option to hit the bishop with ...Nb6!} (10... Nc5 11. Be3 Be6 {would lead back to the main line with 9...Nc5.}) 11. Bd3 ({If} 11. Bb3 {then Black can immediately get exploit the position of the bishop to create direct threats.} c5 {[%cal Gc5c4] This leads to forcing play.} ({An alternative is} 11... Bg4 $5 12. h3 (12. Ng5 Bxg5 13. Bxg5 Qd7 $11) 12... Bxf3 13. gxf3 Bf8 $132) 12. c4 Be6 13. Bxd6 Nxc4 14. Bxc4 Bxc4 15. Qf4 Bxd6 16. Rxd6 Qc7 17. Rhd1 {A lot of pieces have been exchanged and after the forcing} Be2 {further simplifications are inevitable.} 18. R1d5 Bxf3 (18... Rad8 19. Qe3 Bxf3 20. Rxd8 Rxd8 21. Rxd8+ Qxd8 22. Qxf3 b6 $11) 19. Qxf3 Re1+ 20. Kd2 Re6 21. Rxe6 (21. Rd7 Qa5+) 21... fxe6 22. Rd3 Rf8 23. Qe3 Qa5+ 24. Rc3 Qxa2 25. Rxc5 Qxb2 26. Qxe6+ Kh8 27. Rc8 Qd4+ 28. Kc1 Qxf2 29. Qd7 $11) 11... Bg4 $1 12. h3 ({If} 12. h4 {[%csl Gg4] the bishop is very well placed on g4.} Qd7 13. Kb1 Na4 $5 14. Be3 Bf6 15. Bg5 Be7 $1 16. Be3 (16. Qf4 Nc5 17. Bc4 Qf5 $132) 16... Bf6 $11) 12... Bxf3 13. gxf3 d5 {[%cal Ge7f6] After ...Bf6 Black's king will be securely defended and there's potential counterplay on the queenside with ...Na4.} (13... Bf6 14. h4 d5 {leads back to 13...d5.}) (13... Qd7 $5) 14. h4 Bf6 {[%cal Gb6a4]} 15. h5 Na4 $5 {This can lead to interesting complications where Black gets his fair share of chances.} ({A solid alternative is} 15... c6 16. Rhg1 (16. Be3 Qd6 $11) 16... Nc4 17. Bxc4 dxc4 $11) 16. h6 (16. Rde1 Qd7 $11) (16. Bb5 Nxb2 $1 17. Kxb2 c6 18. Ba4 a5 $1 {[%csl Ra4]} 19. Rde1 Qb6+ 20. Kc1 Qc5 21. Rxe8+ Rxe8 22. Re1 Rd8 (22... Re7 $5 23. Rxe7 Bxe7) 23. Qe3 Qxe3+ 24. fxe3 b5 25. Bxb5 cxb5 $11) 16... g6 17. Bb5 Nxc3 (17... Nxb2 $5 18. Kxb2 c6 19. Ba4 a5 $44) 18. Bxe8 (18. bxc3 $6 c6) 18... Nxd1 19. Rxd1 Qxe8 20. Qxd5 Rd8 21. Qxb7 Rb8 22. Qe4 Bxb2+ 23. Kd2 Rd8+ 24. Ke2 Qxe4+ 25. fxe4 Rxd1 26. Kxd1 c6 $11 {Dunlop,G (2536)-Kluegel,J (2524) ICCF email 2021. Black is not worse in this endgame.} *

