1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Be7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 {In this lesson, we will study the most essential lines connected to 5. Nc3, which makes it one of the critical lines in the entire Petroff.} Nd7 9. O-O-O (9. h4 Nf6 10. O-O-O {transposes.}) 9... Nf6 ({Other good options are:} 9... c6) (9... Re8) 10. Bd3 (10. h4 {White is playing for a direct attack with Ng5.} Re8 11. Ng5 {[%cal Gf2f3,Gg2g4]} (11. Bd3 {transposes.}) 11... h6 (11... d5 {also leads to an unclear position after} 12. f3 c5 13. g4 Qa5 14. Kb1 Bf8 $13) 12. f3 {White can ignore the attack on the g5-knight since it would be too dangerous for Black to take it. However, it's not clear how White can create threats if Black ignores the knight.} (12. Bd3 $6 d5 {transposes.}) 12... c6 {A very useful move! Black prepares ...Nd5 while ...b5 also becomes possible.} 13. g4 (13. Bd3 $2 Nd5 $1 $17) 13... b5 ({Here, Black must avoid} 13... Nd5 $6 {due to} 14. Bc4 $36) 14. Re1 (14. Bd3 Nd5 15. Rde1 Nxe3 16. Rxe3 d5 $15) 14... Bd7 15. Bd3 Nd5 {Now, this is good since Bc4 is no longer possible.} 16. Bh7+ Kf8 17. Bd3 Nxe3 ({If Black wanted to, he could go for a repetition.} 17... Kg8 $11) 18. Nh7+ Kg8 19. Rxe3 Qb6 20. Re2 d5 {The knight on h7 makes a strange impression. White has enough resources to keep the balance but not more than that.} 21. g5 c5 22. Rhe1 c4 23. Rxe7 Rxe7 24. Rxe7 Be6 {[%csl Re7,Rh7]} 25. gxh6 Qg1+ 26. Qd1 Qe3+ 27. Qd2 Qg1+ $11) (10. c4 {is harmless; Black can simply play} Ne4 11. Qd5 (11. Qd3 Nc5) (11. Qd4 Nc5) 11... Nf6 $11) (10. h3 Re8 11. g4 (11. Kb1 Bd7 12. Bd3 c5 $1 $132 {[%cal Gd7c6] This is a recurring theme in these lines. Black prepares ...Bc6 and ...b5.}) (11. Bd3 {transposes to 10.Bd3.}) (11. Bc4 {is well met with} c6 {[%cal Gd6d5] , followed by ...d5. Most probably, Black will simply be a tempo up compared to some lines.}) 11... Bd7 12. Rg1 c5 {[%cal Gd7c6] Again, this typical idea - Black prepares ...Bc6.} 13. g5 Ne4 14. Qd5 Bc6 15. Qf5 Qc8 16. Qxc8 Raxc8 $132 {Black has activated his pieces; he is doing fine.}) (10. Bc4 {looks dubious since after} c6 {[%cal Gd6d5] followed by ...d5, Black will often be up a tempo compared to the main line.} 11. Bg5 (11. Rhe1 d5 12. Bd3 Re8 $11) 11... d5 12. Bd3 Re8 (12... h6 {is also possible because the sacrifice} 13. Bxh6 {is only good enough for a draw.} gxh6 14. Qxh6 Qd6 15. Qg5+ (15. Ng5 $2 Bf5 $1 {A nice refutation of White's play.} 16. Nxf7 Rxf7 17. Bxf5 Bf8 $17) 15... Kh8 16. Qh6+ $11) 13. Rhe1 Bg4 $11) 10... Re8 {I prefer this flexible move.} (10... c5 {is another big line.}) 11. Rhe1 (11. Bd4 {White point his two bishops against Black's king and enables the queen to come to d4.} d5 $1 {With this move Black secures an equal game.} 12. Qf4 (12. Rhe1 Bg4 $1 ({White has some pressure after} 12... c5 13. Be5) 13. Qf4 (13. h3 Bxf3 14. gxf3 c5 15. Be5 Bd6 16. f4 Qc7 $132) 13... Bd6 14. Qg5 h6 15. Rxe8+ Qxe8 16. Qh4 Qe6 17. Bxf6 (17. h3 Bxf3 18. gxf3 Be7 $11) 17... Bf4+ 18. Kb1 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Qxf6 20. Qxf6 gxf6 $11) (12. c4 Bg4 13. Bxf6 (13. cxd5 Qxd5) 13... Bxf6 14. Qf4 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Qd6 16. Qxd5 (16. cxd5 $6 b5 $1 {[%csl Rc1,Gf6]}) 16... Bxb2+ 17. Kxb2 Qb4+ $11) (12. Kb1 $6 Ne4 13. Qc1 f5 $15 {[%cal Gc7c5]}) 12... Bd6 {I like this best.} (12... h6 $5 13. Rhe1 Be6) (12... Nh5 $5 {is possible, though the positions after} 13. Bxh7+ Kxh7 14. Qxf7 Bg4 {are very complex.}) {After} 13. Qh4 {Black can force the exchange of queens with} Ne4 $1 {, securing an equal game.} 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. Rhe1 Bf4+ 16. Kb1 Nd6 17. h3 (17. g3 Bh6) 17... b6 18. b4 f6 19. g3 Bh6 $132) (11. a3 {White plays a useful move, waiting for Black to show his hand.} d5 12. c4 (12. Rhe1 Bg4 13. h3 Bxf3 14. gxf3 {0-1 (33) Gukesh,D (2720)-Moussard,J (2635) London 2023.} Bf8 15. Rg1 Qd6 $132 {is similar to the other lines.}) 12... c6 {Black is very solid, and he has not much to fear. A possible continuation:} 13. Rhe1 (13. Kb1 dxc4 14. Bxc4 Qxd2 15. Rxd2 b5 16. Bd3 (16. Ba2 c5 {[%csl Ra2]} 17. c4 a6 $132) 16... a6 $11) 13... Bg4 14. Bd4 c5 15. Be5 Bd6 16. Bg3 (16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. Rxe8+ Rxe8 18. cxd5 g6 19. Bf1 Bxf3 20. gxf3 Re5 21. c4 Rf5 $44 {Black has fully sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) 16... Rxe1 17. Rxe1 Bxg3 18. fxg3 dxc4 19. Bxc4 Qxd2+ 20. Kxd2 Rd8+ 21. Kc1 Rd7 {The endgame is equal.} 22. h3 (22. Ne5 Re7) 22... Bxf3 23. gxf3 Kf8 $11) (11. Kb1 {This is similar to 11.a3 - White plays a useful move.} d5 (11... Bd7 {is probably fine too.}) 12. c4 (12. Rhe1 Bg4 {transposes.}) (12. h3 c5 13. g4 Ne4 14. Qe2 Qc7 15. Rhe1 Bf8 $132) 12... dxc4 {Black is fine after the exchange of queens.} ({Keeping the tension with} 12... c6 {is also possible.}) 13. Bxc4 Qxd2 14. Bxd2 {The pawn structure is symmetrical - Black has no problems to keep the balance.} c6 ({Black is also fine after} 14... Bd6 15. Ng5 Rf8 16. Bc3 Bf5 $11) 15. Rhe1 (15. Ne5 Nd5 16. Rhe1 Be6 $11) 15... Bg4 16. Ne5 Bxd1 17. Bxf7+ Kf8 18. Bxe8 Bxc2+ 19. Kxc2 Rxe8 $11) (11. h4 d5 ({After} 11... Bg4 {White unpins the knight with} 12. Rde1 {, keeping one rook on the h-file for a possible attack.}) 12. c4 {White has a large number of possible continuations:} (12. Ng5 $6 {is well met with} h6 {when White struggles to justify the position of the knight on g5. Black can successfully meet any of White's attacking attempts:} 13. f3 (13. Bd4 hxg5 14. hxg5 Ne4 15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. f4 Qd6 17. Qf2 Qg6 18. g4 e3 $1 19. Qe2 Bd6 20. f5 Qxg5 21. Rh5 Qf4 22. Rdh1 f6 23. Qc4+ Kf8 24. Rh8+ Ke7 25. Rxe8+ Kxe8 26. b4 Ke7 (26... e2+ 27. Kb2) 27. Rh7 Qg5 28. Qe2 Bxf5 29. gxf5 Re8 30. Bxe3 Kd8 31. Bxg5 Rxe2 32. Bd2 Rg2 $15) (13. Kb1 c5 14. c4 Qc7 $1 15. Bf4 (15. cxd5 c4 16. Be2 Bd6 $17) 15... Bd6 $15) 13... c5 $1 14. g4 (14. Bb5 Rf8) 14... c4 $1 15. Bf1 (15. Be2 Bd6 16. Nh3 b5 $17 17. g5 $2 Nh5 $19) 15... b5 $1 16. Nxf7 (16. Kb1 Rb8 $1 {[%cal Gb5b4]}) 16... Kxf7 17. g5 Nh5 18. Bg2 Be6 19. f4 Ng3 20. Rhe1 Kg8 21. gxh6 Bf6 22. Bd4 Bf7 $17) (12. h5 h6 $1 {[%csl Rh5] Stopping the advance of the h-pawn is best. A possible bishops sacrifice on h6 does not work.} 13. g4 {White tries to use the hook created by ...h6.} (13. Bxh6 $2 Ne4 14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. Qe3 Bd6 $19) {After taking the pawn} 13... Nxg4 {Black has enough defensive resources and he obtains good chances.} 14. Bf4 Bc5 15. Nd4 Qf6 16. Rdg1 Kh8 17. Rg3 Ne5 18. Bxe5 (18. Rhg1 $2 Bf8 19. Nb5 Nxd3+ 20. cxd3 Bd7 $1 21. Nxc7 Re2 $1 22. Nxd5 Qe6 $1 23. Qd1 Rxf2 24. c4 Bc6 $17) 18... Rxe5 19. Rf3 Qe7 20. Rg3 Bd6 (20... Qf6 $11) 21. Kb1 Bd7 22. f4 Re4 $1 {A necessary but strong positional exchange sacrifice.} 23. Bxe4 dxe4 24. Rhg1 Rg8 $15 {With a pawn, the pair of bishops, and the better pawn structure, Black has more than enough compensation.}) (12. Rde1 {is well met by} Ne4 13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Qxd8 Bxd8 15. Bf4 b5 $5 16. Nd4 Bd7 $11) ({After} 12. Rhg1 $6 {Black can prevent g4 with the simple} Bg4 $15) (12. Bg5 {Giving up the dark-squared bishop is not dangerous at all for Black.} h6 13. Bxf6 (13. Rde1 $6 Be6 $15) 13... Bxf6 14. Qf4 Be7 $1 15. Nd4 (15. Ne5 Be6 16. Ng4 Bd6 17. Qf3 Qd7 18. Ne3 Qa4 19. Kb1 Qf4 $15 {Nisipeanu,L (2684) -Volokitin,A (2684) Foros 2008}) 15... Bf8 $132) (12. Rhe1 {is comfortably met with} Bg4 $132 {- the bishops is very well placed on g4.}) 12... c6 {Black can choose between keeping the tension with this move or simplifying the game with 12...dxc4.} (12... dxc4 $5 13. Bxc4 Qxd2+ 14. Bxd2 c6 15. Rhe1 (15. Ne5 Nd5 $11) 15... Bf5 16. Ne5 (16. Re5 Bg6 $11) 16... Nd5 17. g4 Be6 18. g5 Bd6 $11) 13. h5 $146 (13. Bd4 Bg4 $132) (13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Qe2 (14. Bd4 Bg4 $11) 14... Qa5 $5 {This leads to major complications.} (14... h6 $5 $13) 15. Bxh7+ Kf8 $1 {Black has good counterplay for the sacrificed pawn.} 16. a3 (16. Ne5 $6 Nf6) (16. c3 Bf6 $132) 16... Bxa3 $1 17. Rxd5 cxd5 18. bxa3 Qxa3+ 19. Kd2 Qb4+ 20. c3 (20. Kd1 Qb1+ $11) 20... Qb2+ 21. Bc2 {White can avoid an immediate draw in this way - the game remains dynamically balanced.} (21. Kd3 Qb5+ $11) (21. Kd1 Qa1+ {1/2-1/2 (21) Hall,R (2620)-Akdag,M (2564) ICCF email 2015}) 21... Bf5 22. Rc1 Rac8 23. Nd4 Be4 24. Qb5 Qxc3+ 25. Kd1 a6 26. Qxb7 Bxc2+ 27. Rxc2 Qd3+ 28. Kc1 Rb8 $11) 13... h6 {Stopping the advance of White's h-pawn. Black is doing well; for example} (13... Bg4 $5 14. h6 g6 $11) 14. cxd5 Qxd5 15. c4 Qd6 16. Bf4 Qc5 17. Be3 Qd6 $11) (11. c4 c5 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gd7c6] A typical resource in our line - Black plays ...c5, preparing ...Bd7-c6.} (11... b6 $5 {is a solid reply. For example} 12. Rhe1 (12. Bd4 Bb7 13. Qf4 h6 $11) 12... Bb7 13. Bd4 h6 14. Qf4 Nh5 15. Qg4 Bg5+ 16. Kb1 Nf6 17. Rxe8+ Qxe8 18. Bxf6 (18. Qg3 Nh5 $11) 18... Bxf6 19. Qf5 Bxf3 20. Qxf3 Rd8 21. c3 Qe5 $11) 12. Rhe1 (12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 Be6 14. Rhe1 Qd7 $11) (12. Bf4 Bd7) 12... Bd7 13. Bg5 (13. Bf4 Bc6 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5]} 14. Ng5 Bf8 $11) (13. Ng5 Bc6) 13... h6 14. Bh4 Bc6 15. Bf5 (15. c3 Ng4) 15... b5 {Black starts active counterplay - his chances are not worse.} (15... Qc7) 16. cxb5 Bxb5 $11) 11... Bg4 $1 ({Black is sligthly worse after} 11... Bd7 12. Bd4 $14) 12. Bg5 ({After} 12. h3 Bxf3 13. gxf3 {it's important for Black to play} d5 $1 {[%cal Ge7f8,Gd8d6] , preparing . ..Qd6 and ...Bf8. Now, Black is very solid, and it's difficult for White to create threats.} 14. Rg1 ({Black is not worse after} 14. c4 dxc4 15. Bxc4 Qxd2+ 16. Kxd2 Bd6 $11) (14. f4 c5 (14... a6 $5) 15. Bb5 {It seems that White wins a tempo, but soon Black will play ...a6, followed by ...b5, creating counterplay on the queenside.} (15. Kb1 $6 {was played in 1-0 (43) Vachier Lagrave,M (2780) -Wei,Y (2736) Abidjan 2019. However, this is already inaccurate and Black is better after} a6 16. f5 b5 $15) 15... Rf8 16. f5 a6 17. Bf1 b5 18. Bg5 h6 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Qxd5 Qc7 $44 {Black has excellent positional compensation for the pawn. His bishop safely defends his king and supports an attack on the queenside.}) (14. h4 Bf8 (14... Qd6) 15. Rg1 (15. h5 h6) 15... Qd6 $1 (15... Kh8 {0-1 (51) Aronian,L (2742)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2779) Chess.com INT 2023} 16. Kb1) 16. Bf4 (16. Bg5 a6) (16. Kb1 Rad8) 16... Qb6 17. Bg5 g6 18. f4 c5 19. h5 Nxh5 20. f5 Bg7 21. Rh1 Nf6 $132) 14... Qd6 {This is the most accurate move.} (14... Bf8 15. Bg5) 15. Bf4 (15. Bh6 g6 $15) (15. f4 c5 $132) (15. Bd4 g6) (15. Kb1 a6 16. h4 c5 17. Bf4 Qb6 18. Rg5 Rad8 19. Rdg1 g6 20. h5 Ne4 21. fxe4 Bxg5 22. Bxg5 dxe4 23. Bxd8 Qxd8 $11) (15. h4 Bf8 $11) 15... Qc6 16. Be5 g6 {[%cal Ge7f8] Black is solid enough on the kingside. A possible continuation:} 17. h4 Bf8 {[%cal Gf8g7]} 18. Bd4 Qd6 19. Qg5 Bg7 20. h5 Nxh5 21. Qxh5 gxh5 22. Bxg7 f6 23. Bh6+ Kh8 24. Bg7+ $11) (12. c4 g6 $1 {Here, we do not want to take on f3 too early since we can no longer play ...d5 afterwards. With ...g6, Black prepares to transfer his bishop to g7.} (12... Bxf3 $6 13. gxf3 $14) 13. Kb1 (13. h3 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Qd7 15. Kb1 (15. f4 d5 $1) 15... Bf8 (15... Qxh3 {was played in an email game.} 16. Bd4 Qxf3 17. Re3 Qf4 18. Bc3 Ng4 19. Rxe7 Qxd2 20. Rxe8+ Rxe8 21. Bxd2 Nxf2 22. Rf1 Nxd3 23. cxd3 Re2 24. Bh6 f5 $44 {½-½ (35) Peled,S (2248)-Bondars,G (2423) ICCF email 2017. We have arrived at an unbalanced ending; chances are about equal.}) 16. h4 d5 17. cxd5 (17. Qc3 Bg7 $11) 17... Qxd5 18. f4 Bc5 $11) (13. Bd4 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Bf8 {1/2-1/2 (83) Aronian,L (2785)-Dominguez Perez,L (2756) Saint Louis 2022} 15. Qg5 (15. Rxe8 Nxe8) 15... Rxe1 16. Rxe1 Nd7 $11) (13. Bg5 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Nd7 $11) 13... Qd7 ({Black can also play the immediate} 13... Bf8 $5 14. Bg5 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Rxe1 16. Rxe1 Bg7 17. a3 (17. Qf4 c6 18. c3 d5 $11) 17... Qd7 18. f4 h6 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. f5 g5 21. h4 Qc6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (33) Seia,J (2478)-Obertin,F (2428) ICCF email 2020}) 14. Be2 (14. Bd4 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Nh5 $11) 14... Ne4 {Next comes ... Bf6 with an active game.} 15. Qa5 (15. Qd5 Bf6 16. h3 Qa4 $5 17. hxg4 Bxb2 18. Kxb2 Qb4+ $11) 15... Bf6 16. h3 b6 17. Qa3 Be6 18. Bd3 Nc5 19. Nd4 Nxd3 20. Qxd3 Bf5 21. Nxf5 Qxf5 22. Qxf5 gxf5 23. b3 Kg7 24. Kc1 Kg6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (25) Betker,J (2454)-Velilla Velasco,F (2545) ICCF email 2019}) (12. Qe2 {Transferring the queen to f1 does not look like a constructive idea.} Bf8 13. h3 Bd7 14. Kb1 c5 15. Qf1 {1/2-1/2 (54) Audi,A (2418)-Siddharth,J (2331) Arandjelovac 2022} d5 $132 {Only Black can be better here.}) (12. Kb1 d5 $1 {Gaining space in the centre, followed by ...Bf8, ...Qd6, or ...c5 is a thematic idea.} 13. Qc1 {White tries to use the opposition of the queen on d8 and the rook on d1. However, the queen is not well-placed on c1.} (13. Bd4 c5 14. Bxf6 (14. Be5 $6 Bd6) 14... Bxf6 15. Rxe8+ Qxe8 16. Qf4 Be6 {[%csl Ge6,Gf6]} 17. Ng5 h6 18. Nxe6 Qxe6 $11 {is very comfortable for Black.}) (13. Bg5 Qd6 14. h3 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Nh5 (15... Bf8 $11) 16. Be3 Rad8 $132) (13. h3 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Bf8 (14... a6) (14... Qd6) 15. h4 Qd6 16. Rg1 Rad8 $11) 13... c5 (13... a6 $5 14. h3 (14. c4 c6) 14... Bxf3 15. gxf3 b5 $132) 14. c4 (14. Bb5 {does not offer anything to White.} Bd7 15. Bxd7 Qxd7 16. Bg5 h6 17. Bh4 Rad8 $11) 14... d4 15. Bg5 Bxf3 {Taking on f3 followed by ...Nh5 is the simplest.} (15... Qd6 {is also good.} 16. c3 {is an improvement over 16.Bf4. However, Black gets good compensation for the pawn after} (16. Bf4 Qa6 17. Be5 {1/2-1/2 (40) Kirk,E (2447)-Song,J (2328) Chalons en Champagne 2021} Nh5 $132) 16... Bf8 17. cxd4 Rxe1 18. Rxe1 Bxf3 19. gxf3 h6 20. Bxf6 Qxf6 $44) 16. gxf3 Nh5 17. c3 g6 18. cxd4 cxd4 $11 {Black does not have any problems in this structure.}) (12. a3 d5 $11) (12. Bd4 d5 13. Qf4 Bd6 14. Rxe8+ Qxe8 15. Qg5 h6 16. Qh4 Bxf3 (16... Qe6) 17. gxf3 Qe6 (17... Qe7) 18. Rg1 Kf8 $11 {Black neutralises White's threats and keeps a very solid position.}) 12... Qd7 {[%cal Gg4f5] Black connects the rooks and prepares a possible ...Bf5.} 13. a3 (13. h3 Bxf3 $146 (13... Bf5 14. g4 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 h6 16. Be3 {1/2-1/2 (30) Suleymanli,A (2588)-Aditya,M (2572) Durres 2023} (16. Bh4 Nh7) 16... Bf8 17. Bd4 (17. Rg1 g6) 17... Rxe1 18. Rxe1 Nh7 $11) 14. gxf3 d5 {I like this idea for Black - we have already seen this in the lines above.} 15. Kb1 ({After} 15. c4 {Black can boldly take on h3.} Qxh3 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Rh1 Qe6 18. Bxh7+ Kf8 19. Be4 (19. cxd5 $2 Qb6 20. c3 g6 $17) 19... Bxb2+ 20. Kxb2 dxe4 21. Qf4 $11) (15. h4 Qd6 16. Rg1 Rad8 $11) 15... Qd6 {The fact that Black has lost a tempo with his queen does not play a role.} 16. h4 Nh5 $11) (13. Kb1 Bf5 {Here we can already neutralise White's bishop.} 14. h3 (14. Nd4 Ne4 $1 {This forces some exchanges.} 15. Bxe4 Bxg5 16. Qxg5 Bxe4 17. f3 Bg6 $11) 14... h6 15. Be3 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Bf8 17. g4 g6 $11) (13. Re2 Bxf3 14. gxf3 c6 $1 {Creating a nice outpost on d5.} 15. Rde1 Nd5 $11) 13... Bf5 {Here, I prefer this over exchanging on f3.} (13... Bxf3 $6 14. gxf3 d5 15. c4 c6 16. Re2 $14) 14. Nd4 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Ne4 $1 {The most concrete move, equalising the game by force.} (15... h6 $5 {is a solid and good alternative.} 16. Bh4 (16. Bd2 c6) 16... Nh7 $11) (15... Nd5 $6 16. Bxe7 Nxe7 17. h4 $14 {1-0 (57) Carlsen,M (2863)-Caruana,F (2835) Lichess.org INT 2020}) 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Kb1 (17. f3 Qg5+ $1 $11 {is an important detail.}) 17... Qh4 $1 18. g3 (18. Re2 Nf6 ({After} 18... Nc5 $6 {White has the trick} 19. Rde1 $1 $14) 19. Nb5 Rxe2 {Black can unbalance the position by taking on e2 or go for the solid ... Qh5.} (19... Qh5 $5 20. Rde1 Qc5 21. b4 Rxe2 22. Rxe2 Qb6 23. Re7 Re8 24. Rxe8+ Nxe8 25. Nd4 g6 26. Qe4 Kf8 $11) 20. Qxe2 Qxh2 21. Nxc7 Rc8 22. Nb5 Qxg2 23. Nxd6 Rf8 24. Rd4 h5 $132) (18. Nf3 Qf4 19. g3 Qg4 20. h3 Qg6 $11) 18... Qh5 19. g4 Qg6 20. Qf1 (20. Qe3 Qg5 (20... Nf6 21. Qf3) 21. Qxg5 Nxg5 22. f4 Ne6 $11) 20... Qg5 {This line was seen in a couple of correspondence games, proving that chances are equal.} (20... d5 {is another good line.} 21. f3 (21. Nb5 a6 22. Nxc7 Nxc3+ 23. Ka1 Nxd1 24. Nxa8 Rxa8 25. Qe2 Ne3 26. Qxe3 h6 $11) 21... Nd6 22. Qf2 Qf6 23. Nf5 Nxf5 24. gxf5 Red8 25. Qc5 c6 $11 {½- (29) ½ (29) Kunzelmann,F (2475)-Turgut,T (2589) ICCF corr 2022}) 21. Qg2 ({After} 21. Nb5 Qc5 {is a simple answer.} 22. f3 Nf6 23. b4 Rxe1 24. Rxe1 Qc6 $11) 21... Qf4 22. f3 Nf6 23. Ne2 Qc4 24. h4 Re6 25. Nd4 Rxe1 26. Rxe1 Re8 27. Rxe8+ Nxe8 $11 {½- (55) ½ (55) Carr,T (2386)-Sherwood,H (2400) ICCF email 2021} *

