1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 {With this lesson, we begin to examine the absolute main line of the Petroff Defence.} d5 6. Bd3 Bd6 {This is the most topical and also the most active line for Black, played by, for example, Ian Nepomniachtchi.} ({The main alternatives are} 6... Be7) ({and} 6... Nc6) 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 {Before studying the move 8.c4 in some detail in Lessons 17 to 23, we look at White's lesser options on move 8.} (8. Nbd2 {was tried in a high-level game by Caruana.} Bf5 9. Re1 Re8 {This already looks fine for Black - he was able to support the strong knight on e4.} 10. g3 (10. Nf1 Nd7 11. Bg5 {This leads to a quiet, symmetrical position.} ({After} 11. Ne3 {Black can defend his central outpost with} Be6 12. c4 c6 $132) 11... Nxg5 12. Rxe8+ Qxe8 13. Bxf5 Nxf3+ 14. Qxf3 c6 $11) 10... Qf6 $5 {This is best - the queen takes aim at f2.} (10... h6 {creating a retreat square for the bishop, was played by Nepomniachtchi.} 11. Nh4 Bh7 12. Qf3 Nc6 13. c3 {½- (61) ½ (61) Caruana,F (2776)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2792) Saint Louis 2022 Now, Black should have played} f5 14. Ng2 g5 $132 {with double-edged play.}) 11. Nh4 (11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Bg5 Qe6 13. Nh4 h6 $132) 11... Bg4 $1 {Thanks to 10...Qf6, Black has some tactics.} 12. Nxe4 Rxe4 13. f3 Rxe1+ 14. Qxe1 Be6 15. Qf2 Nd7 16. c3 Re8 $11 {The position is equal.}) (8. Nc3 {can be met with} Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bg4 {Black will complete his development by playing ...Nc6, with an equal game.} 10. Rb1 (10. c4 dxc4 11. Bxc4 Nc6 12. c3 h6 13. h3 Bf5 $11) (10. Re1 Nc6 11. Rb1 b6 {transposes to 8.Re1.}) (10. h3 Bh5 11. g4 Bg6 12. Bg5 f6 13. Bd2 Bxd3 14. cxd3 Nc6 $11) 10... b6 11. Re1 Nc6 12. Rb5 {White tries to create some concrete problems. Black can ignore the attack on d5 and play} Re8 $1 {with an active game.} 13. Rxe8+ ({Black gets at least sufficient compensation after} 13. Rxd5 Rxe1+ 14. Qxe1 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Qh4 16. f4 Qg4+ 17. Kf1 Qh3+ $11) 13... Qxe8 14. Rxd5 Qe6 15. Rb5 a6 16. Rb1 Qxa2 {Black has won back the pawn. He has good chances in this unbalanced position.} 17. Bd2 Bxf3 18. gxf3 Ne7 19. c4 Ng6 20. Be3 a5 {Now the game could end with a repetition.} 21. Ra1 Qb2 22. Rb1 $11) 8... Bf5 9. Nc3 (9. Nbd2 {transposes to 8.Nbd2.}) (9. c4 c6 {transposes to 8. c4.}) 9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 Bxd3 11. cxd3 (11. Qxd3 {also fails to pose problems.} Nd7 (11... h6 {is also good.} 12. c4 dxc4 13. Qxc4 Qd7 {[%cal Gb8c6] , followed by ...Nc6.}) 12. c4 dxc4 13. Qxc4 h6 14. Qb3 b6 15. c4 Qf6 (15... c6 16. Bb2 Qc7 17. g3 Rfe8 $11 {½- (34) ½ (34) Hansen,E (2609)-Ivic,V (2562) Durres 2023}) 16. Bb2 Rfe8 $11) 11... Re8 12. Rxe8+ (12. Qb3 Rxe1+ 13. Nxe1 b6 14. g3 c6 $11) 12... Qxe8 {Black has the more compact pawn structure, while White struggles to pose any problems.} 13. Qb3 Qc6 14. c4 (14. Bd2 Nd7 $11) 14... Nd7 15. a4 {This was seen in the game 1-0 (30) Adams,M (2706)-Smeets,J (2585) Karlsruhe 2020.} ({Black does not need to fear} 15. cxd5 {since the triple pawn renders White's extra pawn worthless.} Qb6 16. Qc4 Nf6 17. a4 a6 18. Bg5 Qb2 19. Rf1 Re8 $44) {Black could have equalised with} 15... b6 16. Bd2 a6 17. Rc1 h6 $11 {After} 18. cxd5 Qb7 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gd7f6] Black has fully sufficient compensation for the pawn. For example} 19. Bb4 Bxb4 20. Qxb4 Nf6 21. d6 Nd5 22. Qa3 b5 ({or} 22... Rc8 $11) 23. dxc7 b4 24. Qb3 Nxc7 $44 *

