1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Bd3 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. c4 c6 9. Qb3 {The main focus of Lesson 17 lies in this move. White puts pressure on b7 and d5, trying to prevent the development of Black's light-squared bishop. However, 9...Bg4 is possible anyway! We look at the most important lines 9.cxd5, 9.Qc2, 9.Nc3, and 9.Re1 in the following lessons.} (9. Nbd2 {is simply met with} Bf5 $132) ({Closing the position with} 9. c5 {looks premature since Black gets a free hand in the centre.} Bc7 10. Nc3 f5 11. Qc2 Nd7 12. Ne2 Qf6 $132 {[%cal Gg7g5]}) (9. h3 {White prevents ...Bg4, but after} Bf5 {Black has no problems.} 10. Nc3 (10. Qb3 dxc4 11. Bxc4 Na6 $1 {Black can ignore the attack on b7 since 12.Qxb7 would be met with 12...Nb4.} 12. Nbd2 (12. Nc3 b5 13. Bd3 (13. Nxb5 {is possible according to the engine. However, after} Rb8 14. Nxd6 Rxb3 15. Nxf5 Rb6 16. Re1 Nf6 $132 {White has only two pieces for the queen and only Black can hope for some advantage.}) 13... Nd2 14. Bxd2 Bxd3 $11) 12... Qb6 13. Nh4 Nxd2 14. Bxd2 Bd7 $11) 10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 dxc4 13. Qxc4 Nd7 {Black has no problems at all.} 14. Qb3 b6 15. c4 Re8 16. a4 h6 $11) 9... Bg4 $1 {The most concrete solution.} (9... dxc4 $5 {is another very decent option.} 10. Bxc4 (10. Qxc4 Nf6 $11) 10... Nf6 {Black has a decent IQP position - he will win some time by playing ...Nd7-b6, or ... Qb6.} 11. Re1 (11. Nc3 Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7b6]} 12. Qc2 Nb6 13. Bb3 Re8 14. Bg5 Be6 $11) 11... Qb6 (11... b5 12. Bf1) 12. Nc3 (12. Bg5 Qxb3 13. Bxb3 Nd5 14. Nc3 Be6 $11) 12... Qxb3 13. Bxb3 h6 14. Be3 Na6 15. d5 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 cxd5 17. Bxd5 Rd8 18. Rad1 Nc7 19. Be4 Ne8 $11) 10. Bxe4 (10. Nbd2 dxc4 11. Bxc4 ({Black has at least a draw after} 11. Nxc4 Bxf3 12. Qxb7 Bxh2+ 13. Kxh2 Qh4+ 14. Kg1 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Qg4+ $11) 11... Nxd2 12. Bxd2 (12. Nxd2 b5 13. Bd3 Na6 $132) 12... b5 13. Be2 Nd7 {Black has completed his development - he is doing fine. Possible continuations:} 14. d5 (14. a4 a6 15. Rfe1 Be6 16. Qc2 Bd5 $11) (14. Qc2 Re8 $1 15. Rfe1 (15. h3 Bh5 16. Rfe1 Rc8 $11) 15... Rxe2 $1 16. Rxe2 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Qh4 18. f4 (18. Ree1 Qh3) 18... Qg4+ 19. Kf1 Qh3+ 20. Kg1 (20. Ke1 $6 Qxh2) 20... Qg4+ $11) 14... Re8 $11) (10. c5 {does not improve White's position.} Bc7 $132) (10. Nfd2 $6 {After this, White's king will be in some danger.} Ng5 $1 {Black is attacking with several pieces - White must defend very precisely to survive.} 11. cxd5 (11. Qxb7 $2 Qf6 $1 12. c5 Bf4 $1 13. Qxa8 Nh3+ $1 14. Kh1 (14. gxh3 Qh4 $19) 14... Qh6 15. g3 Bxd2 16. Nxd2 Qxd2 $1 $19 {[%cal Gg4f3]}) 11... cxd5 12. Qxb7 Nh3+ $1 13. gxh3 Bc8 $1 14. Qb3 Qg5+ 15. Kh1 Qf4 16. Bxh7+ Kxh7 17. Qg3 Nc6 (17... Qf6 {Keeping the queens on the board in order to continue the attack is tempting. However, White is able to defend the position with perfect play.} 18. Qg2 Nc6 19. Qxd5 Bb7 20. Qg2 Qg6 21. d5 Nb4 22. Nc3 Qxg2+ 23. Kxg2 Nxd5 24. Nxd5 Bxd5+ 25. f3 Be5 26. Ne4 Rab8 $11) 18. Qxf4 Bxf4 19. Nf3 Bd6 $15 {Black is temporarily two pawns down, but he has more than enough compensation due to White's weaknesses and his strong light-squared bishop.}) (10. Be2 Qc7 (10... Qd7 11. h3 Be6 {is also good.}) 11. h3 Be6 12. Nc3 dxc4 13. Bxc4 Bxc4 14. Qxc4 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Nd7 $11) 10... dxe4 11. Ng5 (11. Ne5 Bxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. Qg3 h5 $132) 11... Be7 $1 {The most forcing and, in my opinion, best continuation.} (11... Bc7 $13 {leads to an unclear position.}) 12. Nxe4 {Now some forcing play starts.} ({The greedy} 12. Qxb7 $2 {is too risky for White.} Bxg5 13. Qxa8 Bf3 $1 14. Nd2 Qd7 $1 15. gxf3 Bxd2 16. Bxd2 Na6 (16... exf3 17. Kh1) 17. Qxf8+ Kxf8 18. Rad1 h5 $17 {[%csl Rg1]}) 12... Qxd4 13. Qxb7 (13. Nbc3 Qb6 $11) (13. Re1 Nd7 $11) 13... Qxe4 $1 14. Qxa8 Bh3 $1 15. gxh3 Qg6+ 16. Kh1 Qe4+ 17. f3 (17. Kg1 Qg6+ $11) 17... Qd3 18. Kg2 (18. Nd2 $2 {allowed} Qd7 $1 {, trapping the queen. After} 19. Ne4 (19. Re1 Bh4 $1 20. Re4 Bf6 $17) 19... Na6 20. Qxf8+ Bxf8 {Black's queen is stronger than the two rooks due to White's weak king.} (20... Kxf8 $17) 21. Bf4 Qxh3 22. Rad1 h6 $17 {0-1 (43) Rapport,R (2764)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2766) Madrid 2022}) 18... Qg6+ 19. Bg5 {The only way to continue the game.} (19. Kh1 Qd3 $11) 19... Bxg5 20. Kh1 Qd3 21. Nc3 (21. Na3 Qd7 $44 {[%csl Ra8] is similar.}) 21... Qd7 22. Rad1 Qc7 23. Rfe1 Be7 $1 {This is necessary since 23...Nd7 (or 23...Na6) would have run into 24.Re8.} 24. a3 (24. Nb5 cxb5 25. cxb5 Bf6 $132) 24... Nd7 25. Nd5 {By returning a piece, White manages to extract his queen. The resulting position offers sufficient counterchances for Black.} cxd5 26. Qxd5 Nb6 27. Qb5 h6 $132 {White has a rook and two pawns for knight and bishop. With queens on the board, Black will always have counterplay against White's weak king.} *

