1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Bd3 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. c4 c6 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Nc3 Re8 $5 (10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bg4 {is the main line.}) 11. Re1 (11. h3 {White prevents ...Bg4.} Nxc3 12. bxc3 Nd7 13. Qb3 (13. a4 {[%cal Gc1a3] with the idea of exchanging the dark-squared bishop is another logical try.} Qc7 14. Ba3 Bf4 $5 {I like this ambitious move best.} ({White is sligthly better after} 14... Bxa3 15. Rxa3 {, though Black should be able to equalise step by step.} Nf6 16. a5 (16. Ne5 Be6 17. f4 Rac8 $14 {/=}) 16... Ne4 ({or} 16... Be6) 17. Ne5 (17. Qb1 Bf5 $11) 17... Nd6 18. Qh5 g6 19. Qf3 Be6 $11) 15. Qb3 Nf6 16. c4 dxc4 17. Bxc4 Be6 {Now White has to go for very concrete play:} 18. d5 Rac8 19. dxe6 Qxc4 20. Qxb7 (20. exf7+ Qxf7) 20... Qxe6 21. Qxa7 (21. Rfe1 Qb6 $11) 21... Rc3 $1 {White is temporarily up a pawn; however, with 21...Rc3, Black creates strong counterplay. One threat is ...Rxf3.} 22. Rae1 (22. Nd4 $2 Qd5 23. Nb5 Rg3 $1 $17) (22. Qd4 Rxf3 $1 23. gxf3 g5 (23... Be5 24. Qh4 Bxa1 25. Rxa1 Qb3 26. Bb4 Ne4 $11) 24. Kg2 Be5 25. Qb4 Bxa1 (25... g4 $5) (25... Nd5) 26. Rxa1 Nd5 27. Qg4 Qf6 28. Rg1 Nf4+ 29. Kh1 h6 30. h4 (30. Bc1 Ne2) 30... Nd3 $11) 22... Ne4 $1 23. Bb2 (23. Bc1 Bb8 $44 {...Rxf3 is coming.}) 23... Rxf3 $1 24. Qd4 $1 (24. gxf3 $2 Qxh3 $19) 24... f6 25. Re2 Rb3 (25... Rxh3 {is also enough for a draw.} 26. gxh3 Qxh3 27. f3 Qxf1+ 28. Kxf1 Ng3+ 29. Ke1 Rxe2+ 30. Kd1 Rd2+ 31. Qxd2 Bxd2 32. Kxd2 {White's a-pawn seems to be very dangerous, but Black is in time to stop it.} Nf5 33. a5 Ne7 34. a6 Nc8 $11 {After stopping the a-pawn, Black will always have enough counterplay on the kingside.}) 26. Rfe1 Kf7 {The position is very complex. Black has different options:} (26... Rxb2 27. Qxb2 f5 $11 {We have a material unbalance - the position remains dynamically equal.}) (26... Rxh3 27. Qxe4 ({or} 27. Rxe4 Bh2+ 28. Kf1 Be5 $11) 27... Qxe4 28. Rxe4 Rxe4 29. Rxe4 Rb3 30. Rxf4 Rxb2 $11 {The rook endgame will end in a draw.}) 27. Bc1 (27. Rxe4 Be5 28. Rxe5 fxe5 29. Qd2 $11 {White has sufficient compensation for the exchange but not more than that.}) 27... Rb1 28. Bxf4 Ng3 $1 {Black forces a draw by giving perpetual check:} 29. Rxe6 Rxe1+ 30. Kh2 Nf1+ $11) (13. Bg5 {After this, Black had zero problems in the following high-level game:} Qc7 14. Re1 Rxe1+ 15. Qxe1 Nf8 $11 {1-0 (52) Carlsen,M (2832)-Erigaisi,A (2778) Chess.com INT 2024}) 13... h6 $1 {Calmly prevents a possible Bg5. Black can ignore the attack against d5 due to tactical reasons.} ({White is more comfortable after} 13... Nb6 14. Ba3 Bxa3 15. Qxa3 Be6 16. Rfe1 Nc4 17. Bxc4 dxc4 18. Qb4 $14) 14. Ba3 (14. Qxd5 {is met with} Nc5 $1 15. Bf4 (15. dxc5 $4 Bh2+ $19) 15... Nxd3 16. Qxd6 Qxd6 (16... Qa5 $44) (16... Be6 $44) 17. Bxd6 b6 $44 {With a solid control of the light squares, and play against the c3-pawn, Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) 14... Nf6 {The knight feels more comfortable on f6 than on b6.} 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Ne5 Re7 $11 {Black continues with ...Rc7, ...Be6, ...Rac8, generating sufficient counterplay.}) (11. Nxd5 {does not pose any problems.} Bxh2+ 12. Nxh2 Qxd5 $11) (11. Qb3 Nc6 $1 {Black counters the attack against d5 with an active developing move.} 12. Re1 (12. Bxe4 dxe4 13. Ng5 Re7 $11) (12. Qxd5 $4 Nxc3 $19 {[%csl Rd5,Gd8][%cal Yd6h2,Yd8d5]}) (12. Nxd5 $2 Bg4 $17) 12... Be6 {Black has consolidated this centre. Taking on b7 can lead to a repetition of moves:} 13. Qxb7 Nb4 14. Bxe4 Rb8 15. Bxh7+ Kxh7 16. Qxa7 Ra8 $11) (11. Qc2 {is met with} Bf5 $11 {followed by ...Nc6, etc.}) 11... Nxc3 (11... Bf5 $2 12. Qb3 $16) 12. Rxe8+ ({Black has few problems after} 12. bxc3 Rxe1+ 13. Qxe1 h6 14. c4 b6 15. Ne5 Bb7 16. Bf4 Qf6 $11) 12... Qxe8 13. bxc3 Nd7 {This knight will go to f6 or b6, followed by ...Be6 - the play is similar to lines we have already seen.} 14. Qb3 {Other moves are not critical.} (14. Qc2 h6 15. Bd2 Nf6 16. Re1 Be6 $11) (14. Bd2 h6 $11) (14. Qa4 Nf6 15. Qxe8+ Nxe8 $11) 14... Nb6 ({After} 14... Nf6 $2 {White has the unpleasant} 15. Bg5 $16) 15. Ba3 ({After} 15. a4 {Black can offer the b7-pawn and play} Be6 16. a5 Nc4 17. Qxb7 Rb8 18. Qa6 {The only way to continue the game. However, the queen is not placed well on a6, and this gives Black enough compensation.} (18. Qxa7 Ra8 $11 {leads to a repetition.}) 18... Qd7 19. Ng5 h6 20. Nxe6 Qxe6 21. Bxc4 dxc4 22. g3 Qe1+ 23. Kg2 Qe4+ $11) (15. h3 Be6 $11) 15... Bxa3 16. Qxa3 Be6 {I prefer this straightforward move, though 16...h6 is playable as well.} (16... h6 $5 17. Re1 (17. h3 Be6 18. Rb1 Qf8 19. Qa5 Qc8 20. Ne5 Nd7 21. f4 b6 22. Qa3 Nxe5 23. fxe5 Qf8 24. Qxf8+ Kxf8 25. Kf2 Rc8 26. Rc1 Ke7 $11 {1/2-1/2 (38) Navara,D (2681)-Vidit,S (2723) Prague 2022}) (17. Ne5 Be6 18. Rb1 (18. f4 Nc4) (18. Qb3 Qc8) 18... Qc8 19. Qb4 Bf5 20. Qe7 Be6 21. Rb3 Nd7 22. Ng6 (22. Nxd7 Bxd7) 22... Nb6 23. Nf4 Bf5 24. g3 Bxd3 25. Nxd3 Qf5 $11) 17... Be6 {transposes to 16...Be6.}) 17. Re1 (17. Ne5 Qa4 $11) (17. Rb1 Qc8 (17... Qf8 18. Qb3 h6 19. a4 Rb8 $11) 18. Qb4 Rb8 $11) (17. h4 h6 18. Ne5 Qc8 $11) (17. Ng5 h6 18. Nxe6 Qxe6 $11) 17... h6 18. Ne5 (18. Re3 Qa4 19. Qe7 Qd7 $11) (18. h3 Qc8 19. Re3 Qc7 20. Ne5 a6 21. Qb4 (21. Ng6 Re8) 21... Rd8 $11) (18. h4 Qa4) 18... Nd7 $1 {Black manages to exchange the active knight on e5, thereby securing equal chances.} 19. f4 (19. Qb3 Nxe5 20. Rxe5 Qc6 21. f4 f6 22. Re3 Bf7 $11) ({It is important that} 19. Bb5 {can be met with} Qf8 $1 20. Qxf8+ Nxf8 21. Kf1 Rc8 $11) 19... Nxe5 20. Rxe5 ({After} 20. fxe5 {Black can play} Qd8 $11 {with the idea of ...Qg5.}) 20... Qc6 21. f5 (21. Qb3 f6 22. Re3 Bf7 $11) 21... Bd7 22. Qb3 {The critical line - White wins d5, but Black can generate sufficient counterplay.} (22. Qa5 b5 $11) 22... Qc7 $5 23. Qxd5 (23. Rxd5 $6 Re8 $15 {is quite risky for White.}) (23. g3 Bc6 24. Qa3 Re8 25. Rxe8+ Bxe8 $11) (23. h3 Bc6 24. f6 gxf6 25. Rf5 Re8 26. Rf3 (26. Rxf6 Qg3 $11) 26... Qe7 $11) 23... Qxc3 24. Re7 (24. Qxd7 Qxd3 25. h3 Qd2 $11) 24... Rf8 25. Rxd7 Qxd3 26. h3 Qe3+ $11 *

