1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Bd3 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. c4 c6 9. Qc2 h6 $1 {Modern computers suggest that this is probably Black's best move. Black claims that taking on e4 is not a real threat and simply plays a useful move.} (9... Na6 $5 {is the old main line.}) 10. Re1 ({One of the benefits of ...h6 is that Black can simply meet this with} 10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Re8 {In this line, we see an essential point of ...h6 - Bxh7 is no longer a threat. White struggles to create problems for Black:} 12. c5 (12. Rb1 b6 (12... dxc4 $5 {is another possibility.} 13. Bxc4 {1-0 (62) Popilski,G (2458) -Paravyan,D (2617) Chess.com INT 2022} b5 14. Bd3 Be6 15. a4 Bd5 $11 {After White defends against ...Bxf3, Black will consolidate with ...a6, ...Nd7, etc.}) 13. Be3 Nd7 $11) (12. Qb3 Nd7 $1 {We are already familiar with this motif from the previous lesson.} 13. cxd5 (13. a4 Nf6 $11) 13... cxd5 14. Qxd5 (14. Ba3 Nf6 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 $11) 14... Nc5 $1 {This is the point - Black will get sufficient positional compensation for the sacrificed pawn.} 15. Bf4 Nxd3 16. Qxd6 Qa5 {Exchanging on d6, followed by ...b6 or ...Be6 is also possible.} 17. Bd2 Re6 18. c4 Rxd6 19. Bxa5 Bg4 $11) (12. a4 Nd7 $11) 12... Bc7 13. Rb1 ({If} 13. Be3 {Black completes his development with} Nd7 14. Rae1 {1/2-1/2 (21) Dragnev,V (2551)-Bluebaum,M (2651) Austria 2023} Nf6 $11) 13... Nd7 14. Bd2 Nf6 15. Rfe1 b6 {Black is ready to develop his light-squared bishop with an equal game.} 16. Rxe8+ Qxe8 $11) ({It's important to check what happens when White accepts the pawn sacrifice.} 10. Bxe4 dxe4 11. Qxe4 Re8 {Black's compensation is of a positional, long-term nature. He has the pair of bishops and can put pressure on the d4-pawn. For example} 12. Qh4 (12. Qc2 Bg4 13. Nbd2 Na6 $44 {Black will continue with a possible ...Nb4, ...Bf5, or, if White prevents this, ...Nc7-e6, ...Qf6, etc.}) (12. Qd3 Bg4 13. h3 Bh5 14. Nc3 Na6 $44 {Black is about to generate good counterplay with ...Nb4. If} 15. a3 $2 {then} Nc5 $1 $17 {is already very strong.}) 12... Qxh4 13. Nxh4 Na6 $44 {Even without queens, Black has excellent long-term compensation.}) (10. c5 Bc7 {Since White has taken off the pressure from the d5-pawn, Black will be able to support his knight with ...f5.} 11. Nc3 (11. Bxe4 {This is no improvement over the immediate 10.Bxe4.} dxe4 12. Qxe4 Re8 13. Qh4 Qxh4 14. Nxh4 Be6 $44 {Since White has a backward pawn on d4 and Black can use the d5-square, the compensation is obvious.}) (11. Nbd2 f5 12. b4 (12. Ne5 {is met with} Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd7 $132 {and both e5 and c5 are hanging.}) 12... a5 $1 {Black uses the fact that a3 is not possible and b4-b5 is advantageous for him.} 13. bxa5 (13. b5 $6 {After this, Black is able to develop his knight to the active c6-square.} cxb5 14. Bxb5 Nc6 $15) 13... Rxa5 14. a4 Nd7 15. Nb3 Ra8 16. Bb2 Ndf6 $132) 11... f5 12. b4 (12. Ne2 f4 $1 $132) 12... Nd7 {With this strong knight on e4, Black is doing great. For example} 13. a4 (13. b5 Qf6 $132) ({After} 13. Ne2 {Black prevents Bf4 by playing} f4 $1 $132) 13... Qf6 14. Ne2 (14. b5 Rf7 $132 {[%cal Yg7g5]}) (14. a5 Ng5 $132) 14... Ng5 $11) (10. Nbd2 {After this, Black can complicate matters with 10...f5, or equalise with 10...Nxd2.} Nxd2 (10... f5 $5 11. Ne5 Be6 12. Ndf3 Nd7 $11) 11. Bxd2 dxc4 12. Bxc4 Qf6 13. Bc3 Bf5 14. Qd2 Nd7 15. d5 Ne5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. Bxe5 Qxe5 18. dxc6 {1/2-1/2 (53) Shirov,A (2691)-Moussard,J (2630) Germany 2022 Now,} Rac8 {would have been the most accurate continuation.} 19. Qd5 (19. Rfe1 Qf6 $11) 19... Qxd5 20. Bxd5 bxc6 21. Bc4 Rfd8 $11 {The isolated c6-pawn is not enough for White to claim an advantage.}) (10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Nc3 Nf6 (11... Nxc3 12. bxc3 Nc6 $11 {is also sufficient for equality.}) 12. Re1 Nc6 {Black threatens ...Bg4 as well as ... Nb4.} 13. h3 Nb4 14. Qd1 Nxd3 15. Qxd3 Be6 $11 {Black has a comfortable position.}) 10... Be6 $1 {Black develops while e4 is now indirectly defended.} 11. cxd5 (11. b3 {A playable move - White keeps the tension.} Bb4 $5 {The most direct way.} (11... Na6 {is also fine.} 12. a3 ({Black has sufficient compensation after} 12. Bxe4 dxe4 13. Qxe4 Qd7 $44) 12... Bg4 $1 {Black has to play energetically.} (12... f5 13. Nc3 $14) 13. Bxe4 {White takes the pawn. However, Black's compensation is again sufficient.} (13. Ne5 {This leads to major complications.} Bxe5 14. dxe5 Nac5 15. cxd5 cxd5 16. f3 Rc8 $1 {The tactics work out fine for Black due to his lead in development.} 17. Be3 d4 18. Bxe4 Be6 (18... dxe3 {is also possible.} 19. fxg4 Qd4 20. Nc3 Nxe4 21. Qxe4 Qxc3 $11) 19. Bd2 Nxb3 20. Qb2 d3 21. Bc3 Rxc3 22. Qxc3 (22. Nxc3 $6 Qd4+ 23. Kh1 Rc8 $17) 22... Qb6+ 23. Kh1 Rc8 24. Qxd3 Nxa1 25. Nc3 Nb3 26. Nd5 Qa5 27. Rd1 Nc5 28. Ne7+ Kh8 29. Qe3 Re8 $132) 13... dxe4 14. Qxe4 Qd7 $1 {Black simply completes his development, relying on his positional pluses.} ({Black should not be in a hurry to regain the pawn.} 14... Bxf3 $6 15. Qxf3 Qh4 16. g3 Qxd4 17. Nc3 f5 18. Bb2 Qg4 19. Qxg4 fxg4 20. Rad1 $14 {White has the initiative in this endgame.}) 15. h3 Bh5 16. Nbd2 Rfe8 17. Qc2 Rxe1+ 18. Nxe1 Nc7 19. Ndf3 Bg6 20. Qc3 Ne6 21. Be3 Rd8 $44) 12. Nbd2 ({After} 12. Re2 {Black generates counterplay with} Bg4 13. a3 Bxf3 14. Re3 {In this way, White avoids the weakening of his king position.} (14. gxf3 $6 Ng5 15. axb4 Nxf3+ 16. Kg2 Nxd4 $15) 14... Ba5 (14... Bd6 15. Rxf3 Re8 16. g3 Nd7 17. Re3 Ndf6 $11) 15. Rxf3 Re8 {White has the pair of bishops but Black's pieces are active enough.} 16. b4 Bb6 17. c5 Bc7 18. Nc3 Nd7 $11) (12. Re3 f5 {Black supports the knight on e4 with a good game.} 13. Ba3 a5 14. Bxb4 axb4 15. a4 (15. Nbd2 Nd7) 15... bxa3 16. Rxa3 Rxa3 17. Nxa3 Na6 $11) (12. Bd2 {poses no problems at all.} Nxd2 13. Nbxd2 Nd7 14. a3 Bxd2 15. Qxd2 {1/2-1/2 (22) Delport,W-Steiger, W freechess.de 2019} c5 (15... Bg4 $5 $11) 16. Rad1 Re8 $11) (12. Rf1 $6 Re8 $15) 12... Nd7 $1 {I prefer this developing move.} (12... f5 13. a3 Bd6 14. b4 Nd7 15. Nb3 Bc7 16. Bb2 Qe8 {leads to unclear play.}) ({Black quickly ended up in an unpleasant situation after} 12... Nxd2 13. Bxd2 Bxd2 14. Qxd2 dxc4 $6 (14... Nd7 15. c5 $14) 15. bxc4 Nd7 {1-0 (55) Saric,I (2665)-Saric,A (2536) Rijeka 2021} 16. h3 $14) 13. Bxe4 ({After} 13. a3 {Black can already exchange on d2 with an equal game.} Nxd2 (13... Bc3 $5) 14. Nxd2 (14. Bxd2 Bxd2 15. Qxd2 Bg4 $11) 14... Ba5 (14... Bd6 {is an alternative.} 15. Bb2 (15. Nf3 dxc4 16. bxc4 Bg4 $11) 15... Qf6 $11) 15. Bb2 (15. Re3 Nf6) 15... dxc4 16. bxc4 b5 $11) (13. Bb2 Bg4 $1 {Again, this active move. The following forcing line leads to simplification and equality.} 14. a3 Bxf3 15. axb4 Bxg2 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Bxe4 Bxe4 18. Qxe4 Qg5+ 19. Qg2 Qd2 20. f4 Qxb4 21. d5 f6 22. Kh1 Rf7 23. dxc6 bxc6 24. Qxc6 Rb8 $11) (13. Rb1 {gives Black two decent options.} f5 {is the ambitious choice.} (13... Bf5 14. a3 Ba5 15. b4 Nxd2 16. Bxd2 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 dxc4 18. Qxc4 Bb6 $11) 14. a3 Bd6 15. b4 Bf7 $132) 13... dxe4 14. Qxe4 Bc3 15. Rb1 (15. Ba3 {This allows Black to regain the pawn.} Bxa1 (15... Re8 $5 {is a more complicated alternative.} 16. Rad1 Qa5 17. Bd6 Bf5 18. Qxe8+ Rxe8 19. Rxe8+ Kh7 $132) 16. Bxf8 Bxd4 17. Nxd4 Nxf8 $11) 15... Qa5 {Black has very active play for the pawn. The threats are ...Bf5 and ...Qxa2.} 16. Qf4 (16. b4 Bxb4 17. a3 Bxd2 18. Bxd2 Qa6 $11 {Chances are equal; for example} 19. Qh4 (19. Qf4 Rfe8 $11) 19... Rfe8 20. Qg3 (20. Bxh6 {This is only good enough for a draw.} gxh6 21. Qxh6 Bf5 22. Qg5+ Bg6 23. h4 Kh8 24. Qh6+ Kg8 25. Qg5 $11) 20... Kh7 21. Qc7 Qxc4 22. Rxb7 Nf8 $11) (16. c5 Qxa2 17. Qd3 Bb4 $11) 16... Qxa2 {Black has regained the pawn. The position remains dynamically equal.} 17. Re3 Bxd2 18. Nxd2 Qc2 19. Ra1 (19. Rg3 Rfe8 $1 {A crucial resource! Black defends against Qxh6 by creating counter-threats.} 20. h3 (20. Qxh6 $2 {is refuted by} Bg4 $1 $19) (20. Ba3 Bxc4) 20... Kh7 $11 ({or} 20... Bf5 $11)) 19... Rfd8 (19... Nf6 20. Nf3 Rfe8 21. Bd2 a5 $11) 20. Nf3 b5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (43) Moussard,J (2632)-Nguyen,T (2577) Riga 2021} (20... a5 $11 {[%cal Ga5a4]})) (11. Be3 Nd7 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Qxe4 Nf6 15. Qd3 Nd5 16. Nc3 Re8 $44 {With an isolated pawn on d4 strong control of d5, Black's chances are not worse.}) (11. Bxe4 $6 dxe4 12. Qxe4 (12. Rxe4 $2 Bf5 $17) 12... Bxc4 $15) 11... cxd5 12. Bxe4 dxe4 13. Qxe4 {This is the main tabia after 9.Qc2 h6. We can already conclude that Black has good compensation for the pawn.} Nc6 $5 {This is what the computer suggests - I think it gives Black an easy game.} (13... Bd5 {is more popular. There can follow} 14. Qg4 Qd7 ({Black should avoid} 14... Be6 $6 15. Rxe6 $1 fxe6 16. Nc3 $14 {, when White has more than enough compensation for the exchange.}) 15. Qxd7 (15. Qh5 Nc6 $44) 15... Nxd7 16. Nc3 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Rac8 {This endgame is quite acceptable for Black. It's very difficult for White to make use of his extra pawn due to his numerous weaknesses.} 18. Be3 (18. Bd2 Nb6 $11) 18... f5 {[%csl Re4]} 19. Rac1 Rfd8 20. Nd5 (20. Kg2 Nf6) 20... Rxc1 21. Bxc1 (21. Rxc1 Nf8 22. h4 Kf7 23. Kg2 Ne6 $11) 21... Kf7 22. Ne3 Kf6 23. Bd2 Nf8 24. Nc4 Kf7 25. d5 Ng6 26. Rd1 Bc7 27. Bb4 Ne5 28. Nxe5+ Bxe5 $11) 14. Nc3 Nb4 {This is the basic idea - Black puts his knight on d5.} 15. a3 (15. Ne5 $5 {This can be an interesting try for White.} Qf6 $1 16. Bf4 {With this move, White is prepared to sacrifice an exchange.} Bf5 17. Qxb7 Rfb8 18. Qf3 Nc2 19. Nd5 Qe6 {Black has enough resources to keep the balance.} 20. Nd3 {Now things become very tactical.} ({The position after} 20. Ne3 Nxe1 21. Rxe1 Bg6 22. d5 Qf6 23. Nxg6 fxg6 24. Bxd6 Qxd6 $11 {is roughly equal.}) 20... Nxd4 21. Qg3 Qxd5 22. Bxd6 Rb6 23. Bc7 (23. Be5 {is similar.} Nf3+ $1 24. Qxf3 Qxf3 25. gxf3 Bxd3 $11) 23... Nf3+ $1 {With this, Black forces a drawish endgame.} (23... Rg6 $2 24. Nf4 $16) 24. Qxf3 Qxf3 25. gxf3 Rg6+ 26. Bg3 Bxd3 $11 {Black should hold the draw without too much trouble.}) (15. Bd2 Qd7 {Black is not worse; for example} 16. Ne5 Bxe5 17. dxe5 Nd3 18. Re2 Bf5 19. Qd5 (19. Qh4 Rae8 $11 {[%csl Re5]}) 19... Rfd8 20. Qxd7 Rxd7 $44 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Yd3b2]}) 15... Nd5 16. Bd2 (16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. Qg4 Be6 {Black is fine and can choose between different options.} (17... Qf6 $5 18. Qh5 Rfd8 $44) (17... Qc8 $5 18. Qh5 Qc6 19. Bd2 Rae8 20. Rac1 Rxe1+ 21. Rxe1 Rd8 $44) 18. Rxe6 (18. Qh5 Qd7 19. Ne5 Bxe5 20. dxe5 Rfd8 21. Be3 Qb5 $11) (18. Qe4 Bd5 $11) 18... fxe6 19. Bxh6 Qf6 20. Bd2 b5 $11) 16... Re8 $1 {This seems like the most accurate move, though 16...Rc8 was also possible.} (16... Rc8 17. Ne5 Bb8 18. Qf3 Nxc3 19. bxc3 Qd5 20. Qxd5 Bxd5 $44 {1/2-1/2 (41) Saric,I (2674) -Vachier Lagrave,M (2736) Austria 2022}) 17. h3 {Black has sustained positional compensation. White can try many different options, but none of them changes the basic assessment.} (17. Rac1 Qd7 18. Ne5 Nxc3 19. Bxc3 Qb5 20. Qf3 Qd5 21. Qxd5 Bxd5 $44) (17. Ne5 Nxc3 18. Bxc3 f6 19. Nf3 Qd7 $44) (17. Nb5 Bf8) (17. Kh1 Bf8 18. Rac1 Nxc3 19. Bxc3 Qd7 (19... Qd5 20. Qxd5 Bxd5 $44) 20. Ne5 Qb5 21. Qd3 Qd5 22. Qf3 Bd6 $44 {½- (45) ½ (45) Talibov,S (2431)-Samadov, R (2501) Baku 2025}) 17... Rc8 18. Rac1 (18. Ne5 Bb8 $44) 18... Bb8 19. Nxd5 (19. Qd3 Nxc3 20. Rxc3 Bd5 $44) 19... Qxd5 20. Qxd5 Bxd5 21. Rxc8 Rxc8 22. Nh4 (22. Re7 h5 (22... Kf8 23. Bb4 Kg8 $11) 23. Ne5 Rd8 $44) 22... Be6 23. Bc3 Bd6 24. d5 Bd7 $44 {[%csl Gd6,Gd7]} ({A last trap to avoid:} 24... Bxd5 $4 25. Rd1 $18) *

