is the critical continuation.} ({Black has no problems after} 14. Nh3 Re8 15. Bf4 (15. Nf4 Be4 16. Qg4 Qd7 $132) 15... Bxf4 16. Nxf4 Be4 17. Qh5 Qf6 $11) 14... Bxh2+ 15. Kxh2 Qh4+ 16. Qh3 Qxh3+ 17. gxh3 Bxe4 18. Rg1 Re8 $1 {Black must return his extra pawn!} ({Black loses the f7-pawn after} 18... Kh7 $2 19. Ba3 $16) (18... Bg6 $4 {is not possible due to} 19. Rxg6 $18) 19. Bxh6 g6 {White has a small initiative in this endgame, so we look at it in some detail. Black misses his dark-squared bishop, but on the plus-side, he has the more compact pawn structure.} 20. a4 (20. Rge1 Nd7 21. Bf1 c5 (21... Bf5) 22. Bb5 Bc6 23. Rxe8+ Rxe8 24. Bxc6 bxc6 25. Be3 cxd4 26. Bxd4 a6 27. Rd1 Re2 $11 {1/2-1/2 (52) Vachier Lagrave,M (2780)-Wang,H (2722) Douglas 2018}) (20. h4 b5 $5 {I like this best - Black creates active counterplay on the queenside.} ({White retained a slight pull after} 20... Nd7 21. h5 Nb6 22. Bb3 {J.Van Foreest-Esipenko,French League 2023.}) 21. Bb3 a5 22. a4 (22. a3 a4 23. Ba2 Nd7 24. h5 Kh7 $11 ({Another idea is} 24... Nb6 $5 25. hxg6 Bd5 {when Black gets sufficient compensation for the sacrificed pawn.})) 22... Nd7 23. h5 bxa4 24. Rxa4 (24. Ba2 Kh7 $11 {After the h6-bishop steps back, Black has ...Kg7.}) (24. Bxa4 Nb6) 24... Kh7 25. Bf4 Nb6 26. Raa1 Nd5 (26... Kg7) 27. hxg6+ Bxg6 $11) 20... Nd7 21. Rge1 (21. Bf1 Nf6 22. Be3 Rad8 23. c4 Nh5 24. Ra3 Ng7 $11 {Black regroups the knight to f5, with sufficient counterplay, ½-½ (29) Bernadskiy,V (2550)-Ter Sahakyan,S (2574) Villorba 2019.}) 21... Bf5 (21... a5 $5) 22. Bf1 Nf6 (22... a5) 23. c4 Rxe1 {The most straightforward way - Black goes for the exchange of all the rooks, which limits White's chances.} (23... Rad8 24. Bg5 Kg7 25. Rxe8 Rxe8 26. a5 Rd8 27. Be3 a6 28. Ra4 Ng8 29. Rb4 Rd7 30. Bg2 Ne7 31. h4 Be6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (40) Vachier Lagrave,M (2789)-Caruana,F (2822) Stavanger 2018}) 24. Rxe1 Re8 25. Rxe8+ (25. Rc1 Rd8) 25... Nxe8 {There is too little material left, and Black can keep the balance without too much trouble. For example} 26. a5 (26. Be3 a5 27. Bd2 (27. d5 Bc2 28. Bb6 Bxa4 29. Bxa5 Bb3 30. dxc6 bxc6 $11) 27... Bc2 28. Bxa5 Bxa4 29. Kg3 Nd6 30. Kf4 f6 31. Bb4 Nf5 32. d5 cxd5 33. cxd5 Kf7 34. Bc4 Ke8 $11) (26. Bd2 Be6 27. Bb4 Ng7 28. a5 b6 29. a6 Bc8 30. c5 bxc5 31. Bxc5 Ne6 32. Bxa7 Nc7 33. Bg2 Nd5 $11) 26... b6 27. axb6 (27. a6 $6 Nc7 $15) (27. Bg2 Bd7 $11) (27. Bd2 Be6 $11) 27... axb6 28. Bf4 (28. Kg3 f6 $11) (28. Be3 Be6 $11) 28... Kf8 29. Kg3 Ke7 $11) (12. Ne5 {can simply be met with} Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd7 {when Black generates sufficient counterplay to compensate White's pair of bishops.} ({We should avoid} 13... Qa5 $6 {when after the strong} 14. Bg5 $1 $14 {Black should abstain from taking either of the pawns.} Qxc3 $2 (14... Qxe5 $2 15. Re1 $18) 15. Rc1 Qa5 16. Re1 $16 {Black is too far behind with his development.} Nd7 $2 17. e6 $1 $18) 14. Ba3 (14. Re1 Nb6) 14... Re8 (14... c5 $5 15. Re1 Qa5) 15. f4 Nb6 16. Bb3 Nd5 17. Qf3 Qa5 $11) (12. h3 Nd7 $11) (12. a4 Nd7 13. Re1 h6 $11) 12... Qa5 $1 13. d5 (13. Nh4 {We can meet this with} Be6 $1 {since the g5-bishop is unprotected.} 14. Bxe6 Qxg5 15. Nf3 ({The endgame after} 15. Qg4 Qxg4 16. Bxg4 {does not promise White anything.} g6 17. Rab1 (17. Rfb1 b6 18. a4 Rd8 19. g3 (19. a5 b5) 19... Nd7 $11) 17... b6 $11) 15... Qa5 16. Bh3 $5 {This is the critical move - White prevents the development of our knight to d7.} (16. Qb3 {is simply met with} Qc7 {, followed by ...Nd7.} 17. Bh3 (17. Bc4 Nd7 18. a4 (18. Rfe1 Nf6 $11) (18. g3 Nf6 $11) 18... Nf6 (18... b6 {is also possible.}) 19. a5 g6 20. g3 Rab8 $11) 17... Nd7 18. g3 (18. Rab1 b6) (18. c4 b6 19. Bxd7 Qxd7 20. Rad1 Rfe8 $11) 18... Nf6 {Black can also play other moves - he has already equalised; the pawn structure is fine for Black.} (18... Rfe8) (18... g6) 19. c4 (19. a4 g6 20. a5 Rab8 $11) 19... b6 20. Bg2 (20. a4 a5) 20... Rfe8 21. a4 Rab8 22. Rfb1 g6 23. Ra2 a5 24. Rd1 Kg7 $11 {1/2-1/2 (35) Pappier,C (2497)-Mayer,R (2486) ICCF email 2018}) (16. Bg4 {is similar to 16. Bh3.} Qxc3 (16... Qc7 $5 17. c4 Nd7) 17. Rb1 b6 18. Qe2 Qa5 19. Rfc1 Na6 20. Rxc6 Rad8 $11) (16. Bc4 {Compared to 16.Bb3, Black can now take on c3.} Qxc3 17. Qe2 Qa5 18. Ne5 Na6 19. Bxa6 Bxe5 $11) (16. Bb3 {This move was played in the majority of games. Here we play} Nd7 {, completing the development. Taking on c3 must be avoided.} (16... Qxc3 $2 17. Ng5 $18) 17. Qd3 (17. c4 c5 $1 {This gives White a protected passed pawn, but it blocks the b3-bishop and gives Black good control of some dark squares.} 18. d5 ({Only Black can be better after} 18. dxc5 $6 Qxc5) 18... Rad8 19. g3 (19. Re1 a6 20. a4 Rfe8 $11) 19... Ne5 20. Ng5 {Transferring the knight to e4 looks logical. However, Black generates sufficient counterplay:} h6 21. Ne4 b5 22. Qc2 Nxc4 23. Bxc4 bxc4 24. Qxc4 Qb4 25. Rac1 Rfe8 26. Nxc5 Qxc4 27. Rxc4 Re2 $11) (17. Nd2 {is not dangerous - Black can simply play} Nf6 {with equal chances. For example} 18. Qf3 ({Or} 18. Nc4 Qc7 19. g3 g6 20. a4 Kg7 $11) 18... Qg5 19. Nc4 (19. Qd3 Rfe8 20. g3 Rad8 $11) 19... Qf4 20. Qxf4 (20. Qh3 Rad8 21. Na5 Rb8 $11) 20... Bxf4 21. g3 Bc7 $11) 17... Nf6 {Black's position is very solid. Still, some care is necessary, and quite often, we will improve our position by playing ...g6, ... Kg7, thereby neutralising White's pressure against f7.} 18. Rfe1 (18. Nh4 Rae8 19. Rae1 (19. Nf5 Bc7 $11) 19... g6 {Simply protecting f5 and exploiting the fact that} 20. Nxg6 {can be met with} Bxh2+ $1 21. Kxh2 Qh5+ 22. Nh4 Qxh4+ 23. Kg1 Ng4 24. Qh3 Qxh3 25. gxh3 Nf6 $11) (18. g3 {was tried in some games. For example} g6 19. h4 (19. Rae1 Rae8 20. Kg2 Kg7 21. h4 {1/2-1/2 (31) Sasikiran,K (2675)-Banusz,T (2619) Linares 2019} c5 $11) 19... Kg7 20. Kg2 (20. c4 c5 21. d5 Rae8 $11) 20... c5 (20... Rae8 $5 {is also possible - this is, in general, the typical setup for Black in this line.} 21. Rh1 Re7 22. Rae1 (22. c4 Rfe8) 22... Rfe8 23. Rxe7 Rxe7 24. c4 Qd8 $11) 21. Rh1 cxd4 22. cxd4 (22. h5 Qxc3 23. Qb5 Qc6 24. h6+ Kg8 25. Qxc6 bxc6 26. Nxd4 Rfc8 $11) 22... Rfe8 $11) (18. Rae1 Rae8 19. g3 {transposes to 18.g3.}) 18... Rae8 (18... Rfe8 19. h4) 19. g3 (19. h4 g6 {is similar.}) 19... g6 20. Kg2 (20. h4 Kg7 21. Ng5 Qd8 22. Kg2 h6 23. Ne4 Nxe4 24. Rxe4 Rxe4 25. Qxe4 Re8 26. Qf3 Qf6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (38) So,W (2770) -Grischuk,A (2777) chess24.com INT 2020}) 20... Kg7 21. h4 Rxe1 $5 $146 ({Or} 21... c5 $5 22. Rxe8 Rxe8 23. Ng5 Re7 {1/2-1/2 (62) Abdusattorov,N (2651)-Ivic, V (2610) Belgrade 2022}) 22. Rxe1 c5 {Black has more or less equalised. He has to watch out for tactics connected to Ng5 and taking on f7, but against correct play, White cannot achieve anything. Some possible continuations:} 23. Re2 (23. Ne5 cxd4 24. Qxd4 (24. Nc4 Qd5+ 25. Kg1 Bc5 26. Re5 Qc6 27. cxd4 Rd8 28. Na5 Qd6 29. Nxb7 Qxe5 30. Nxd8 Qxd4 31. Qxd4 Bxd4 $11) 24... Qc7 25. Nxf7 (25. Ng4 Qc6+ 26. f3 Bc5 $11) 25... Rxf7 26. Bxf7 Kxf7 27. Qxa7 Qc6+ 28. f3 (28. Kg1 Bc5) 28... Bc5 $11) (23. Ng5 cxd4 24. Qxd4 Qc5 25. Qxc5 Bxc5 26. Bxf7 Rxf7 27. Ne6+ Kg8 28. Nxc5 Rc7 $11) 23... Qd8 24. Ng5 (24. Qb5 Qc7) 24... Qc8 25. Re3 h6 26. dxc5 Bxc5 27. Bxf7 Qc6+ 28. Rf3 hxg5 (28... Rxf7 29. Nxf7 Kxf7 30. h5 gxh5 31. Qh7+ Ke6 32. Qxh6 Be7 $13) 29. Qxg6+ Kh8 30. Qxf6+ (30. hxg5 Nd7 31. Qf5 (31. Qxc6 bxc6 32. Bb3 Rxf3 33. Kxf3 Nb6 $11) 31... Kg7 32. g4 Qxf3+ 33. Qxf3 Rxf7 34. Qxb7 Ne5 $11) 30... Qxf6 31. Rxf6 gxh4 32. Rf5 (32. gxh4 Kg7) 32... Be7 33. Rh5+ Kg7 34. Bb3 hxg3 35. fxg3 b6 $11) 16... Qxc3 $5 {Here we can take the pawn. Black will return it at the right moment to equalise the chances.} (16... Qc7 17. c4 $14 {gives White a small advantage.}) 17. Rb1 (17. Qb1 Qb4 18. Qe4 Qa5 19. Rab1 b6 20. Rfd1 (20. Rfc1 a6 21. g3 Ra7 22. Ne5 Re7 $11) 20... Na6 $1 {Black returns the pawn to complete his development.} (20... a6 $2 21. d5 $16) 21. Qxc6 Rad8 $11) 17... b6 18. Rb3 (18. Re1 Na6 19. Qa4 Qa5 20. Qxa5 bxa5 $11) (18. Qe2 Qa5 19. Rfc1 (19. d5 Qa4 $1) 19... Na6 $1 {We have seen this already - Black gives his c-pawn to complete his development. Chances are equal after} 20. Rxc6 Rad8 21. Qc4 Nb8 22. Rc8 Qa6 $11) 18... Qa5 19. d5 {This was tried (amongst others) in the high-level encounter Praggnanandhaa-Nepomniachtchi, Candidates 2024. Now, some complications ensue:} cxd5 20. Ng5 g6 {The easiest defence. Black has enough resources to keep the balance.} (20... h6 21. Nxf7 Kxf7 22. Rd3 $13 {was played in ½-½ (44) Praggnanandhaa,R (2747)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2758) Toronto 2024}) 21. Ne6 (21. Rd3 Nc6 22. Bd7 (22. Rxd5 Bc5 23. Ne4 {½- (100) ½ (100) Cahaya,S (2184) -Madaminov,M (2501) Chess.com INT 2024} Qxa2 24. Nxc5 bxc5 25. Rxc5 Rfd8 26. Bd7 Ne7 $15) 22... Ne7 23. Qa1 d4 24. Nxh7 Kxh7 25. Qxd4 Be5 26. Qh4+ Kg7 27. Qxe7 Qc5 $11 {½-½ (27) Safarli,E (2597)-Radjabov,T (2723) Sharjah 2024}) (21. Bg4 Nc6 22. Rh3 Be5 23. Nxh7 Rfd8 24. f4 Bg7 25. f5 Rd6 26. f6 Bh8 $15) 21... Nc6 $5 {The position is very complex, but Black can already secure equal chances in several ways.} (21... fxe6 22. Bxe6+ Kg7 23. Bxd5 (23. Qd4+ Rf6 24. Rf3 Nd7 25. Bxd7 Raf8 $11) 23... Nc6 24. Bxc6 Rad8 25. Rd3 Qe5 $11) (21... Re8 $5 22. Qd4 fxe6 23. Qf6 Qc5 24. Bxe6+ Rxe6 25. Qxe6+ Kg7 26. Rf3 Qc7 27. Qf6+ Kg8 $11) 22. Nxf8 Rxf8 23. Bd7 Ne7 $44) (13. Re1 {is another logical move.} Nd7 14. Nh4 (14. Qd2 {gives Black an easy game after} Nb6 ({or} 14... Rae8 $11) 15. Bb3 Nd5 $11) (14. Qb3 b5 15. Bf1 Rfe8 {Black has good control of the light squares. The following simplification led to an equal game.} (15... Bg4) (15... Nb6) 16. c4 Be6 17. Qc2 bxc4 18. Bxc4 Bxc4 19. Qxc4 Qd5 20. Rec1 Rac8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (30) Anand,V (2783)-Caruana,F (2807) Saint Louis 2017}) 14... Rae8 {Black can afford to give up his light-squared bishop since his pawn structure is very solid.} ({Black can also play} 14... Nb6 $5 15. Bb3 Be6 {and if} 16. Bxe6 Qxg5 {similar to the line 13.Nh4.}) 15. Nxf5 (15. Rxe8 Rxe8 16. Nxf5 (16. Qb3 Be6 17. Bxe6 Rxe6 18. Nf3 h6 19. Bd2 Qa6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (50) Martinez Alcantara,J (2620)-Nyzhnyk,I (2670) Clayton 2021}) 16... Qxf5 17. h4 h6 18. Bd3 Qe6 19. Be3 (19. Bd2 Nf6 $11) 19... Nb6 $11) 15... Rxe1+ $1 (15... Qxf5 16. Be3 Nf6 17. Bd3 Qd7 {1/2-1/2 (43) Nakamura,H (2736)-Aronian,L (2773) chess24.com INT 2020} 18. g3 $14) 16. Qxe1 Qxf5 {Black's active pieces and the more compact pawn structure offset White's pair of bishops.} 17. Be3 (17. Qd2 Nf6 18. Bd3 Ne4 19. Bxe4 Qxe4 $11) (17. Bd2 Bf4 $11) (17. Bh4 Qh5 18. Bg3 Bxg3 19. hxg3 Nf6 $11 {0-1 (58) Swiercz,D (2655)-Dominguez Perez,L (2758) Saint Louis 2021}) 17... b5 18. Bf1 (18. Bb3 Nb6) 18... Nb6 $11) (13. Bd3 h6 14. Be3 Nd7 $11) (13. Qd2 Nd7 14. Rae1 (14. Rfe1 Rae8 $11) 14... Rae8 15. Bb3 Bg4 $11) (13. Bb3 Nd7 14. Nh4 (14. c4 c5 15. dxc5 Bxc5 16. Qd5 Bb6 $11) 14... Be6 15. Bd2 Rae8 $11) 13... Be4 (13... Qc5 $5 {is another decent option.}) 14. dxc6 Bxf3 (14... Nxc6 $6 15. Qxd6 Bxf3 16. Qg3 Be4 {1/2-1/2 (44) Van Foreest,J (2682) -Bogner,S (2571) Karlsruhe GER 2020} 17. Rae1 Rfe8 18. h4 $14) 15. Qxf3 Nxc6 16. Bd5 (16. Qd5 h6 $11) 16... h6 {Probably, there are other options as well, but this is good enough.} 17. Be3 (17. Bh4 Ne5 18. Qe4 Rae8 (18... Kh8 $5 19. Bxb7 Rab8) 19. Rad1 (19. Bxb7 Ng6) (19. Bg3 {1/2-1/2 (21) Ostrovskiy,A (2371) -Siddharth,J (2407) Long Island City 2022} Kh8 $11) 19... Qxc3 20. Bxb7 Ng6 21. Qc6 Qb4 22. Rxd6 Nxh4 23. Rd7 Re1 $11) 17... Rad8 $1 {This is important - Black completes his development. Next, he will try to exchange the dark-squared bishops.} ({Black ran into serious trouble after} 17... Qxc3 $6 18. Rab1 Rab8 19. Rfd1 Qe5 20. g3 Qe7 21. Bxc6 bxc6 {1-0 (50) Giri,A (2773) -Vidit,S (2723) Chess.com INT 2022 After} 22. Rxb8 Bxb8 23. Qxc6 $16 {White is clearly better due to threat of Rd7.}) 18. c4 ({If White takes on c6} 18. Bxc6 bxc6 19. Qxc6 {, then Black regains the pawn with} Be5 20. Qc5 Qxc3 21. Qxc3 Bxc3 22. Rad1 (22. Rac1 Bd4) 22... a5 $11) (18. Rad1 Qxc3 19. g3 Bc7 $11) (18. Rfd1 Bc5 $1 {In this way, Black neutralises the advantage of the pair of bishops.} 19. Bxc5 (19. c4 Bxe3 20. Qxe3 Nb4 $11) (19. Bf4 Bd6 $1 {Black insists on exchanging the dark-squared bishops.} 20. Bxc6 (20. Be3 $11) 20... Bxf4 21. Bxb7 (21. Bd5 Be5 22. Rac1 Rd6 $11) 21... Be5 22. Bd5 Qxc3 23. Bxf7+ Kh7 {White won a pawn, but it's not enough to claim an advantage.} 24. Qe4+ (24. Rxd8 Rxd8 25. Qxc3 Bxc3 26. Rb1 Rd2 $11) 24... Kh8 25. g3 Qc7 26. Rxd8 Rxd8 27. Rb1 Bxg3 28. hxg3 Qxf7 $11) 19... Qxc5 20. Rab1 (20. Bb3 Rxd1+ 21. Rxd1 Qe7 22. Kf1 Rd8 23. Re1 (23. Rd5 Rxd5 24. Bxd5 Nd8 25. Qf4 Qd7 26. c4 Kf8 $11) 23... Qc7 24. Re4 (24. g3 Na5 25. Bd5 Nc4 $11) 24... Kf8 (24... Na5 25. Bd5 Nc6 26. Qf5 Rf8 $11 {½-½ (28) Pezo,E (2252)-Jeute,V (2252) ICCF email 2021}) 25. g3 (25. Rf4 Rd7) 25... Rd7 26. Kg2 (26. Qe3 Re7) 26... Re7 27. Bd5 Ne5 28. Qf5 Qxc3 29. Re2 (29. Bxb7 Rxb7 30. Rxe5 Rc7 $11) 29... b5 (29... Qc7 30. Rc2 Qd6 31. Rc8+ Re8 32. Rxe8+ (32. Bxb7 Qd4) 32... Kxe8 33. Qc8+ Ke7 34. Qxb7+ Kf6 $11) 30. Rc2 Qd4 31. Bb3 Rd7 32. Rc8+ Ke7 33. f4 Nc4 34. Qxb5 Nd6 35. Qc5 (35. Qe2+ Qe4+ 36. Qxe4+ Nxe4 37. Ba4 Rd2+ 38. Kg1 f5 $11) 35... Qxc5 36. Rxc5 g6 $11) 20... Ne5 21. Qe4 Rfe8 {Black is prepared to sacrifice a pawn since he will always get sufficient compensation. For example} 22. Rxb7 (22. Bxb7 Qxc3 23. g3 (23. Bd5 Rd7 $11) 23... Rxd1+ 24. Rxd1 Kf8 25. Bd5 g6 26. Kg2 Kg7 $11) 22... Nf3+ 23. Qxf3 Qxd5 24. Qxd5 Rxd5 25. Rdb1 Re2 26. Rxa7 Rdd2 27. Rf1 Rc2 $1 {Black is two pawns down, however, White cannot improve his position due to Black's active rooks.} (27... Rxa2 $6 28. Rxa2 Rxa2 29. Rc1 {would offer some winning chances to White.}) 28. Ra3 g5 29. g3 (29. g4 Kg7 30. Kg2 Re6 $11) 29... Kg7 30. Kg2 Kg6 31. Kf3 h5 32. h3 f6 $11) 18... Bc5 $1 {Again, Black goes for the exchange of the dark-squared bishops.} 19. Bxc6 (19. Bxc5 Qxc5 20. Rad1 (20. Rab1 Nb4) 20... Rc8 21. Rfe1 b6 $11) (19. Bf4 Bd6 20. g3 (20. Bg3 Qc5) (20. Be3 $11) 20... Bxf4 21. Qxf4 Rd7 22. Qf5 Re7 $11) 19... bxc6 20. Qf5 {With this, White wins a pawn, but once again, Black generates sufficient compensation.} Bb6 21. Qxa5 Bxa5 22. Bxa7 Bc3 23. Rac1 (23. Rab1 Bd4 24. c5 Rd5 $11) (23. Rad1 Ra8 24. Rd7 Rfe8 25. g3 Re4 $11 {½- (36) ½ (38) Peng,X (2521)-Liu,Y (2573) Fuling 2024}) 23... Bd4 24. Bxd4 Rxd4 {Black's activity is sufficient to offset White's extra pawn.} 25. Rfd1 (25. Rc2 c5 26. Rb1 Ra8 27. g3 Ra4 $11) (25. c5 Rd2 26. a4 Ra8 27. Ra1 Ra5 $11) (25. g3 Ra8 26. Rc2 c5 $11) 25... Rxd1+ 26. Rxd1 Ra8 27. Rd2 (27. Rd6 Rxa2 28. g4 Ra6 29. c5 Kf8 $11) 27... Ra4 28. Rc2 Kf8 29. Kf1 Ke7 30. Ke2 Kd6 31. Kd3 f5 (31... Kc5) 32. Kd4 g5 33. Re2 c5+ 34. Kc3 g4 35. Rd2+ (35. Kb3 Rb4+) 35... Ke6 $11 *

