1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Bd3 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. c4 c6 9. Re1 {We have arrived at the absolute main line of the variation with 6... Bd6. The final three lessons are dedicated to 9.Re1.} Bf5 10. cxd5 {Here we look at White's less common options of move ten. We will look at 10.Qc2 and 10. Qb3 in lessons 22 and 23.} (10. Ng5 {A concrete try - White tries to utilise the pin on the e4-knight, but since this neglects the development of the queenside, Black is fine in the following complications.} Re8 11. Bxe4 dxe4 12. Nc3 Nd7 $1 {Black manages to complete his development since the pawn on e4 is indirectly protected.} 13. Ngxe4 (13. c5 Bc7 (13... h6 $5 {is also possible.}) 14. Qb3 Qe7 $5 {Black supports e4, defends f7, and indirectly defends b7!} (14... Bg6 {is also good. After} 15. Ngxe4 h6 $44 {Black has sufficient compensation.}) 15. Ngxe4 (15. Qxb7 $2 {runs into} Nxc5 $1 $17) 15... Qh4 16. g3 Qh5 {Black has excellent positional compensation due to the weakness of the light squares in White's position. For example} 17. Bd2 (17. Qxb7 Bh3 18. Re3 Be5 $1 19. Qb4 Rad8 $40) 17... Rab8 $44) (13. Ncxe4 Bxh2+ {will probably transpose to 13.Ngxe4.}) 13... Bxe4 (13... Bxh2+ $6 {is the less accurate move order. White retains some advantage after} 14. Kxh2 Bxe4 15. Kg1 Qh4 (15... Bf5 16. Bf4 $14) 16. Be3 Bf5 17. Qd2 h6 18. f3 $14 {1-0 (40) Kollars,D (2580) -Banusz,T (2620) Germany 2021}) 14. Nxe4 (14. Rxe4 {is similar.} Bxh2+ 15. Kxh2 Rxe4 16. Nxe4 Qh4+ 17. Kg1 Qxe4 18. Be3 Re8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (22) Dimitrov,D (2289) -Sneddon,I (2281) ICCF email 2020}) 14... Bxh2+ $1 {This is the point - Black regains the pawn.} 15. Kf1 ({Black has a good position after} 15. Kxh2 Qh4+ 16. Kg1 Rxe4 17. Be3 Rae8 $11 {1-0 (43) Kollars,D (2607)-Firouzja,A (2785) Chess. com INT 2023}) 15... Qa5 {Black's chances are not worse.} (15... Bc7 {is also good.}) 16. Qf3 (16. Bd2 Qf5 17. Qf3 Qxf3 18. gxf3 Bc7 $11) (16. b3 Qf5 17. g4 Qg6 18. Qf3 Re6 19. Qf5 Rae8 20. f3 Nf6 $11) 16... f5 $1 17. Nc3 Rxe1+ 18. Kxe1 Re8+ 19. Kf1 Bb8 20. Bd2 Qd8 (20... Qb6 21. Qd3 Nf6 22. Re1 Rxe1+ 23. Bxe1 g6 24. b3 Qc7 25. d5 Qd6 26. Bd2 Kf7 $11 {1/2-1/2 (47) Pastor Cutillas,A (2307) -Chmielewski,M (2368) ICCF email 2019}) 21. Re1 (21. Qxf5 Qh4) 21... Rxe1+ 22. Kxe1 Qf6 (22... g6 $11) 23. Ne2 Qe6 24. b3 Bc7 $11) (10. Nc3 {This is similar to 9.Nc3.} Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 dxc4 13. Qxc4 Nd7 {We have already seen this pawn structure - Black is doing fine here. Quite often, he continues with ...Qc7, ...b5, threatening to gain complete control of the important squares d5 and c4.} 14. Rb1 (14. Bg5 Qc7 15. Be7 {This leads to simplification and an equal position.} ({White slid into a worse position after} 15. Re2 b5 (15... Rae8) 16. Qd3 Rfe8 17. Rae1 Rxe2 18. Rxe2 Nb6 $15 {0-1 (55) Shankland,S (2708) -Aronian,L (2782) Kolkata 2021}) 15... b5 16. Qe2 Bxe7 17. Qxe7 Rfc8 18. a4 Nb6 $11) (14. Qb3 {does not change much.} b6 ({or} 14... b5 15. a4 a6 $11) 15. c4 Re8 $11) 14... Qc7 15. Qb3 b5 {- The typical strategy in these positions. If Black is allowed to play ...Nb6, he could already claim to be better.} (15... b6 16. c4 Rfe8 $11) 16. c4 bxc4 17. Qxc4 c5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (18) Anand,V (2779) -Caruana,F (2823) Saint Louis 2016}) (10. c5 {After taking the pressure off d5, White fails to pose problems.} Bc7 11. Nc3 (11. Qc2 Bg4 $5 12. Ne5 Bh5 $132) 11... Nd7 12. Qc2 Re8 13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Bg5 Nf6 (14... f6 $5 15. Bh4 Nf8) 15. Nh4 Qxd4 16. Nxf5 Qe5 17. Nh6+ gxh6 18. Bxf6 Qxh2+ 19. Kf1 Qh1+ 20. Ke2 Qh5+ $11 {1/2-1/2 (23) Jankowicz,R (2407)-Lauk,U (2386) ICCF email 2004}) 10... cxd5 11. Nc3 (11. Qb3 {can be met by the active} Nc6 $1 12. Nc3 (12. Qxb7 $2 Nb4 $19) 12... Be6 13. Qxb7 Nb4 14. Bxe4 Rb8 15. Qxa7 Ra8 $11) 11... Nxc3 12. bxc3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nd7 {In general, Black has few problems in this structure. He is very solid and will always have counterchances due to White's weaknesses on the c-file.} 14. Qf5 (14. Bg5 f6 15. Bd2 Nb6 16. Nh4 Qd7 17. Nf5 Rfe8 $11) (14. Qb5 Nb6 15. a4 a6 16. Qb3 Nc4 $1 $11 17. Qxb7 $4 Rb8 18. Qxa6 Qd7 $19) 14... Nb6 15. Ng5 {This is the most direct attempt to create problems. However, Black is in time to defend against White's threats:} g6 16. Qh3 h5 17. g4 (17. f4 Qc8 18. f5 Qxf5 19. Qxf5 gxf5 20. Rf1 Rfe8 $11) 17... Qd7 $1 18. gxh5 Rfe8 $1 {The most accurate move. Before exchanging on h3, Black neutralises White's rook on the e-file.} 19. Be3 (19. Bd2 Qxh3 20. Nxh3 gxh5 $11) ({Black has sufficient compensation after} 19. Rxe8+ Rxe8 20. Qxd7 Re1+ 21. Kg2 Nxd7 22. hxg6 fxg6 23. Nf3 Rd1 24. Bb2 Rxa1 25. Bxa1 Nb6 $44 {due to White's bad dark-squared bishop.}) 19... Qxh3 20. Nxh3 gxh5 21. Bf4 Bf8 $1 {Black has equalised.} 22. Kg2 f6 23. Reb1 Rac8 24. a4 Re7 25. a5 Nc4 $11 {1-0 (60) Dragnev,V (2565)-Cheng,B (2574) Vienna 2023} *

