1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Bd3 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. c4 c6 9. Re1 Bf5 10. Qc2 {This creates the positional threat of Nc3 since ...Nxc3 could now be met with Bxf5.} Na6 $1 {This is Black's main answer to 10.Qc2. Before playing ...Bg6, Black develops his knight with a gain of a tempo.} (10... Bg6 $5 {is another decent option.}) 11. a3 Bg6 $1 12. c5 {The only critical try. White gains space on the queenside and forces Black to temporarily misplace his bishop.} ({After} 12. b4 {Black can go for the tempting piece sacrifice} Bxb4 $5 {After} ({The more solid} 12... Re8 {is also playable.} 13. c5 Bb8 14. Nbd2 Nc7 $1 {Black can ignore the attack on e4 since he will get good compensation for the pawn.} 15. Nxe4 (15. Bb2 Nxd2 16. Rxe8+ Nxe8 17. Qxd2 Nf6 $11) 15... dxe4 16. Bxe4 (16. Rxe4 Bxe4 17. Bxe4 g6 18. g3 Qd7 $11) 16... Rxe4 $1 17. Rxe4 Qd5 18. Nd2 Ne6 {Black wins back the pawn.} 19. f3 (19. Bb2 $6 {is not recommended due to} Bf4 $1 $17) 19... Bxe4 20. Qxe4 Qxe4 21. fxe4 Nxd4 22. Bb2 Ne6 23. Nc4 Bc7 $11) 13. axb4 Nxb4 14. Qb3 Nxd3 15. Qxd3 Nxf2 16. Qb3 (16. Qc3 Nd3) 16... Nd3 17. Rd1 dxc4 18. Qxc4 b5 19. Qb3 Nxc1 20. Rxc1 Be4 $44 {Black has three pawns for the piece. The position is objectively unclear, but I feel that Black has good chances due to his strong light-squared bishop and passed pawns on the queenside.}) (12. Nc3 {With Black's light-squared bishop protected, this is harmless.} Nxc3 13. Bxg6 hxg6 14. Qxc3 dxc4 15. Qxc4 Nc7 $11) (12. Be3 {gives Black time to improve his position with} Rc8 {- Now c4-c5 can comfortably be met with ...Bb8.} 13. Nbd2 (13. c5 {leads to a good version (for Black) of the main line.} Bb8 14. Nc3 f5 15. Ne2 f4 16. Bc1 Qf6 $132) (13. Nc3 Nxc3 14. Qxc3 (14. bxc3 dxc4 15. Bxg6 hxg6 16. Qa4 Nc7 17. Qxc4 Nd5 $11) 14... Bxd3 15. Qxd3 dxc4 16. Qxc4 Nc7 $11) 13... Nxd2 (13... f5 $132) 14. Qxd2 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 dxc4 16. Qxc4 Nc7 $11 {Black has no problems - White must play accurately to not end up worse.}) 12... Bb8 $1 {[%cal Ga6c7] The best move - Black will reorganise his position with .. .Nc7-e6, etc.} 13. Nc3 (13. Nbd2 {This is less active than 13.Nc3. I like the double-edged nature of the following positions.} f5 14. Qb3 ({Giving up the light-squared bishop for the a6-knight is not a successful strategy.} 14. Bxa6 bxa6 15. Qa4 Qc8 $132) 14... Rf7 15. Nf1 (15. Bxa6 {is again not to be feared.} bxa6 16. Qa4 Qc8 17. b4 f4 $132 {1/2-1/2 (30) Williamson,H (2529)-Straka,Z (2569) ICCF email 2017}) 15... Qf6 {Black can prevent the following lines with} (15... h6 $5) 16. Bg5 $5 {This is a way to unbalance the position - White gets sufficient compensation for the piece but not more than that.} (16. Rb1 h6 $11) 16... Nxg5 17. Nxg5 Qxg5 18. Re8+ Rf8 19. Rxf8+ Kxf8 20. Qxb7 Nc7 21. Re1 Qd8 22. Ng3 a6 23. Nxf5 Bxf5 24. Bxf5 Nb5 25. Rd1 Ra7 26. Qxc6 Rf7 $11) 13... f5 14. Ne2 {White prepares Nf4.} (14. Qb3 {Another very concrete idea - White wants to make use of the pin on the a2-g8 diagonal.} Bh5 $1 {Black ignores White's threat and goes for active counterplay, which leads to a very double-edged game.} ({White is slightly better after} 14... Rf7 $6 15. g3 $14) 15. Bxe4 (15. Nxe4 fxe4 16. Bg5 (16. Rxe4 {is met with} Rxf3 $1 {, leading to a big mess.} 17. gxf3 Bxf3 {Black has dangerous counterplay against White's king.} 18. Re3 (18. h3 Bxe4 19. Bxe4 Qe7 20. Bf5 g6 21. Bg4 h5 $11) 18... Qg5+ (18... Bxh2+ $5 19. Kf1 Bg4 {is another possible line.}) 19. Kf1 Qg2+ 20. Ke1 Qg1+ 21. Bf1 Bg2 22. Qd3 Bc7 $1 {[%cal Ga8f8] The position seems very dangerous for White. Objectively, the game remains dynamically balanced. For example} 23. Qe2 (23. Bd2 $2 Rf8 $19) (23. Re7 Rf8 $44) 23... Rf8 24. f3 (24. Re7 Be4 $44) 24... Ba5+ (24... Bf4 $5) 25. b4 Nxb4 26. Qxg2 Nc2+ 27. Ke2 Qxg2+ 28. Bxg2 Nxa1 29. Kd1 Rf6 $1 30. Bf1 Rh6 31. Bb2 (31. h3 Rg6) 31... Rxh2 32. Bxa1 Rh1 33. Ke2 Rh2+ $11) (16. Bxe4 Kh8 17. Bg5 Qd7 {transposes to 16.Bg5.}) 16... Qd7 17. Bxe4 {White has won a pawn but after} Kh8 {he has to allow ... Bxf3 gxf3.} 18. Bc2 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Qh3 20. f4 {White can defend by returning the extra pawn. The resulting endgame is equal.} Qxb3 21. Bxb3 Bxf4 22. Be7 Rf7 23. Bd1 Nc7 24. Bg4 g6 $11) (15. Qxb7 $2 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Qh4 $19) 15... fxe4 16. Nxe4 Bxf3 17. gxf3 {Black has sufficient compensation due to White's weakened king position. For example} Nc7 $146 ({or} 17... Qd7 18. Ng3 h6 $44) 18. Nd6 (18. Bg5 Qd7 19. Nd6 Ne6 20. Qe3 Nxg5 21. Qxg5 Bxd6 22. cxd6 Qxd6 23. Re7 Rf7 $11) 18... b6 19. Qe3 Rf6 $11 {Black is about to play ...Ne6 with ample counterplay.}) (14. b4 $2 Nc7 $17 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc7e6,Gg6h5]}) 14... Nc7 15. Nf4 (15. Qb3 $6 {Going after the b7-pawn is not recommended at this point - Black will start a dangerous attack on the kingside.} Ne6 16. Qxb7 Be8 17. b4 (17. Bd2 a5 $17) 17... Bc7 18. Bxe4 fxe4 19. Ng5 Bd7 $1 20. Nxe6 Bxh2+ 21. Kh1 Bxe6 22. Qxc6 Bg4 23. Nc3 Rf5 $17) (15. Ne5 $2 {led to a big advantage for Black in the following email game:} Ne6 16. Bf4 Qh4 17. Bg3 Qg5 18. Nd7 Bxg3 19. hxg3 Rfe8 20. f4 Qe7 21. Ne5 Bh5 22. Bxe4 dxe4 23. Rad1 Rad8 $17 {1/2-1/2 (50) Orekhov,V (2226)-Bysina,J (2019) ICCF email 2019}) (15. Bf4 $2 Bh5 $1 $17) 15... Be8 (15... Bf7 16. Ne5 g5 17. Ne2 Ne6 18. f3 Qe7 $13 {is also possible.}) 16. Ne5 (16. h4 Qf6 17. Qb3 {Again, Black gets dangerous counterplay after this.} Ne6 $1 18. Nxe6 Qxe6 19. Ng5 (19. Qxb7 Bh5 20. Ng5 Qf6 {transposes to 19.Ng5.}) 19... Qf6 20. Qxb7 Bh5 $1 {White is able to keep the balance with best play.} 21. Qd7 (21. Be2 $6 Bxe2 22. Rxe2 h6 23. Nf3 a5 24. Bd2 Ra7 25. Qb6 Re7 $15 {[%cal Gg7g5]}) 21... Nxf2 (21... Bf7 $5 22. Bxe4 dxe4 23. Nxf7 Rxf7 24. Qc8+ Rf8 25. Qb7 h6 26. g3 Kh7 27. Qxa8 Bxg3 28. Qxf8 Bxf2+ 29. Kxf2 Qxf8 $132) 22. Kxf2 Qxd4+ 23. Be3 Qxh4+ 24. Kf1 Qh1+ $11 {1/2-1/2 (26) Francescone, G (2332)-Sneddon,I (2335) ICCF email 2020}) (16. Bf1 {White vacates d3 for his knight. After} g5 17. Nd3 Ne6 18. b4 g4 19. Nfe5 Qf6 20. Qb2 Bc7 $132 {the position is complicated with chances for both sides.}) (16. Qb3 $6 g5 $15) 16... g5 $1 {This was tested in several email games and also in the high-level encounter Vidit-Nepomniachtchi.} 17. Ne2 Ne6 18. f3 Qf6 $1 {Black can ignore the attack on his knight.} 19. fxe4 fxe4 20. Ng4 Qg6 {Black will regain the piece. The following complications have already been worked out until deep into the endgame!} 21. Bxe4 (21. Bc4 h5 22. Ne5 Nxd4 23. Nxg6 Nxc2 24. Nxf8 dxc4 $132) 21... Qxe4 22. Qxe4 dxe4 23. Be3 (23. Ng3 {leads to another forcing line that can end with perpetual check.} Nxd4 24. Rxe4 Nb3 25. Nh6+ Kg7 26. Ngf5+ Kg6 27. Re6+ Rf6 28. Ne7+ Kg7 29. Nef5+ Kg6 $11) (23. Nc3 Nxd4 24. Nxe4 Nc2 25. Bxg5 ({Vidit chose to test Nepomniachtchi with} 25. Bd2 {, however, Black was well prepared for the following complications:} Nxe1 26. Rxe1 h5 27. Nh6+ Kg7 28. Nxg5 Kg6 29. Re7 Bf4 $1 30. Re6+ Kxg5 31. g3 {1/2-1/2 (52) Vidit, S (2719)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2779) Baku 2023} h4 $1 32. Bxf4+ Rxf4 33. gxf4+ Kxf4 34. Nf7 Bxf7 35. Rf6+ Ke4 36. Rxf7 b6 $11) 25... h5 26. Nef6+ Kf7 27. Rf1 {White's compensation is only enough for a draw.} Nxa1 28. Nd7+ Kg6 29. Nxf8+ Kxg5 30. Ne6+ Kg6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (30) Bolhari,O (2309)-Skeels,J (2298) ICCF email 2018} ({or} 30... Kxg4 31. h3+ Kh4 32. Rc1 $11)) 23... Bh5 24. Nf2 (24. h3 Bf4 25. Nc3 Rad8 $11) 24... Bf4 {After reactivating the bishop, Black has nothing to complain about.} 25. Ng3 Bxg3 26. hxg3 Bg6 27. Ng4 Rad8 $11 {Kuhne,D (2469)-Bobykin,K (2479) LSS email 2018.} *

