1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Bd3 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. c4 c6 9. Re1 Bf5 10. Qb3 Qd7 ({Another popular continuation is} 10... Na6) 11. c5 {This is the most important continuation nowadays.} (11. Nc3 {was played extensively in the past.} Nxc3 12. Bxf5 Qxf5 {Now, White has two serious options:} 13. Qxb7 {This leads to unbalanced positions with queen versus two rooks in the main line, while 13.bxc3 is a more positional alternative. Black needs to know some theory against both lines.} (13. bxc3 b6 (13... dxc4 $2 14. Qxb7 $16) 14. cxd5 (14. h3 dxc4 15. Qxc4 b5 16. Qb3 Nd7 $11) (14. Bg5 dxc4 15. Qxc4 b5 16. Qb3 Nd7 17. a4 a6 18. Be7 {1/2 (18) Svidler,P (2727)-Nisipeanu,L (2678)/Baku 2015/CBM 169} Bxe7 19. Rxe7 Nb6 $11) 14... cxd5 15. Qb5 {This is the only way to pose problems. Other moves allow Black to develop his knight.} (15. Ne5 Nd7 $11) (15. Ba3 Bxa3 16. Qxa3 Nc6 17. h3 (17. h4 h6) (17. Re3 Rae8 18. Rae1 Rxe3 19. Rxe3 Na5 $11) 17... Qd7 18. Ne5 Nxe5 19. Rxe5 Rae8 20. Rae1 Re6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (21) Svidler,P (2728)-Kramnik,V (2766) Wijk aan Zee 2007}) (15. Nh4 Qh5 16. g3 Nc6 17. Ng2 Na5 $11) 15... Qd7 $1 {The only move.} (15... Nd7 $2 16. Qc6 $18 {already wins for White.}) 16. a4 ({Against} 16. Rb1 {, Black solves his problems with} Rd8 $1 (16... Rc8 17. g3) (16... Nc6 17. g3) 17. g3 (17. a4 h6 18. g3 Qb7 19. a5 Nd7 20. a6 Qc8 21. Qxd5 Nf6 22. Qb3 Qxa6 $132 {1/2-1/2 (70) Lagno,K (2547)-Koneru,H (2586) Chess.com INT 2022}) 17... Qxb5 18. Rxb5 Na6 $1 {Black can afford to sacrifice the d5-pawn.} 19. Rxd5 (19. Bd2 {allows Black to consolidate with} Nc7 20. Rb2 b5 21. Reb1 Kf8 22. h4 Rab8 23. h5 Rb6 $11) 19... Nc7 20. Rh5 Rac8 {Black's compensation is based on counterplay against the weakness on c3 and the awkward position of White's rook.} 21. Bd2 g6 22. Rh4 Nd5 23. Rc1 Rc4 $44 {0-1 (62) Dominguez Perez,L (2754)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2766) Zagreb 2022}) 16... Qxb5 17. axb5 a5 $1 {Black turns the backward a-pawn into a protected passed pawn.} 18. Nh4 {White's only hope lies in attacking the d5-pawn.} (18. bxa6 Nxa6 $11 {leads to equality.}) 18... g6 19. g4 {White prepares Ng2-e3.} ({Carlsen, playing this with the white pieces, ended up worse after} 19. Bh6 $6 Rc8 20. g4 Nd7 21. Ng2 Rxc3 22. Ne3 {1/2-1/2 (46) Carlsen,M (2853)-Deac,B (2700) Warsaw 2023} Rd3 $17) 19... Nd7 20. Ng2 Nf6 $146 {This is my suggestion - this is the easiest method for Black.} (20... Rfc8 {was played by Nepomniachtchi - this is also sufficient:} 21. Bf4 Bxf4 22. Nxf4 Rxc3 23. Nxd5 Rd3 24. Re7 Nf8 25. Nf6+ Kg7 26. Ne8+ Kg8 27. d5 a4 $11 {1/2-1/2 (33) Carlsen,M (2855)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2782) Dubai 2021}) 21. Bh6 Rfc8 (21... Bxh2+ $5 {also deserves attention.} 22. Kh1 Bd6 23. Bxf8 Kxf8 24. Ne3 Bf4 $44 {Black has sufficient compensation according to the computer.}) 22. Ne3 Rxc3 23. g5 Nd7 24. Nxd5 Rc4 25. Re4 a4 26. Kg2 (26. Rae1 Rcc8) 26... a3 27. Rae1 Rcc8 28. R4e2 Kh8 $11 {It's hard to make progress for both sides. Black has to keep his back rank defended while White has to keep the a-pawn in check.}) 13... Ne4 $5 {After this, a position with queen against two rooks will arise.} (13... Qd7 14. Qxd7 Nxd7 15. c5 Bxh2+ 16. Nxh2 Ne4 $14 {may be possible, but White's position is easier to play.}) 14. Qxa8 (14. c5 $6 {This is risky for White.} Bxh2+ $1 15. Kxh2 Nd7 16. Qxc6 (16. Be3 Ndf6) 16... Ndf6 17. Kg1 Ng4 18. Be3 (18. Rf1 Rae8) 18... Qh5 19. Qd7 Rad8 20. Qe7 f5 21. Qh4 Qxh4 22. Nxh4 f4 23. Bc1 Ngxf2 24. Nf3 Rde8 25. Ne5 Re6 $15) 14... Qd7 15. cxd5 cxd5 ({Black fails to trap White's queen after} 15... Nf6 $6 16. Re3 $1 Nxd5 17. Rb3 Nb4 18. Rxb4 Bxb4 19. Be3 {- White retains some advantage:} Bd6 (19... Na6 $2 20. Ne5 $18) 20. d5 c5 21. b4 cxb4 22. Rc1 (22. h3) 22... Rd8 23. Qxa7 {1/2-1/2 (73) Karjakin,S (2781)-Caruana,F (2808) Stavanger 2017} Bf8 24. Rd1 Qxa7 25. Bxa7 Nd7 26. Bd4 f6 $14) 16. Rxe4 Nc6 17. Qxf8+ Kxf8 {This is the basic position of the line beginning with 13.Qxb7. Materially speaking, White can be quite happy since he has two rooks and a pawn for the queen. However, practice has shown that Black can generate sufficient counterplay with ...f6, ...g5, ...Ne7-f5, etc. If White prevents ... g5 with h4, then ...Qg4 will be annoying.} 18. Re2 (18. Re3 f6 19. Bd2 (19. h4 Qg4 $132) 19... g5 20. h3 (20. Rc1 $2 g4 21. Nh4 Nxd4 $17) (20. Bc3 Ne7 21. Rae1 Nf5 22. Re6 Kf7 $11) 20... h5 21. Rc1 Ne7 22. Rb3 Nf5 23. Bb4 Bxb4 24. Rxb4 Kf7 $11) (18. Re1 f6 19. Bd2 g5 20. Bc3 h5 21. h3 Ne7 22. a3 Nf5 23. Bb4 g4 24. hxg4 hxg4 25. Nh2 g3 $11) 18... f6 19. Bd2 (19. h4 $6 Qg4 20. Be3 Ne7 $15) 19... g5 20. Bc3 {1/2-1/2 (23) Ragger,M (2669)-Nguyen,T (2548) Germany 2021} (20. h3 h5) 20... Ne7 21. Rae1 Nf5 {A typical position for this line. White's rooks cannot enter the opponent's camp and his queenside pawns are not going to advance soon. On the other hand, Black always has counterplay on the kingside. For example} 22. h3 (22. Re6 Kf7 23. h3 h5 $11) (22. Nd2 Kf7 23. Nf1 h5 24. Ng3 Ng7 $11) 22... h5 23. a3 Kg7 24. Nd2 Kg6 25. Nf1 Bf4 26. Re8 (26. g3 Bd6 27. Kg2 Ng7 $132) (26. Re6 h4 27. Nh2 Bxh2+ 28. Kxh2 Nd6 29. Re7 Qa4 $11) 26... h4 27. Rg8+ (27. Bd2 Bd6) 27... Kh7 28. Ree8 (28. Rf8 Kg7) 28... Qa4 29. Rgf8 Kg7 30. Bb4 Qd1 $11 {White managed to enter, but so did Black's queen - the position remains balanced.}) ({Against this, we can go for a very concrete solution:} 11. Be3 dxc4 (11... Na6 $5) 12. Bxc4 (12. Qxc4 Na6 13. a3 Nf6 $11) 12... b5 {Next, we play ...Na6, followed by ...Nc7, ...Nb4, or - in case White plays Ne5 - ...Nc5.} 13. Bd3 (13. Bf1 Na6 14. Ne5 (14. Nbd2 Nb4 $11) 14... Qc7 15. Nd2 (15. Rc1 Nac5 $1 $11) (15. Nc3 Nb4 $11) 15... Nac5 $1 {Thanks to the knight on e5, Black can activate his a6-knight with tempo.} 16. Qd1 Nxd2 17. Qxd2 Rad8 18. Qc1 Rc8 $11) 13... Na6 14. a3 Rfe8 $146 {This is an improvement over a game Caruana-Moussard.} (14... Bg6 15. Nh4 Rfe8 16. Nxg6 hxg6 17. Nc3 (17. g3 Nc7 18. Qc2 Nf6 19. Nd2 Nfd5 $11) 17... Nxc3 18. bxc3 {1-0 (47) Caruana, F (2764)-Moussard,J (2644) Chess.com INT 2023 Black could have held the balance with the accurate} Nc7 $1 19. a4 (19. Bxg6 $6 Bxh2+ 20. Kxh2 Qd6+ $15) 19... a5 20. Bd2 b4 21. Bxg6 Nd5 22. Rxe8+ Rxe8 23. Bd3 bxc3 24. Bxc3 Nxc3 25. Qxc3 Bb4 26. Qc4 Qd5 27. Qxd5 cxd5 28. Kf1 Rc8 $11) 15. Qc2 ({One important point of 14...Re8 can be seen after} 15. Nh4 Be6 $1 16. Qc2 Bd5 $11) (15. Nbd2 Nxd2 16. Bxd2 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 Nc7 $11) 15... Bg6 16. Nc3 (16. Nh4 Nf6 17. Nxg6 hxg6 18. Nd2 c5 $1 {Black gets rid of the potentially weak c6-pawn and equalises.} 19. dxc5 Nxc5 20. Bxc5 Bxc5 21. Qxc5 Qxd3 $11) (16. h4 Nf6 17. Bxg6 hxg6 18. Nbd2 Rac8 $11) 16... Nxc3 ({Also possible is} 16... Nf6 17. Bg5 Nc7 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. Ne4 Nd5 $11 {Black equalises thanks to his strong knight in the centre.}) 17. Bxg6 hxg6 18. Qxc3 Rac8 19. Rac1 c5 20. dxc5 Nxc5 $11 {Black has fully equalised.}) (11. a3 {gives Black the chance to play the useful} Re8 {Now, White again has a choice:} 12. Nc3 (12. Qc2 Bg6 13. c5 (13. Nc3 Nxc3 14. Rxe8+ Qxe8 15. Qxc3 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 dxc4 17. Qxc4 Nd7 $11) 13... Bc7 {We can compare this to 10.Qc2. Here, Black is one tempo up, but the queen blocks d7. However, it will not be too difficult for Black to improve his queen and complete his development.} 14. Nc3 (14. Nbd2 Nf6 $5 {Black can choose between this solid continuation and the more complicated 14...f5.} (14... f5 15. Ne5 Bxe5 16. dxe5 Qe7 17. b4 Nd7 18. f4 a5 19. Nb3 axb4 20. axb4 Rxa1 21. Nxa1 Nf8 22. Nb3 Ne6 $11) 15. b4 a6 16. Bb2 Qc8 17. Rxe8+ Nxe8 18. Re1 Nd7 $11) 14... Nxc3 15. Qxc3 Rxe1+ {This is the simplest.} ({Also possible is} 15... Be4 16. Bf1 Qf5 17. Nh4 Qf6 18. g3 Nd7 19. Bh3 Nf8 20. f3 Bg6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (57) Usmanoff,R (2134)-Koronowski,H (2065) LSS email 2020}) 16. Nxe1 Qe6 $11 {Black completes his development with ...Nd7 - the position is equal.}) (12. Nbd2 h6 {Black plays a useful move, waiting for White to show his hand.} 13. Nf1 (13. Qc2 Nxd2 14. Rxe8+ Qxe8 15. Bxd2 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 dxc4 17. Qxc4 Nd7 18. Re1 Qd8 $11) 13... dxc4 14. Bxc4 Na6 $11) (12. Bf1 dxc4 13. Bxc4 Na6 $11) (12. Be3 {is simply met with} dxc4 13. Qxc4 (13. Bxc4 Na6 14. Nc3 Nxc3 (14... b5 15. Bf1 Nc7 $11) 15. bxc3 b5 16. Bf1 Nc7 $11) 13... Nf6 {Black equalises without problems.} 14. Nc3 Be6 15. Qa4 Qc7 $11) 12... Na6 {Black completes his development.} 13. cxd5 {This leads to several exchanges and equality.} (13. Qc2 {is well met with} Bg4 $1 14. Ne5 Bxe5 15. dxe5 Nac5 {, giving Black an active game.} 16. cxd5 Nxd3 17. Qxd3 Nxc3 18. Qxc3 cxd5 $11) 13... Nxc3 14. Rxe8+ Rxe8 15. Qxc3 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 cxd5 $11) (11. Nh4 Be6 12. Qc2 ({After} 12. c5 {Black has no trouble mobilising his pieces.} Bc7 13. Nf3 (13. Nc3 Na6 {probably transposes.}) 13... Na6 14. Nc3 Rae8 $132) (12. Nc3 {allows Black to equalise with the simple} Nxc3 13. bxc3 dxc4 14. Bxc4 Bxc4 15. Qxc4 Na6 $11) 12... Na6 (12... f5 $5 {is similar.}) 13. a3 (13. cxd5 cxd5 14. a3 f5 15. Nc3 {transposes to 13.a3.}) 13... f5 14. cxd5 {Otherwise, Black exchanges on c4.} (14. Nc3 Nxc3 15. Qxc3 dxc4 16. Bxc4 Bxc4 17. Qxc4+ Qf7 $11) (14. Nf3 dxc4 (14... Rae8 $11) 15. Bxc4 Bxc4 16. Qxc4+ Qf7 17. Qxf7+ Rxf7 $11) 14... cxd5 15. Nc3 ({After} 15. Nf3 $6 Rac8 16. Nc3 Nb8 $1 $15 {Black has already the better game.}) 15... Nb8 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6] This is important - the knight had nothing to do on a6, but thanks to 14.cxd5 the c6-square has become available.} 16. f3 (16. Be3 Nc6 17. f3 {transposes.}) 16... Nc6 $1 17. Be3 {This is the critical line; now Black needs to be precise:} ({White cannot keep the extra piece after} 17. fxe4 Nxd4 18. Qd1 dxe4 {Now, White's best chance is to return the piece with} 19. Nxe4 {, leading to an approximately equal position.} fxe4 20. Bxe4 Nb3 $132) 17... Nxc3 18. bxc3 Be7 $1 {This, in combination with ...Bg5 on the next move, allows Black to obtain equal chances.} 19. Bf2 ({Black has at least a draw after} 19. g3 Bxh4 20. gxh4 f4 $5 (20... Rac8 {is an alternative.}) 21. Bxh7+ Kh8 22. Bf2 Bg4 $5 (22... Rf6 23. Bd3 Rg8 $44) 23. fxg4 Qxg4+ 24. Kh1 Qf3+ $11) 19... Bg5 $1 20. Re2 (20. Bg3 Rac8) 20... g6 21. Rae1 Bf7 22. g3 Rfe8 $11) (11. Nbd2 {poses not problems at all.} Nxd2 12. Bxd2 (12. Nxd2 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 dxc4 14. Nxc4 Na6 $11) 12... Bxd3 13. Qxd3 dxc4 14. Qxc4 Na6 15. Rad1 Nc7 $11) 11... Bc7 12. Nc3 $5 (12. Nh4 {does not make much sense at this point.} Be6 13. Nc3 Na6 $132) (12. g3 Ba5 $5 {I like this continuation - protecting b7 with a gain of tempo.} ({Also possible are:} 12... a5) (12... b6) (12... Re8) 13. Re3 {White has some choice, but Black is doing fine in any case.} (13. Re2 Na6 14. Ne5 Qe6 15. f3 Nexc5 $1 16. dxc5 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 Nxc5 18. Qc2 Rfe8 19. Nc3 Bxc3 20. Qxc3 Nd7 21. Nxd7 Qxe2 22. Bh6 gxh6 23. Nf6+ Kf8 24. Nxh7+ $11) (13. Nbd2 Re8 14. Qc2 Na6 15. a3 Nxd2 16. Bxd2 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 Bxd2 18. Qxd2 Nc7 $11) (13. Bd2 Bxd2 14. Nbxd2 Nxd2 15. Nxd2 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Na6 $11) (13. Ne5 $6 Qd8 {[%cal Gb8d7]}) (13. Nc3 Nxc3 14. Ne5 Qc8 15. bxc3 f6 16. Bxf5 Qxf5 17. Nf3 (17. Qxb7 $2 fxe5 18. Be3 Nd7 19. Qxc6 Bxc3 20. Qxd5+ Kh8 $19 {0-1 (20) De Winter,A (2413)-Suyarov,M (2405) Chess.com INT 2024}) 17... Qxf3 18. Qxb7 Bxc3 19. Re7 Qf5 20. Rxg7+ Kh8 21. Bh6 Bxa1 22. g4 Qc2 23. Rg5 Qc1+ 24. Kg2 Qxg5 25. Bxg5 fxg5 26. Qxa8 Bxd4 27. Qxa7 Rxf2+ 28. Kh1 $11) 13... Re8 {Black is quite active and his chances are not worse at all.} 14. Bd2 {This leads to some exchanges resulting in equality.} (14. Nh4 Be6 15. f3 Ng5 $1 16. Bd2 (16. Nf5 $6 b6 $15) 16... Bd8 17. f4 Ne4 18. f5 Bxf5 19. Nxf5 Qxf5 20. Bxe4 dxe4 21. Nc3 Bf6 22. Rf1 Qd7 23. Rxf6 gxf6 24. Nxe4 Re6 25. Nd6 Rxe3 26. Bxe3 Na6 $132) (14. Nc3 Na6 $132) (14. Qa3 Bc7 $132) 14... Bxd2 15. Nbxd2 Nxd2 16. Rxe8+ Qxe8 17. Nxd2 Bxd3 18. Qxd3 Nd7 19. Nf3 Nf8 $11) (12. Nbd2 {White puts e4 under pressure. The drawback of this move lies in obstructing the c1-bishop.} Re8 $5 (12... Be6 {is another good move.}) 13. Nh4 (13. Qc2 Na6 (13... h6 $5) 14. a3 Re6 $1 {Black can simply mobilise his pieces since White cannot win a pawn by taking on e4.} 15. Nf1 (15. b4 Rae8 $11) (15. Nh4 $2 Nexc5 $1 $19) (15. Nxe4 $6 dxe4 16. Rxe4 (16. Bxe4 $2 Rae8 17. Ne5 $8 Qxd4 $17) 16... Bxe4 17. Bxe4 g6 $15) 15... Rae8 {Black is doing great. Next, he will bring the a6-knight into the game.} 16. b4 Bg6 17. Be3 Qd8 18. Rab1 Nb8 19. b5 f5 20. Qc1 Nd7 21. Bf4 Bxf4 22. Qxf4 Bh5 $11) (13. Nf1 h6 {A useful move in any case.} (13... a5 $5) 14. Ng3 (14. Nh4 Bh7 15. f3 Bd8 $1 16. g3 Nf6 $11) 14... Bh7 (14... Bg6 $5 15. Bd2 a5 {is also possible.}) 15. Be3 (15. Re2 b6 {This leads to more complicated play than 15...Qc8. Black prepares to take on c5, followed by ...a5 and ...Na6.} (15... Qc8 {, preparing ...Nd7, is also possible. For example} 16. Nd2 Nxg3 17. Rxe8+ Qxe8 18. Bxh7+ Kxh7 19. hxg3 Qc8 20. Nf3 Nd7 $11) 16. Be3 bxc5 17. dxc5 a5 18. Rae1 (18. Qb7 Na6 $11) (18. Bd4 Na6 $11) (18. Qc2 f5) 18... Na6 {Black has counterplay against c5.} 19. Bd4 Bxg3 20. hxg3 Naxc5 21. Bxc5 Nxc5 22. Rxe8+ Rxe8 23. Rxe8+ Qxe8 24. Bxh7+ Kxh7 25. Qc3 Nb7 26. b4 axb4 27. Qxb4 $11 {Black has an extra pawn, but White is active enough to keep the balance.}) 15... Qc8 16. Nd2 Nd7 {Black has solved his problems.} 17. Ndxe4 dxe4 18. Bc4 Bg6 19. d5 cxd5 20. Bxd5 Bxg3 21. hxg3 Nxc5 22. Qb5 Re5 $11) 13... Be6 14. Qc2 (14. Qd1 $6 f5 15. f3 Nf6 $15) (14. Nf1 Qe7 15. g3 b6 16. f3 Ng5 17. Qc2 g6 $132) 14... Na6 (14... f5 15. f3 {also leads to unclear play.}) 15. a3 (15. Nxe4 $6 {is quite risky since White will be forced to exchange his light-squared bishop.} dxe4 16. Bxe4 Nb4 17. Bxh7+ Kh8 18. Qd2 Kxh7 19. Qxb4 Bd5 20. h3 Rh8 $1 $40 {Black's counterplay on the kingside looks quite dangerous.}) 15... Bg4 $1 {An important resource, which initiates some complications.} 16. Nxe4 (16. b4 Ng5 $1 17. Rxe8+ Rxe8 18. Nf1 Qe7 $11) (16. Re3 Ng5 $5 $146 {Black prepares ...Ne6, hitting d4.} (16... Qd8 $5 {is also quite possible.} 17. Ndf3 f5 18. h3 Bxf3 19. Nxf3 Qf6 $11) ({White had a slight advantage after} 16... Bd8 17. Nhf3 Bf6 {0-1 (66) Saric,I (2674) -Bluebaum,M (2651) Austria 2022} 18. h3 Bf5 19. b4 Nc7 20. Bb2 $14) 17. Nf1 (17. Nb3 h6 $11) 17... Ne6 $1 {Black goes for a counterattack against d4. The following forced line leads to an unbalanced, approximately equal endgame.} 18. Bxh7+ Kh8 19. Bf5 (19. Qd3 Qd8) 19... Nxd4 $1 20. Bxd7 Nxc2 21. Bxe8 (21. Rxe8+ Rxe8 22. Bxe8 Nxa1 23. Bxf7 Nxc5 $11) 21... Nxe3 22. Bxf7 Nxf1 23. Kxf1 Nxc5 $11) (16. f3 $2 Bd8 $1 $15) 16... dxe4 17. Rxe4 (17. Bxe4 f5 18. h3 fxe4 19. hxg4 Qxg4 20. g3 Rad8 $132) 17... Rxe4 18. Bxe4 Qxd4 {Attack and counterattack balance each other out - the game remains dynamically balanced in the following complications.} 19. Be3 (19. Bxh7+ Kh8 20. Be3 (20. g3 Re8 (20... Qxc5 $11) 21. Be3 Rxe3 22. fxe3 Qxe3+ 23. Kg2 g6 24. Bxg6 fxg6 25. Qxg6 Qe2+ 26. Kg1 Be5 $11) 20... Qf6 21. g3 g6 22. Bxg6 (22. Qe4 Qe6 23. Bxg6 fxg6 24. Nxg6+ Kg7 25. Bd4+ Kf7 26. Ne5+ Bxe5 27. Bxe5 Qf5 $132) 22... fxg6 23. Bd2 Qf7 (23... Bf5 24. Nxf5 Qxf5 25. Bc3+ Kg8 26. Qb3+ Qf7 27. Qxb7 Rf8 28. Bd4 Qc4 29. Be3 Qb5 30. Qxb5 cxb5 31. c6 $11) 24. Nxg6+ Kg8 25. Re1 Re8 26. Rxe8+ Qxe8 27. Ne7+ Qxe7 28. Qg6+ Qg7 29. Qe8+ $11) 19... Qf6 20. Nf3 (20. g3 g6 $11) (20. Nf5 h6) (20. Bxh7+ Kh8 {transposes to 19.Bh7+.}) 20... Bxf3 (20... Re8 21. Nd2 g6 $11) 21. Bxf3 Be5 22. Rd1 (22. Qb3 Qe7 23. Re1 Bf6 24. Qc2 Nc7 $11) 22... Rd8 23. Rxd8+ (23. b4 Nc7) 23... Qxd8 24. g3 Nc7 25. b4 (25. Qb3 Qc8) 25... Ne6 26. Qe4 Bd4 27. Bg4 Bxe3 28. Qxe3 Nd4 $11) (12. Qc2 {This is similar to 10.Qc2, though here Black's task seems rather simple - prepare the development of the knight to d7 and equalise. It seems that White cannot do much about this.} Re8 13. Be3 Qd8 {[%cal Gb8d7]} (13... h6 $5 14. Nc3 Qd8 15. Ne5 Nd7 16. f3 Nxe5 17. dxe5 Bg6 18. Bxe4 dxe4 19. f4 Qh4 $11) 14. Nbd2 (14. Nc3 Nd7 15. Nd2 Nf8 $11) 14... Nd7 15. Bg5 (15. Ng5 Ndf6) 15... f6 16. Be3 (16. Bh4 Nf8 17. Nxe4 $2 dxe4 18. Bxe4 Rxe4 $1 19. Rxe4 Qd5 20. Nd2 (20. Rae1 Re8 21. Nd2 Ba5 $17) 20... Bf4 21. f3 Bxd2 22. Qxd2 Bxe4 23. fxe4 Qxe4 $15) 16... Bg6 17. Nxe4 (17. Nh4 f5 18. Nxg6 hxg6 $132) 17... dxe4 18. Bc4+ Kh8 19. Nh4 Bh5 20. Nf5 (20. Qb3 Nf8) 20... Bg6 $11) 12... Re8 $1 ({Less clear is} 12... Nxc5 13. Bxf5 Nxb3 14. Bxd7 Nxa1 15. Bf5 {White will eventually pick up the knight on a1, when I prefer his chances.}) 13. Be3 {Here, White has many possible options, but in my opinion, the only critical ones are 13.Be3 and 13.Ne2.} (13. Ne2 h6 $1 {The most accurate move.} 14. Bf4 (14. Ng3 Bg6 ({Similar is} 14... Bh7 15. Be3 Qc8 $11) 15. Be3 (15. Nh4 Bh7 $11) 15... Qc8 {Next, we simply want to develop the knight to d7.} 16. Nh4 (16. Qc2 Nd7 $11) 16... Bh7 17. f3 {White can try this pawn sacrifice.} Nxg3 18. Bxh7+ Kxh7 19. hxg3 Bxg3 20. Bf2 Bxf2+ 21. Kxf2 Nd7 {White has some compensation for the pawn, but Black can neutralise the opponent's initiative.} 22. Rxe8 ({After} 22. Nf5 Re6 23. Qd3 {Black has the cold-blooded reply} Qd8 $5 {, when White has not more than a draw.} 24. Nxh6+ Kxh6 25. Rxe6+ fxe6 26. Rh1+ Kg5 27. Qe3+ Kf6 28. Rh6+ gxh6 29. Qxh6+ $11) 22... Qxe8 23. Re1 (23. Qxb7 $6 Qd8 $15) (23. Nf5 $6 Qe6 $15) 23... Qd8 24. Nf5 g6 25. Nd6 {Now Black can force a draw.} Qh4+ 26. Kf1 Qh1+ $11) (14. Be3 {transposes to 13.Be3.}) (14. Qc2 Qe7 (14... Qc8 $5) 15. Bf4 (15. Ng3 Bg6 16. Qb3 b6 $132) 15... Bxf4 16. Nxf4 Nd7 $11) 14... Bxf4 15. Nxf4 Qc7 $1 {The most logical move - Black attacks f4 and vacates d7 for his knight.} 16. Nxd5 $5 {An interesting try, but it's not enough for an advantage. Black is doing fine in any case:} (16. g3 g5 $1 17. Ng2 Nd7 18. Qc2 Nf8 19. Nd2 Qd7 $11) (16. Nh5 Nd7 17. Nh4 Bh7 18. f3 Qd8 $1 19. g3 Nef6 20. Bxh7+ Kxh7 21. Rxe8 Qxe8 22. Nxf6+ Nxf6 23. Nf5 Qe6 24. Nd6 Ne8 $11) (16. Ne2 Nd7 $11) 16... cxd5 17. Qxd5 Qd7 $1 18. Rxe4 $1 Bxe4 19. Bxe4 Qxd5 20. Bxd5 Nc6 21. Bxc6 (21. Rd1 Rad8) (21. Bb3 Rad8 22. d5 Na5 23. d6 Nxb3 24. axb3 Re4 $11) 21... bxc6 22. Ne5 Re6 {White has two extra pawns for the exchange. Black can generate enough counterplay to keep the balance. For example} 23. f4 g6 24. g4 Rd8 25. f5 Rf6 26. Rd1 gxf5 27. gxf5 Kf8 $11) (13. Bg5 Na6 14. Bh4 Bg6 $11) ({After} 13. g3 {Black can start active counterplay with} b6 $1 (13... h6 $5) 14. Qc2 (14. cxb6 axb6 15. Bf1 h6 $11) 14... Na6 $1 15. a3 bxc5 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Rxe4 Bxe4 18. Bxe4 Rxe4 19. Qxe4 Re8 20. Qd3 Qd5 21. Bd2 Nb8 $11) (13. a3 Na6 14. Be3 (14. Qc2 {transposes.}) 14... Bg4 {Again, this active move. The complications are fine for Black:} 15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. Ng5 Bf5 17. Qc2 Bg6 18. Rad1 Rad8 19. Ngxe4 f5 20. Ng5 f4 21. Qb3+ Bf7 22. Qc2 ({After} 22. Qxf7+ Qxf7 23. Nxf7 Kxf7 24. Bc1 {Black regains the pawn with} Rxd4 $11) 22... Bg6 $11) (13. Qc2 Na6 14. a3 Bg4 $1 {Black answers the attack against e4 with a counterattack against f3.} 15. Nxe4 (15. Ne5 {leads to an equal position.} Bxe5 16. dxe5 Naxc5 17. Nxe4 dxe4 18. Bxe4 Nxe4 19. Qxe4 $11) 15... dxe4 16. Rxe4 {Now Black has at least a draw.} Bxf3 17. gxf3 Qh3 18. f4 Qg4+ 19. Kf1 Qh3+ $11) (13. Bf1 h6 $11) 13... h6 $1 14. Nh4 (14. Qc2 {After this, Black equalises by playing} Bh7 15. Nd2 (15. b4 Qd8 $11) 15... Nf6 {, exchanging the light-squared bishops and afterwards preparing ...Nd7.} 16. Bxh7+ Nxh7 17. b4 Qd8 18. Nf3 (18. b5 Nd7 19. Qa4 Ba5 $11) 18... Nd7 19. b5 Ndf8 $11) ({After} 14. Ne2 $5 {it's important to play} Qc8 $1 {[%cal Gb8d7] , protecting b7 and preparing ...Nd7.} 15. Nh4 (15. Bf4 Nd7 $11) (15. Ng3 Bh7 $11) 15... Be6 16. Nf4 (16. f3 $2 Nxc5 17. dxc5 d4 18. Qb4 dxe3 19. Qe4 f5 20. Nxf5 Bxf5 21. Qxf5 Qxf5 22. Bxf5 Na6 $17) (16. Bf4 Nd7 17. Bxc7 Qxc7 $11) 16... Bxf4 17. Bxf4 g5 $1 18. Bxe4 (18. Bxb8 Qxb8 19. Nf3 Qf4 $11) 18... dxe4 19. Qg3 Kh7 20. Rxe4 gxf4 21. Qxf4 (21. Qd3 $6 Kh8) 21... Bd5 (21... Rg8 22. Rae1) 22. Rae1 Rxe4 23. Rxe4 Bxe4 24. Qxf7+ Kh8 25. Qf6+ Kg8 26. Ng6 Bxg6 27. Qxg6+ Kf8 28. Qf6+ Ke8 29. Qg6+ $11) (14. Rad1 {is well met with} Bg4 $1 {After} 15. Bxe4 (15. Be2 Qc8 {[%cal Gb8d7]}) 15... dxe4 16. Ne5 Bxd1 17. Rxd1 Bxe5 18. dxe5 Qc8 19. Nxe4 Rxe5 20. Nf6+ $5 {Black must not fall into White's trap.} Kf8 (20... gxf6 $2 21. Bxh6 $18) 21. Nh7+ Kg8 22. Nf6+ $11) (14. Rac1 {Black simply completes his development and activates his pieces:} Na6 15. Ne2 Bg4 16. Ng3 Ba5 17. Re2 Re7 $11) ({After} 14. g3 {Black has a tactical solution:} Nxg3 $1 {Now both possible captures lead eventually to a draw.} 15. hxg3 (15. fxg3 Bxd3 16. Qxb7 Na6 17. Ne5 Qh3 $1 18. Nxd3 Bxg3 19. Re2 Rab8 20. Qxa6 Rxe3 21. Rxe3 Rxb2 22. Rxg3 (22. Re2 Bxh2+ 23. Kh1 Be5+ 24. Kg1 Bxd4+ 25. Nf2 Bxf2+ 26. Kxf2 Qh2+ 27. Kf3 Qh3+ $11) 22... Qxh2+ 23. Kf1 Qh1+ 24. Rg1 Qf3+ 25. Ke1 Qe3+ $13) 15... Bxd3 16. Qxb7 Na6 17. Ne5 Rxe5 18. Qxa8+ Re8 19. Qxa7 Qh3 20. Bf4 (20. Bd2 Rxe1+ 21. Rxe1 Bxg3 22. fxg3 Qxg3+ $11) 20... Rxe1+ 21. Rxe1 Bxf4 22. gxf4 Qg4+ $11) 14... Bh7 ({White gets an initiative after} 14... Be6 $6 15. f4 $1) 15. g3 (15. f3 {leads to nothing.} Ng5 16. Bxh7+ Nxh7 17. f4 b6 18. Nf3 Nf6 19. Ne5 Qc8 $11) (15. Rad1 Na6 16. a3 Re6 $11) (15. a3 Na6 16. Qc2 Re6 17. f3 (17. Re2 Rae8 18. Rae1 Bd8 19. Nf3 Bc7 $11) 17... Nf6 18. Nf5 Rae8 {Black has developed everything and solved all the problems.} 19. Bf2 (19. g4 Bf4) 19... Rxe1+ 20. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 21. Bxe1 Bd8 $11) (15. Qc2 Qd8 {[%cal Gb8d7]} 16. g3 Nd7 17. f3 Nef6 $11) 15... Bd8 $1 (15... b6 16. Rac1 $14) 16. Nf3 (16. f3 Bxh4 17. gxh4 Nxc3 18. Bxh7+ Kxh7 19. bxc3 Qh3 $11 {is at least equal for Black.}) (16. Ng2 Nf6 17. Bxh7+ Nxh7 $11) 16... Bf6 17. Rad1 (17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. Ne5 Bxe5 19. dxe5 Qe7 20. Bd4 (20. Red1 Bf5 $11) 20... Nd7 {Black has developed everything, and there is nothing to fear.} 21. Nxe4 (21. Qxb7 $6 {is too risky.} Nxe5 $15) 21... Bxe4 22. Rxe4 Nxc5 23. Bxc5 Qxc5 24. Rd1 Rad8 25. Rxd8 Rxd8 26. Qxb7 Rd2 27. Rf4 Qd5 $11) 17... Na6 18. Bxe4 dxe4 {I prefer this, although it's also possible to take with the bishop.} (18... Bxe4 19. Ne5 Bxe5 ({Black should avoid} 19... Rxe5 $6 20. dxe5 Bf3 21. Ne2 Bxe5 22. Bxh6 Qg4 23. Qe3 Re8 24. h3 Qe4 25. Qxe4 Bxe4 26. Be3 Nb4 27. Nd4 Nd3 28. Re2 $14) 20. Nxe4 Bxd4 21. Bxd4 Rxe4 22. Rxe4 dxe4 23. Bxg7 Qg4 24. h3 (24. Bxh6 $2 Nxc5) (24. Bd4 Rd8) 24... Qxg7 25. Qxb7 Rb8 26. Qxa6 e3 27. b3 exf2+ 28. Kxf2 Qf6+ 29. Kg1 Re8 $11 {Black has enough compensation for the pawn.}) 19. Ne5 Bxe5 20. dxe5 Qe7 21. e6 {White tries to saddle Black with some weaknesses, but Black's position remains stable enough.} (21. Rd6 Qxe5 22. Qxb7 Nxc5 23. Bxc5 Qxc5 24. Qxc6 (24. Rxc6 Qh5) 24... Qb4 $11 {Material is equal and Black has an active position.}) 21... fxe6 {This is probably the easiest way. White retains some compensation for the pawn, but not enough to claim an advantage.} (21... Bf5 {is more complicated.} 22. exf7+ (22. Rd7 Qxe6 23. Qxe6 Bxe6 24. Rxb7 Bc8 $132 {1/2 (56) Maghsoodloo,P (2740)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2769) Wijk aan Zee 2024}) 22... Qxf7 23. Qxf7+ Kxf7 24. a3 Rad8 25. Rxd8 Rxd8 26. g4 Bxg4 27. Nxe4 Kg8 28. Nd6 Nxc5 29. Bxc5 b6 30. Bb4 c5 31. Nb7 Rd3 32. Nxc5 bxc5 33. Bxc5 a5 $11) 22. Rd6 (22. Qc4 Rad8 23. Rxd8 Rxd8 24. Nxe4 (24. Bd4 Qd7 25. Be5 Bf5 26. Bd6 Nc7 27. Nxe4 Nb5 $11) 24... Bxe4 25. Qxe4 Qf7 $11 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gd8d5]}) 22... Qf7 23. Red1 e5 24. Qxf7+ Kxf7 25. b4 Nc7 26. a4 a6 $11 *

