{Black to move How can Black justify his material sacrifices?} 14... Bh3 $1 15.
gxh3 Qg6+ 16. Kh1 Qe4+ 17. f3 (17. Kg1 Qg6+ $11) 17... Qd3 $1 $44 {Black has
sufficient compensation for the rook. For example} (17... Qd3 18. Kg2 Qg6+ 19.
Bg5 {The only way to continue the game.} Bxg5 20. Kh1 Qd3 21. Nc3 Qd7 22. Rad1
Qc7 23. Rfe1 Be7 $1 {This is necessary since 23...Nd7 (or 23...Na6) would have
run into 24.Re8.} 24. a3 Nd7 25. Nd5 {By returning a piece, White manages to
extract his queen. The resulting position offers sufficient counterchances for
Black.} cxd5 26. Qxd5 Nb6 27. Qb5 h6 $132 {White has a rook and two pawns for
knight and bishop. With queens on the board, Black will always have
counterplay against White's weak king.}) *

